oes.com/m/30_days_of_night|title=30 Days of Night (2007)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| 28 (19 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/30-days-of-night|title=30 Days of Night Reviews|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n|  {{sort grade|C}}<ref name=\"IDWScore\" />\n|-\n| ''30 Days of Night: Dark Days''\n| 7% (6 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/30_days_of_night_dark_days|title=30 Days of Night: Dark Days|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| TBA (0 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/30-days-of-night-dark-days|title=30 Days of Night: Dark Days Reviews|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| TBA\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: left;\"| <small>'''List indicator(s)'''</small>\n* <small>A dark grey cell indicates information is not available for the film.</small>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of IDW Publishing publications]]\n\n==References==\n[[Category:Lists of films based on comics]]\n[[Category:Lists of television series based on works]]\n[[Category:IDW Publishing]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove {{Draft}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_television_series_and_films_based_on_IDW_Publishing_publications"}
{"title_page": "Siamosaurus", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Simosaurus}}{{short description|Potentially dubious genus of spinosaurid theropod dinosaur}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Barremian]]-[[Aptian]]) {{Fossilrange|129.4|113}}\n| image = Siamosaurus_tooth_by_PaleoGeek.png\n| image_caption = Illustrated [[holotype]] tooth, with [[Penny (British decimal coin)|British penny]] for scale\n| taxon = Siamosaurus\n| authority = [[Eric Buffetaut|Buffetaut]] & Ingavat, [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *'''''S. suteethorni''''' <small>Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986 ([[type species|type]])</small>\n| synonyms = *'''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'''''? <small>Hou, Yeh & Zhao, 1975</small>\n}}\n'''''Siamosaurus''''' (meaning \"Siamese lizard\") is a potentially [[Dubious name|dubious]] [[genus]] of [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived sometime between 129.4 to 113 million years ago, during the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]] of what is now [[Isan|northeastern]] [[Thailand]]. The first reported spinosaurid from Asia, it is confidently known only from tooth [[Fossil|fossils]], the first of which were found in the [[Sao Khua Formation]], with more teeth later recovered from the younger [[Khok Kruat Formation]]. The [[type species]] '''''Siamosaurus suteethorni''''', whose name honours Thai [[palaeontologist]] [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], was formally described in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]. One possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth was discovered in the Japanese [[Sebayashi Formation]] in 1994, and a tooth similar to it was found at the same site in 2015. In 2009, four teeth from China's [[Xinlong Formation]] formerly thought to belong to a [[Pliosauroidea|pliosaur]] (under the species name '''\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''''') were identified as those of a spinosaurid. \"''S''.\" ''fusuiensis'' may be the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''. Two partial spinosaurid skeletons have been found in Thailand, one in the Sao Khua and the other in the Khok Kruat Formation, but whether they belong to ''Siamosaurus'' or not is unclear.\n\nThe [[holotype]] tooth is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at its base. Since it is a tooth [[taxon]], ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s body size and weight are uncertain, though it has been estimated at between {{Convert|5.1 to 9.1|m||abbr=}} and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}. ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight, oval to circular in cross section, and lined with distinct lengthwise grooves. The tooth's [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] was wrinkled, similar to that of teeth from the related genus ''[[Baryonyx]]''. ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s identity has been questioned by many palaeontologists, who argue that its teeth are too similar to those of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles for it to be confidently classed as a dinosaur. Other researchers, who agree that the teeth are spinosaur in origin, deem them too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurs to  raise a new genus unequivocally. Based on characteristics of their teeth, ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' have been placed in the [[Spinosaurinae]] [[subfamily]].\n\nLike in all spinosaurids, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth were conical, with reduced or absent [[Serration|serrations]]. This made them suitable for impaling rather than tearing flesh, a trait typically seen in largely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) animals. In addition, its relatives are known to have consumed [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] and small to medium-sized dinosaurs, and there is fossil evidence of ''Siamosaurus'' itself eating [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] dinosaurs, either via scavenging or active hunting. ''Siamosaurus'' lived in a [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] habitat of [[Floodplain|floodplains]] and meandering rivers, where it coexisted with other theropod, sauropod, and (in at least the Khok Kruat Formation) [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]] dinosaurs. [[Isotope analysis]] of spinosaurid teeth indicates they may have had [[semiaquatic]] habits, and ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s role as a largely piscivorous predator might have reduced the prominence of contemporaneous [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]] competing for the same food source.\n\n== History of discovery ==\n[[File:Cretaceous_strata_in_northeast_and_southeastern_Thailand.png|thumb|left|Geological map of the [[Khorat Plateau]] in northeast Thailand]]\n\nThe [[Sao Khua Formation]], where the first ''Siamosaurus'' [[Fossil|fossils]] were discovered, is part of the [[Khorat Group]].<ref name=\":0\">Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref> The formation is dated to the [[Barremian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], 129.4 to 125 million years ago,<ref name=\":15\" /> though it was formerly believed to be [[Late Jurassic]] in age.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Racey|first=Andrew|last2=G. S. Goodall|first2=J|date=2009|title=Palynology and stratigraphy of the Mesozoic Khorat Group red bed sequences from Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249552008|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|volume=315|issue=1|pages=69\u201383|bibcode=2009GSLSP.315...69R|citeseerx=10.1.1.1030.8425|doi=10.1144/SP315.6|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Bertin|first=Tor|date=2010|title=A catalogue of material and review of the Spinosauridae|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235679976|journal=PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology|volume=7|pages=|via=}}</ref> Out of all [[Mesozoic]] formations in northeastern Thailand, the Sao Khua is the most abundant and diversified in [[vertebrate]] fossil discoveries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> The Khorat Group exhibits fossil [[taxa]] only of continental origin, with no definitive evidence for marine fossils or [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] structures found so far. In 1963, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi of the [[Hokkaido University]] reported ichthyosaur and [[Plesiosauria|plesiosaur]] teeth from the Sao Khua Formation, but these have now been identified as belonging to ''Siamosaurus'' and a [[Crocodilia|crocodilian]] respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/books/book/1678/late-palaeozoic-and-mesozoic-continental|title=Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Continental Ecosystems in SE Asia|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Cuny|first2=Gilles|date=2009|publisher=Geological Society of London|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=2018-06-11|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Suteethorn|first4=Varavudh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, French [[Paleontologists|palaeontologist]] [[Eric Buffetaut|\u00c9ric Buffetaut]] and his Thai colleague Rucha Ingavat described a set of fossil teeth recovered from the Phu Pratu Teema locality of the Sao Khua Formation, in [[Khon Kaen Province]]. They reached no conclusion as to what animal they originated from, their opinion being that the specimens belonged \"either to an unusual [[Theropoda|theropod]] [[dinosaur]], or to some unknown crocodilian\". In [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], a reassessment of the remains by the same authors attributed them to a new [[genus]] and [[species]] of [[spinosaurid]] theropod, which they named ''Siamosaurus suteethorni''. The generic name alludes to the ancient name of Thailand, \"''Siam''\", and is combined with the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u03c3\u03b1\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''{{lang|grc-Latn|sauros}}''), meaning \"lizard\" or \"reptile\". The specific name honours Thai [[geologist]] and palaeontologist [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], and his contributions to [[vertebrate]] palaeontology discoveries in Thailand.<ref name=\":0\" />[[File:Museum_Dinosaur_KK.jpg|thumb|The [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]] houses [[fossil]] replicas and a sculpture of ''Siamosaurus''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Boonchai|first=N|last2=Grote|first2=Paul|last3=Jintasakul|first3=P|date=2009-01-01|title=Paleontological parks and museums and prominent fossil sites in Thailand and their importance in the conservation of fossils|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286206751|journal=PaleoParks - the Protection and Conservation of Fossil Sites Worldwide|pages=75\u201395}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|date=2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref>]]The best-preserved specimen from the series, designated DMR TF 2043a, was chosen as the [[holotype]] of ''Siamosaurus.<ref name=\":0\" />'' The [[Paratype|paratypes]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Siamosaurussuteethorni|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> comprise eight other well-preserved teeth catalogued as DMR TF 2043b to i. The original fossils are currently housed in the palaeontological collection of the [[Department of Mineral Resources (Thailand)|Department of Mineral Resources]], [[Bangkok]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Other Thai fossils later referred to the taxon, including two well preserved teeth (SM2016-1-147 and SM2016-1-165) and one [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#cervicals|cervical]] (neck) [[vertebra]] (SM2016-1-067) are stored in the [[Sirindhorn Museum]], [[Kalasin Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219641|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219713|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219621|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> ''Siamosaurus'' teeth are common in the Sao Khua Formation, and further isolated specimens would later be found throughout the late 20th century and 21st century.<ref name=\":1\" />''<ref name=\":24\" />'' Sculptures of the animal have been erected in various places across northeastern Thailand, including Si Wiang Dinosaur Park,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1137381/jurassic-park-vs-the-weekend-warrior|title=Jurassic Park vs the weekend warrior|date=2016|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Siam Paragon]] shopping mall in Bangkok,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/formerly-one-of-the-biggest-smiles-in-the-land-of-smiles|title=Formerly one of the biggest smiles in the Land of Smiles|date=2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Phataranawik|first=Phatarawadee|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Dinosaurs-in-the-big-city-30273487.html|title=Dinosaurs in the big city - The Nation|date=2015|work=The Nation|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]].<ref name=\":102\">{{Cite news|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|date=2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Siamosaurus'' ''suteethorni'' was also illustrated on Thai postage stamps released in 1997, along with fellow Thai dinosaurs ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]] sirindhornae,'' ''[[Siamotyrannus]] isanensis'', and ''[[Psittacosaurus]] sattayaraki''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Scott Publishing Co|url=http://archive.org/details/scott2002standar00scot_1|title=Scott 2002 standard postage stamp catalogue. Volume 6 : countries of the world, So-Z|date=2001|publisher=Sidney, OH : Scott Pub. Co.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khok_Kruat_spinosaurid_neural_spine.png|thumb|left|upright=0.60|Illustrated [[neural spine]] of a [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] skeleton (specimen SM-KK 14) from the [[Khok Kruat Formation]]]]\n\n''Siamosaurus'' is the first reported spinosaurid dinosaur from Asia,<ref name=\":14\" /> and subsequently to its naming, material resembling or possibly belonging to the taxon has been found across the continent. In 1975, Chinese palaeontologist Hou Lian-Hai and colleagues described five teeth as a new species of the [[Pliosauroidea|pliosauroid]] ''[[Sinopliosaurus]]'', which they named ''S. fusuiensis'', the specific name referring to [[Fusui County]] in [[Guangxi]], China, from which the fossils were collected.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hou|first1= L.|last2= Yeh|first2= H.|last3=  Zhao|first3= X. |date=1975|title= Fossil reptiles from Fusui, Kwangshi |journal=Vertebrata PalAsiatica|volume=13|pages= 24\u201333|issue=1|issn=1000-3118}}</ref> Four of these teeth (one was not found in the museum collection) were reassigned by Buffetaut and colleagues in 2008 to a spinosaurid theropod, and referred to as [[\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis|\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'']]''.'' The researchers deemed it as \"closely related to, if not identical with\" ''Siamosaurus suteethorni.<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref>'' American palaeontologist Mickey Mortimer informally placed \"''S.''\" ''fusuiensis'' under the latter genus as a tentative additional species, ''Siamosaurus''? ''fusuiensis'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Sinopliosaurusfusuiensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=M.|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> which was also done by Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi in a 2016 book.''<ref name=\":20\" />'' In 2019, \"''S''.\" ''fusuiensis'' was referred to by Thai palaeontologist Wongko Kamonlak and colleagues as ''Siamosaurus sp''. (of uncertain species).''<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892|via=}}</ref>'' Later in 2019, Thai palaeontologist Adun Samathi and colleagues considered the teeth as belonging to an indeterminate spinosaurid.<ref name=\":22\" /> The specimens were retrieved from China's Early Cretaceous [[Xinlong Formation]], in which spinosaurid teeth are frequently reported, though most of them are hard to differentiate from those of Japan or Thailand without more complete fossil material, such as a skull''.''<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=Mo|first=Jinyou|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|last4=Amiot|first4=Romain|last5=Cavin|first5=Lionel|last6=Cuny|first6=Gilles|last7=Suteethorn|first7=Varavudh|last8=Suteethorn|first8=Suravech|last9=Jiang|first9=Shan|date=2015|title=Early Cretaceous vertebrates from the Xinlong Formation of Guangxi (southern China): A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279805233|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=153|issue=1|pages=143\u2013159|doi=10.1017/S0016756815000394|via=}}</ref> Buffetaut and Suteethorn suggested that the Xinlong Formation could be geologically related to the Sao Khua or Khok Kruat Formation, since similar types of fossils have been recovered in all three regions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=1999|title=The dinosaur fauna of the Sao Khua Formation of Thailand and the beginning of the Cretaceous radiation of dinosaurs in Asia|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018299000048|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=150|issue=1\u20132|pages=13\u201323|bibcode=1999PPP...150...13B|doi=10.1016/S0031-0182(99)00004-8|issn=0031-0182|via=}}</ref> Further spinosaurid teeth from unnamed and indeterminate forms have been discovered in central China<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271967379|title=A probable Baryonychine (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) tooth from the Upper Cretaceous of Henan Province, China|last=Hone|first=David|last2=Xu|first2=Xing|date=2010|journal=Vertebrata PalAsiatica|volume=48|issue=1|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-19|last3=Wang|first3=Deyou|pages=19\u201326|issn=1000-3118}}</ref> and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2014/02/140224204737.htm|title=First discovery of dinosaur fossils in Malaysia|last=|first=|date=2014|access-date=2018-10-25|publisher=ResearchSEA|language=en|via=ScienceDaily}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, an isolated tooth (specimen [[Gunma Museum of Natural History|GMNH]]-PV-999) was found by a fossil prospector in the [[Sebayashi Formation]], Japan. The tooth was believed to belong to a [[marine reptile]] until 2003, when Japanese palaeontologist Yoshikazu Hasegawa and colleagues referred it to ?''Siamosaurus sp.'' (of uncertain species).<ref name=\":4\" /> The tooth came from rocks dated to the Barremian, similar in age to [[Sediment|sediments]] that ''Siamosaurus'' teeth have been recovered from in Thailand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasegawa|first=Y|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Manabe|first3=M|last4=Takakuwa|first4=Yuji|date=2003|title=A possible spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Gunma, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/313142817|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=7|pages=1\u20135|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2015, a more incomplete tooth was recovered from the same formation by two local children. Kept under the specimen number KDC-PV-0003, the tooth was assigned to an indeterminate spinosaurid in 2017 by Japanese palaeontologist Kubota Katsuhiro and colleagues.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsuhiro|first=Kubota|last2=Takakuwa|first2=Yuji|last3=Yoshikazu|first3=Hasegawa|date=2017|title=Second discovery of a spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Kanna Town, Gunma Prefecture, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317368894|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=01|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Phu_Wiang_Spinosaurid_Skeletal_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|Skeletal diagram and estimated size of \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" compared to a human]]\n\nThailand's [[Khok Kruat Formation]] assumes a younger ([[Aptian]]; 125 to 113 million years old) age than the Sao Khua Formation,<ref name=\":12\" /> and has provided many spinosaurid teeth, including ones from ''Siamosaurus'' and closely allied forms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/svpca2005/SVPCA2005Abstracts.pdf|title=53rd Symposium of Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy|last=Ahlberg|first=P.E.|last2=Blom|first2=H.|last3=Brazeau|first3=M.D.|last4=Anderson|first4=P.|publisher=The Natural History Museum|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|volume=|pages=575\u2013581|via=}}</ref> Given the varied size and [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of the teeth found, the presence of multiple spinosaur taxa in the region is likely.''<ref name=\":24\" />''<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Kamonlak|first=Wonkgo|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252320809|title=The palaeoenvironment of the spinosaurid-bearing strata in the Khok Kruat Formation from Northeastern Thailand|last2=Lauprasert|first2=Komsorn|last3=Buffetaut|first3=Eric|last4=Suttethorn|first4=Varavudh|last5=Suteethorn|first5=Suravech|publisher=Program and Abstracts. 9th Annual Meeting of the European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists|year=2011|isbn=|location=Heraklion, Crete|pages=14\u201319}}</ref> Nearly 60 fossil teeth were recovered from the formation by joint Thai-French palaeontological fieldwork between 2003 to 2008, including specimens from the Sam Ran, Khok Pha Suam, and Lam Pao Dam localities. Eight of these teeth were described in detail by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, and classified into two main [[Morphotype|morphotypes]]: the Khok Kruat morphotype, which is found only in the Khok Kruat Formation, and the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, which includes forms widely recovered from both the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.''<ref name=\":24\" />'' \n\nIn 2004, excavation began on a partial skeleton from an outcrop of the Khok Kruat Formation near the city of [[Khon Kaen]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|title=52nd Symposium for Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy and the 13th meeting of the Symposium for Palaeontological Preparation and Conservation|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|publisher=University of Leicester & New Walk Museum|year=2004|isbn=|location=Leicester|pages=}}</ref> The specimen (SM-KK 14) consists of cervical and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] (back) vertebrae, a {{Convert|60|cm||adj=on}} high [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#neural spine|neural spine]], [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] (hip) fragments, a possible [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#metacarpal|metacarpal]] (long bone of the hand), and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#chevron|chevron]]. The cervical vertebrae and pelvic region resemble those of the European spinosaur ''[[Baryonyx]]'', and the neural spine is elongated, similarly to those of other spinosaurids.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=Adun|last2=Chanthasit|first2=Phornphen|last3=Sander|first3=Paul Martin|date=2019|title=A review of theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic to mid-Cretaceous of Southeast Asia|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396919300151|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|series=Palaeobiodiversity of Southeast Asia, issue 1|language=en|volume=105|issue=3|pages=201\u2013215|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2019.03.003|issn=0753-3969|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> A ''Siamosaurus'' tooth found nearby indicates the skeleton may belong to this genus, though this could also represent a scavenging event.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2019, a series of spinosaurid [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' were recovered from the Sao Khua Formation, and described in a dissertation by Samathi. The fossils (SM-PW9B-11 to 17, SM-PW9B, SM-PW9A-unnumbered, SM-PW9-unnumbered, and SM 2017-1-176) were designated by Samathi as \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\", and bear similarities to the possible spinosaurid ''[[Camarillasaurus]]'' and a ''Baryonyx'' specimen discovered in Portugal.<ref name=\":23\">Adun Samathi (2019) CHAPTER 6: \"A Spinosaurid from Thailand and the Reassessment of ''Camarillasaurus'' from the Early Cretaceous of Spain\" in [http://hss.ulb.uni-bonn.de/2019/5605/5605.pdf THEROPOD DINOSAURS FROM THAILAND AND SOUTHEAST ASIA PHYLOGENY, EVOLUTION, AND PALEOBIOGEOGRAPHY] Dissertation Thesis, University of Bonn pp.161-181</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nIn 2004, [[Don Lessem]] estimated ''Siamosaurus'' at {{Convert|9.1|m||abbr=}} long.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lessem|first=Don|url=http://archive.org/details/scholasticdinosa00less|title=Scholastic dinosaurs A to Z : the ultimate dinosaur encyclopedia|last2=Sovak|first2=Jan|last3=Scholastic Reference (Firm)|date=2004|publisher=New York : Scholastic|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 2005, Sussana Davidson and colleagues gave a lower estimate of {{Convert|8|m||abbr=}} in length and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/usborneinternetl00susa|title=The Usborne Internet-linked World atlas of dinosaurs|last=Davidson|first=Susanna|last2=Turnbull|first2=Stephanie|last3=Firth|first3=Rachel|last4=Rey|first4=Luis V.|last5=Slane|first5=Andrea|last6=Naish|first6=Darren|last7=Martill|first7=David M.|last8=Usborne Publishing Ltd|date=2005|publisher=New York : Scholastic Inc.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> And in 2016, Molina-P\u00e9rez and Larramendi estimated it at approximately {{convert|5.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|1.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall at the hips and weighing {{convert|255|kg|lb}}.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|last=Molina-Per\u00e9z & Larramendi|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=9780565094973|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=275}}</ref> However, reliable calculations on the weight and body size of fragmentary dinosaurs like ''Siamosaurus'' are hindered by the lack of good material, such as a skull or body fossil.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" was calculated as approximately {{convert|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} long by Samathi in 2019.<ref name=\":23\" /> \n\n=== Type specimens ===\n[[File:Asian_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Diagram comparing the [[holotype]] tooth (first from left) with other spinosaurid teeth from Asia]]\n\nFossil theropod teeth are typically identified by attributes such as the proportions, size, and curvature of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#crown|crown]], as well as the presence and/or shape of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#denticles|denticles]] (serrations).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Joshua B.|last2=Vann|first2=David R.|last3=Dodson|first3=Peter|date=2005|title=Dental morphology and variation in theropod dinosaurs: Implications for the taxonomic identification of isolated teeth|journal=The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology|language=en|volume=285A|issue=2|pages=699\u2013736|doi=10.1002/ar.a.20206|pmid=15986487|issn=1552-4884}}</ref> The holotype of ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' (specimen DMR TF 2043a) is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} in total length, with the crown being {{Convert|47.7|mm||abbr=on}} long, and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm||abbr=on}} wide at its base. It is among the larger teeth discovered by Buffetaut and Ingavat, one much smaller specimen (DMR TF 2043b) measures {{Convert|24.3|mm||abbr=on}} in length. According to the authors, this dramatic size range suggests the teeth are from individuals of different ages. The holotype tooth is relatively straight, with only minor front to back curvature. It is oval in cross section while other specimens are nearly circular in this aspect. Unlike in most theropods, the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#carinae|carinae]] (cutting edges) of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth lack well-defined serrations. Some teeth (including the holotype) have a wave-like double recurvature when viewed from the front or back, which Buffetaut and Ingavat compared to that seen in [[Carnosauria|carnosaur]] teeth from the same formation and one ''[[Deinonychus]]'' tooth described by [[John Ostrom]] in 1969. The ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype is symmetrically concave front to back, and bears 15 flutes (lengthwise grooves) on its [[Glossary of dentistry#lingual|lingual]] (inward facing) and [[Glossary of dentistry#labial|labial]] (outward facing) surfaces. These flutes run from the base of the crown before stopping {{Convert|5|mm||abbr=on}} from the rounded tooth tip. A region of the holotype where the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#enamel|enamel]] (outer layer of the teeth) has weathered away reveals that these flutes extend down to the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentin|dentin]] (second layer of the teeth).<ref name=\":0\" /> The enamel also has a granular (finely wrinkled) texture, as seen in teeth from the spinosaurid ''Baryonyx''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2007|title=The spinosaurid dinosaur Baryonyx (Saurischia, Theropoda) in the Early Cretaceous of Portugal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/spinosaurid-dinosaur-baryonyx-saurischia-theropoda-in-the-early-cretaceous-of-portugal/E2F9B7C099506CE2CD948E022FBDAD5E|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=144|issue=6|pages=1021\u20131025|doi=10.1017/S0016756807003883|bibcode=2007GeoM..144.1021B|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref> Some of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#root|root]] is preserved in the holotype and, as in all theropods, there is a large pocket for the tooth [[Pulp (tooth)|pulp]], which would have housed blood vessels and nerves.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Khok Kruat teeth ===\n[[File:Siamosaurus.jpg|thumb|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]] of ''Siamosaurus'' based on relatives]]Of the two Khok Kruat Formation tooth morphotypes assigned by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, morphotype I, the Khok Kruat morphotype, is on average {{Convert|46.35|mm||abbr=on}} in total length, of which the crown takes up {{Convert|43.77|mm||abbr=on}}, with a {{Convert|18.40 by 13.5|mm||abbr=on|adj=on}} wide base. They are oval in cross section, have well defined carinae, and a smooth enamel surface, which becomes wrinkled at the base of the crown. They bear fine, sharply defined flutes, of which there are about 21 to 32 on each side. Morphotype II, the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, is on average {{Convert|51.25|mm||abbr=on}} long, with a {{Convert|48.30|mm||abbr=on}} tall crown that is {{Convert|17.30  by 14.65|mm||abbr=on}} wide at the base. They are also oval in cross section and have distinct carinae, but unlike the Khok Kruat morphotype, the entire length of the crown has wrinkled enamel, and the flutes are coarser and fewer in number, with 11 to 16 on each side. The ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype also shares with ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'', GMNH-PV-999, and IVPP V 4793 a wrinkled enamel surface, and between 12 to 15 flutes on each side.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n=== Possible material ===\n[[File:Sebayashi_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Partial tooth of an indeterminate spinosaurid (KDC-PV-0003) and possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth (GMNH-PV-999), in the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo]]\n\nThe first Sebayashi Formation specimen (GMNH-PV-999) is an isolated tooth crown with a partially intact root. It is unknown on which jaw the tooth was positioned nor which surface faced the inside or outside of the mouth. The tooth's front and back carinae are well-defined, though the former is not well preserved. Besides having a broader, {{Convert|20 by 14|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}} wide base and being slightly smaller at {{Convert|51|mm||abbr=on}} in length, GMNH-PV-999 has a very similar morphology to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype. Features shared between the two specimens include: a straight and only slightly compressed shape; a somewhat oval cross section; no serrations on the carinae (possibly due to bad preservation); and flutes on the crown surface, the Japan specimen having 12 on each side. The specimens also share a crown surface with numerous small granular structures oriented parallel to their lengths. Because of these resemblances, Hasegawa and colleagues regarded GMNH-PV-999 as nearly identical to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype tooth.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nKDC-PV-0003, the second tooth found in the Sebayashi Formation, consists of a slightly recurved crown fragment with a preserved length of {{Convert|10|mm||abbr=on}}, the top and bottom of the tooth having broken off. At its base, the crown is {{Convert|7.4|mm||abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|6.8|mm||abbr=on}} wide, with an almost circular cross section. Though less complete than the former specimens, KDC-PV-0003 exhibits better preservation of small details such as visible serrations, although poorly defined ones. The denticles, of which there are two to three every {{Convert|1|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}}, are visible only on the front carinae, due to the rear of the tooth being obscured by rock [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. A {{Convert|5.5|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}} long gap at the fossil's base exposes the dentine, which is covered in a {{Convert|1.6|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}} thick layer of enamel. The little that is preserved of KDC-PV-0003 shows that like the first Sebayashi Formation tooth, it has a granular texture and a minimum of 12 flutes on its surface, not all of which stretch to the full length of the crown. The granular structures of KDC-PV-0003 are sharper than in GMNH-PV-999. The interdenticle sulci (tiny furrows near the gaps between each denticle) of KDC-PV-0003 have an [[Oblique angle|oblique]] orientation of 45 degrees, exactly like those seen in GMNH-PV-999.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOut of the four teeth referred to \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'', specimen [[IVPP]] V 4793 is the most intact, although still somewhat deformed. The crown, which is missing its tip, is {{Convert|69|mm||abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|16.5 by 13|mm||abbr=on}} wide at the base. The tooth is straight, only slightly recurved, and has an oval cross section. The front and rear carinae are distinct, though their serrations have been heavily eroded, similar to those of KDC-PV-0003. Like the Thailand and Japan teeth, the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' specimens bear developed flutes and a granular surface. As in both Sebayashi Formation teeth, there are 12 flutes on each face of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''{{'}}s teeth. Like in KDC-PV-0003, these flutes are of varied lengths. Buffetaut and colleagues likened the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth most to those of ''Siamosaurus'', given their identical crown shape, fluting, and granular enamel.<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />\n\n== Classification ==\n[[File:Spinosaurus_sp_Marocco_Cenom.JPG|thumb|Tooth of the related genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', Museo di Storia Naturale A. Stoppani, [[Lombardy]]]]\n\nIn 1986, Buffetaut and Ingavat classified ''Siamosaurus'' as a theropod because of the straight tall crown and double lateral recurvature of its teeth. At the time, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s particular combination of dental characteristics, especially the longitudinal fluting and lack of serrations, had not been observed in other theropods. The authors noted similarities in ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth to those of [[Ceratosauria|ceratosaurian]] tooth crowns, some of which also have longitudinal flutes. However, this identification was ruled out, since ceratosaur teeth differ in cross section, bear far fewer dental flutes, and have distinct serrations. Buffetaut and Suteethorn concluded that the closest taxon in [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentition|dentition]] to ''Siamosaurus'' was ''[[Spinosaurus]]''. Like ''Siamosaurus,'' this African genus had straight and unserrated conical teeth, and though ''Spinosaurus'' lacked the developed flutes seen in ''Siamosaurus,'' Buffetaut and Ingavat noted that both smooth and fluted spinosaur teeth have been reported from Africa. Therefore, they tentatively placed ''Siamosaurus'' in the Spinosauridae [[Family (biology)|family]], based on close similarities in dentition to ''Spinosaurus aegyptiacus.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nMany palaeontologists later questioned Buffetaut and Ingavat's identification of ''Siamosaurus'', given that spinosaurid teeth, including many from Asia, have often been mistaken for those of aquatic reptiles like crocodilians, plesiosaurs, and ichthyosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2010|title=Spinosaurs before Stromer: early finds of spinosaurid dinosaurs and their interpretations|url=http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/343/1/175|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|language=en|volume=343|issue=1|pages=175\u2013188|bibcode=2010GSLSP.343..175B|doi=10.1144/SP343.10|issn=0305-8719|via=}}</ref> In view of this, the German palaeontologist [[Hans-Dieter Sues]] and colleagues in 2002 asserted that there is not enough material to confidently identify ''Siamosaurus'' as a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sues|first=Hans-Dieter|last2=Frey|first2=Eberhard|last3=Martill|first3=David M.|last4=Scott|first4=Diane M.|date=2002|title=Irritator challengeri, a spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Brazil|url=|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|language=en|volume=22|issue=3|pages=535\u2013547|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2002)022[0535:icasdt]2.0.co;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> In 2004, American palaeontologist [[Thomas Holtz]] and colleagues considered it a [[dubious name]], stating that the teeth might instead belong to contemporaneous fish such as [[saurodontid]] or [[Ichthyodectidae|ichthyodectid]] [[Teleost|teleosts]].<ref name=\"HMC04\">Holtz Jr., T.R., Molnar, R.E., and Currie, P.J. (2004). \"Basal Tetanurae\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., and Osm\u00f3lska, H. (eds.), ''The Dinosauria'' (second edition). Berkeley: University of California Press:Berkeley, p. 71-110. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref> The same year, American palaeontologist [[David Weishampel]] and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' as an indeterminate theropod.<ref>{{Citation|last=Weishampel|first=David|title=Dinosaur Distribution|date=2004|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/234025996|volume=|pages=517\u2013606|access-date=2018-08-28|last2=Le Loeuff|first2=Jean|last3=Coria|first3=Rodolfo|last4=M. P. Gomani|first4=Elizabeth|last5=Zhao|first5=X|last6=Xu|first6=Xing|last7=Barrett|first7=Paul|last8=Sahni|first8=Ashok|last9=Noto|first9=Christopher}}</ref> And in 2012, an analysis by American palaeontologist Matthew Carrano and colleagues agreed with the possibility of confusion with other reptiles, and regarded the genus as a possible indeterminate spinosaurid. They noted that oftentimes, isolated teeth are an unstable foundation for naming new theropod taxa, and most species based on them turn out to be invalid.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Carrano|first=Matthew T.|last2=Benson|first2=Roger B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=Scott D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|url=|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|language=en|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927|issn=1477-2019}}</ref> This problem is especially common with spinosaurs, given that skull and skeletal fossils from the group are rare.<ref name=\"hone2017\" />\n\n[[File:Plesiosaur_skull.jpg|thumb|left|Spinosaurid teeth are often mistaken for those of [[plesiosaurs]] (above) and vice versa, though there are certain differences between their dentition]]\n\nAuthors such as Buffetaut and Ingavat in 1986, and Hasegawa and colleagues in 2003 have noted that since crocodilian teeth are usually more strongly recurved than spinosaur teeth, they cannot represent the same taxon.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Crocodilians also lack the lateral double recurvature of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s tooth crowns, which, based on their shape, were vertically inserted into the jaw, whereas long-snouted crocodilian teeth are usually angled outwards from the mouth. Though ''Siamosaurus'' and plesiosaur teeth are similar in overall shape, Buffetaut and Ingavat pointed out that plesiosaurs have significantly more curvature to their tooth crowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Other researchers have also noted that compared to plesiosaurs, Asian spinosaurid teeth also have coarser and more numerous flutes that extend almost the whole length of the crown.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />''<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2008, Buffetaut and colleagues stated that the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth bear carinae on the plane of the crown's curvature, a condition not observed in plesiosaur teeth. The discovery of the Khok Kruat skeleton and of baryonychine teeth with dental flutes similar to those of ''Siamosaurus'', were also brought up by the researchers as further evidence of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s spinosaurid classification.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />'' Later discoveries revealed that largely straight tooth crowns with flutes and a lack or reduction of serrations were unique characteristics of spinosaurid teeth.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966}}</ref> Due to new discoveries and research on spinosaurid teeth since ''Siamosaurus'' was named in 1986, a redescription of the genus's validity is currently being prepared by Buffetaut.<ref name=\":222\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=Adun|last2=Chanthasit|first2=Phornphen|last3=Sander|first3=Paul Martin|date=2019-07-01|title=A review of theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic to mid-Cretaceous of Southeast Asia|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396919300151|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|series=Palaeobiodiversity of Southeast Asia, issue 1|language=en|volume=105|issue=3|pages=201\u2013215|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2019.03.003|issn=0753-3969}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|Restoration of ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'', a [[Spinosaurinae|spinosaurine]] from what is now Laos]]\n\nIn 2012, French palaeontologist Ronan Allain and colleagues described a partial skeleton from the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, and used it to name the new spinosaurid genus ''[[Ichthyovenator]]''. They considered it the first definitive evidence of spinosaurids in Asia, in light of the debated identity of ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis.''<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> In a 2014 abstract, Allain announced that further ''Ichthyovenator'' material, including three teeth had been excavated. Typically of spinosaurines, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s teeth bore straight and unserrated crowns, though no comparison was made to the other Asian teeth.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2017, Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Cesar Schultz suggested that the various Asian teeth might eventually be attributed to ''Ichthyovenator''-like forms. The researchers accepted ''Siamosaurus'' as a spinosaurid, but stated that its teeth and those of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' are too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurids to unequivocally erect new taxa.<ref name=\":17\" /> Carrano and colleagues noted that the Khok Kruat skeleton may provide answers to their identification.<ref name=\":6\" /> Authors such as Milner and colleagues in 2007,<ref name=\":9\" /> Bertin Tor in 2010,<ref name=\":14\" /> [[Thomas Holtz]] in 2011,<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{cite book|last=Holtz|first=Thomas R. Jr.|title=Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages|date=2011|chapter=Winter 2010 Appendix|chapter-url=http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf}}</ref> and Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019 regarded the skeleton as first definitive evidence of spinosaurs in Asia.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\nSpinosaurids were large [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] [[Carnivore|carnivores]] with well-built forelimbs and elongated, crocodile-like skulls. The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] affinities of the group are subject to active research and debate, given that in comparison to other theropod groups, many of the family's taxa are based on poor fossil material.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Traditionally, the group is split into the [[subfamilies]] Spinosaurinae (unserrated, straight teeth with well marked flutes and more circular cross sections) and Baryonychinae (finely serrated, somewhat recurved teeth with weaker flutes and a more oval cross section). Since spinosaurines were, on average, larger animals than baryonychines, their teeth were also generally larger as well.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\" /> The morphological variation seen in spinosaurid teeth, however, has shown that the aforementioned characteristics are not always consistent within the subfamilies.<ref name=\":19\" /> The validity of Baryonychinae has also been cast into doubt by researchers such as Sales and Schultz.<ref name=\":17\" /> As it is definitively known only from teeth, ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s exact position within the Spinosauridae is difficult to determine.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409|via=}}</ref> In 2010, British palaeontologist David Hone and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' in the Spinosaurinae.<ref name=\":19\" /> Likewise, British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues resolved ''Siamosaurus'' as a [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] (early-diverging or \"primitive\") member of the subfamily in 2019, their [[cladogram]] can be seen below:<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2019|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|url=|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1='''''Siamosaurus suteethorni'''''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Ichthyovenator laosensis]]'' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\nLater in 2019, the Khok Kruat Formation teeth were also referred to the Spinosaurinae by Kamonlak and colleagues, on the basis that both the Khok Kruat and ''Siamosaurus'' morphotypes lack characteristics seen in baryonychines, such as long and slender roots, 0-10 flutes on each side, no well defined carinae, a sculptured surface of the crown base, and 45 degree orientation of the interdenticle sulci. But they share with spinosaurines a sub-circular to oval cross section, fluted tooth crowns, well defined front and rear carinae, distinct striations on the crown, varying denticle size, and a wrinkled surface of the crown base. The authors also noted that unlike spinosaurines such as ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Spinosaurus'', Asian spinosaurines usually have more laterally compressed tooth crowns, and wrinkles across more of the enamel surface.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n==Palaeobiology==\n\n=== Diet and feeding ===\nBuffetaut and Ingavat suggested in 1986 that ''Siamosaurus'' probably led a heavily [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle, as has often been suggested for spinosaurids. Spinosaurids had highly specialised teeth better suited for piercing rather than tearing flesh, due to their long, conical tooth crowns with reduced or absent serrations. This dental morphology is also seen in other piscivorous predators like plesiosaurs and long-snouted crocodilians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> Though skull material from ''Siamosaurus'' is lacking, spinosaurs are known to have had low, narrow and elongated jaws, with snout tips that fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape, similar to that of modern [[Gharials]].<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Fossil evidence has shown that besides fish, spinosaurids also consumed other dinosaurs and [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Martill|first2=David|last3=Escuilli\u00e9|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2004|title=Pterosaurs as part of a spinosaur diet|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/430033a|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=429|issue=6995|pages=33|bibcode=2004Natur.429...33B|doi=10.1038/430033a|issn=0028-0836|pmid=15229562|via=}}</ref> In the Sao Khua Formation, localities such as Wat Sakawan have yielded sauropod remains in association with tooth crowns from ''Siamosaurus'', documenting either predation or scavenging on part of the latter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Spinosaurid_and_Kinnareemimus.PNG|thumb|Restoration of a generic spinosaur feeding on a [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] carcass in the [[Sao Khua Formation]] (''[[Kinnareemimus]]'' in the background), based on teeth belonging to ''Siamosaurus''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=Marcel B.|last3=Horn|first3=Bruno L. D.|last4=Oliveira|first4=Isabel A. P. de|last5=Schultz|first5=Cesar L.|date=2016-02-01|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmid=26829315|pmc=4734717|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2006, Thai biologist Komsorn Lauprasert examined fossils collected from the Phu Kradung, Sao Khua, and Khok Kruat Formations. In this study, the teeth of ''Siamosaurus'' and a Morrocan spinosaurid were compared to those of crocodilians using [[Scanning electron microscope|scanning electron microscopy]]. Lauprasert found that spinosaurids and crocodilians may have employed similar feeding tactics and been under comparable [[Constraint (classical mechanics)|mechanical constraints]], based on resemblances in the [[microstructure]] of their tooth enamel. Lauprasert suggested that ''Siamosaurus'' could have therefore replaced the [[ecological niche]] of contemporaneous long-snouted crocodilians as a piscivorous predator. He notes that this likely occurred in correlation with the rising aridity of the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations during the Early Cretaceous, since ''Siamosaurus'' had better mobility in a dry environment than crocodilians did. This could explain the absence of long-snouted crocodilian fossils from that time and place.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite thesis|last=Lauprasert|first=Komsorn|title=Evolution and palaeoecology of crocodiles in the mesozoic of Khorat plateau, Thailand|date=2006|publisher=Chulalongkorn University|url=https://cuir.car.chula.ac.th/handle/123456789/14411|language=en}}</ref> A similar scenario was proposed for spinosaurids by Hone and colleagues in 2010, who also noted that compared to large crocodilians and obligate aquatic predators, they could more easily travel from one body of water to another in search for prey.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Aquatic habits ===\n\nA 2010 publication by French palaeontologist Romain Amiot and colleagues compared the [[isotopes of oxygen|oxygen isotope]] ratios of spinosaurid teeth from various localities, including Thailand and China, with those of turtles, crocodilians, and contemporaneous theropods. The study revealed that, among theropods, spinosaurid isotope ratios were closer to those of turtles and crocodilians. Thai spinosaurid teeth tended to have the largest difference from the ratios of other theropods, and those from Morocco tended to have the least difference. The authors concluded that spinosaurids, like modern crocodilians and hippopotamuses, were [[semiaquatic]] animals, and spent much of their daily lives in or near water. They also suggested that  piscivory and aquatic habits may explain how spinosaurids coexisted with other large theropods; by feeding on different prey items and occupying a distinct ecological role, a phenomenon known as [[niche partitioning]], the different types of theropods would have been out of direct competition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"RMetal10\">{{cite journal |last=Amiot |first=R. |author2=Buffetaut, E. |author3=L\u00e9cuyer, C. |author4=Wang, X. |author5=Boudad, L. |author6=Ding, Z. |author7=Fourel, F. |author8=Hutt, S. |author9=Martineau, F. |author10=Medeiros, A. |author11=Mo, J. |author12=Simon, L. |author13=Suteethorn, V. |author14=Sweetman, S. |author15=Tong, H. |author16=Zhang, F. |author17=Zhou, Z. |year=2010 |title=Oxygen isotope evidence for semi-aquatic habits among spinosaurid theropods |journal=Geology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013142 |doi=10.1130/G30402.1|bibcode=2010Geo....38..139A }}</ref>\n\n== Palaeoenvironment and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Sao_Khua_Formation_V2.png|thumb|left|Restoration of ''Siamosaurus'' hunting fish in the Sao Khua Formation, with a herd of ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]]'' in the background]]\n\nThe sediments of the Sao Khua Formation, composed of [[Red clay|red clays]], [[Mudstone|mudstones]], [[Sandstone|sandstones]], [[Siltstone|siltstones]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] rocks, record a [[fluvial]] environment dominated by lakes, [[Floodplain|floodplains]], and meandering low-energy rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> This is consistent with the types of vertebrate fauna present in the formation, which comprise only terrestrial or freshwater animals, including dinosaurs, turtles, freshwater [[hybodont sharks]] and [[Actinopterygii|actinopterygian]] fishes, and the freshwater crocodilian ''[[Sunosuchus]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Besides ''Siamosaurus'', there were dinosaurs like the [[Metriacanthosauridae|metriacanthosaurid]] ''Siamotyrannus isanensis'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrano|first1=M. T.|last2=Benson|first2=R. B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=S. D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927}}</ref> the [[Ornithomimosauria|ornithomimosaur]] ''[[Kinnareemimus]] khonkaenensis'',<ref name=\"description\">Buffetaut, E., Suteethorn, V. and Tong, H. (2009). \"An early 'ostrich dinosaur' (Theropoda: Ornithomimosauria) from the Early Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of NE Thailand\", pp. 229-243 IN E. Buffetaut, G. Cuny, J. Le Loeuff & V. Suteethorn (eds.), ''Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Ecosystems in SE Asia''. Geological Society, London, Special Publications 315: 229-243. {{doi|10.1144/SP315.16}}</ref> the [[Megaraptora|megaraptoran]] ''[[Phuwiangvenator]]'' ''yaemniyomi'', the basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaur]] ''[[Vayuraptor]]'' ''nongbualamphuensis,<ref name=\"Samathietal2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=A.|last2=Chanthasit|first2=P.|last3=Martin Sander|first3=P.|date=May 2019|title=Two new basal coelurosaurian theropod dinosaurs from the Lower Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of Thailand|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=239\u2013260|doi=10.4202/app.00540.2018|doi-access=free}}</ref>'' a ''[[Compsognathus]]''-like theropod, as well as sauropods like ''Phuwiangosaurus sirindhornae'' and two indeterminate forms. Sauropod remains are some of the most abundant in the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> No [[Ornithischia|ornithischian]] dinosaur fossils have been found in the Sao Khua Formation, possibly suggesting that they were uncommon compared to [[Saurischia|saurischian]] dinosaurs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations had a more [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] climate than the older, more humid [[Phu Kradung Formation]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Khok Kruat Formation is composed mostly of sandstones, conglomerates, siltstones, and [[Shale|shales]]. Similarly to the Sao Khua Formation, the deposition of these sediments occurred in an arid to semi-arid floodplain environment of slow-moving, meandering rivers.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=Jintasakul|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|last4=You|first4=Hai-Lu|date=2015|title=A New Basal Hadrosauroid Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation in Nakhon Ratchasima Province, Northeastern Thailand|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145904|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045904S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145904|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4696827|pmid=26716981}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> Vertebrates from the Khok Kruat assemblage include [[Semionotiformes|semionotiform]] fishes, hybodont sharks, turtles, dinosaurs, pterosaurs, and crocodilians. The dinosaur fauna of this ecosystem included the [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] ''[[Siamraptor]]'' ''suwati'',''<ref name=\"Chokchaloemwong2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Chokchaloemwong|first=Duangsuda|last2=Hattori|first2=Soki|last3=Cuesta|first3=Elena|last4=Jintasakul|first4=Pratueng|last5=Shibata|first5=Masateru|last6=Azuma|first6=Yoichi|date=2019|editor-last=Liu|editor-first=Jun|title=A new carcharodontosaurian theropod (Dinosauria: Saurischia) from the Lower Cretaceous of Thailand|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=14|issue=10|pages=e0222489|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0222489|issn=1932-6203|pmc=6784982|pmid=31596853}}</ref>'' [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontians]] like ''[[Sirindhorna]] khoratensis'',<ref name=\":15\" /> ''[[Ratchasimasaurus]] suranaerae'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=JINTASAKUL|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|date=2011|title=A New Iguanodontian Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation, Nakhon Ratchasima in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264655916|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=85|issue=5|pages=969\u2013976|doi=10.1111/j.1755-6724.2011.00530.x|via=}}</ref> and ''[[Siamodon]] nimngami'';<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=2011|title=A new iguanodontian dinosaur from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous, Aptian) of northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396911000425|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|language=en|volume=97|issue=1\u20132|pages=51\u201362|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2011.08.001|issn=0753-3969|via=}}</ref> as well as a ''Phuwiangosaurus''-like sauropod,<ref name=\":7\" /> an indeterminate [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsian]],<ref name=\"sereno2010\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives on Horned Dinosaurs: The Royal Tyrrell Museum Ceratopsian Symposium|last=Sereno|first=Paul C.|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2010|editor1-last=Ryan|editor1-first=Michael J.|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|pages=21\u201358|chapter=Taxonomy, cranial morphology, and relationships of parrot-beaked dinosaurs (Ceratopsia:''Psittacosaurus'')|editor2-last=Chinnery-Allgeier|editor2-first=Brenda J.|editor3-last=Eberth|editor3-first=David A.}}</ref> and various indeterminate theropods.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> The formation is probably equivalent to the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, since animals like advanced iguanodontians, sauropods, and spinosaurids have also been found there.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\nAmerican palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted in 2010 that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues suggested such a global distribution may have occurred earlier across [[Pangaea]] before the [[Late Jurassic]], even if Asia became separated from the supercontinent first.<ref name=\"AXRK122\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> In 2019, Spanish palaeontologist Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues also indicated a complex [[biogeographical]] pattern for spinosaurs during the Early Cretaceous, based on anatomical similarities between the ''Ichthyovenator'' and the European genus ''[[Vallibonavenatrix]]''.<ref name=\":32\">{{cite journal |last1=Malafaia |first1=Elisabete |last2=Gasulla |first2=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last3=Escaso |first3=Fernando |last4=Narv\u00e1ez |first4=Iv\u00e1n |last5=Sanz |first5=Jos\u00e9 Luis |last6=Ortega |first6=Francisco |title=A new spinosaurid theropod (Dinosauria: Megalosauroidea) from the upper Barremian of Vallibona, Spain: Implications for spinosaurid diversity in the Early Cretaceous of the Iberian Peninsula |journal=Cretaceous Research |date=February 2020 |volume=106 |page=104221 |doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104221}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Megalosauroidea}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q134636}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Barremian life]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1986]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by \u00c9ric Buffetaut]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Simosaurus}}{{short description|Potentially dubious genus of spinosaurid theropod dinosaur}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Barremian]]-[[Aptian]]) {{Fossilrange|129.4|113}}\n| image = Siamosaurus_tooth_by_PaleoGeek.png\n| image_caption = Illustrated [[holotype]] tooth, with [[Penny (British decimal coin)|British penny]] for scale\n| taxon = Siamosaurus\n| authority = [[Eric Buffetaut|Buffetaut]] & Ingavat, [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = *'''''S. suteethorni''''' <small>Buffetaut & Ingavat, 1986 ([[type species|type]])</small>\n| synonyms = *'''''\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis'''''? <small>Hou, Yeh & Zhao, 1975</small>\n}}\n'''''Siamosaurus''''' (meaning \"Siamese lizard\") is a potentially [[Dubious name|dubious]] [[genus]] of [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived sometime between 129.4 to 113 million years ago, during the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]] of what is now [[Isan|northeastern]] [[Thailand]]. The first reported spinosaurid from Asia, it is confidently known only from tooth [[Fossil|fossils]]; the first of which were found in the [[Sao Khua Formation]], with more teeth later recovered from the younger [[Khok Kruat Formation]]. The [[type species]] '''''Siamosaurus suteethorni''''', whose name honours Thai [[palaeontologist]] [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], was formally described in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]]. One possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth was discovered in the Japanese [[Sebayashi Formation]] in 1994, and a tooth similar to it was found at the same site in 2015. In 2009, four teeth from China's [[Xinlong Formation]] formerly thought to belong to a [[Pliosauroidea|pliosaur]] (under the species name '''\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''''') were identified as those of a spinosaurid. \"''S''.\" ''fusuiensis'' may be the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''. Two partial spinosaurid skeletons have been found in Thailand, one in the Sao Khua and the other in the Khok Kruat Formation, but whether they belong to ''Siamosaurus'' or not is unclear.\n\nThe [[holotype]] tooth is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} long and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm|}} wide at its base. Since it is a tooth taxon, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s body size and weight are uncertain, though it has been estimated at between {{Convert|5.1 to 9.1|m||abbr=}} and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}. ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight, oval to circular in cross section, and lined with distinct lengthwise grooves. The tooth's [[Tooth enamel|enamel]] was wrinkled, similar to that of teeth from the related genus ''[[Baryonyx]]''. ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s identity has been questioned by many palaeontologists, who argue that its teeth are too similar to those of contemporaneous aquatic reptiles for it to be confidently classed as a dinosaur. Other researchers, who agree that the teeth are spinosaur in origin, deem them too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurs to unequivocally raise a new genus. Based on characteristics of their teeth, ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' have been placed in the [[Spinosaurinae]] [[subfamily]].\n\nLike in all spinosaurids, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth were conical, with reduced or absent [[Serration|serrations]]. This made them suitable for impaling rather than tearing flesh, a trait typically seen in largely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) animals. Its relatives are known to have also consumed [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] and small to medium-sized dinosaurs, and there is fossil evidence of ''Siamosaurus'' itself eating [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] dinosaurs, either via scavenging or active hunting. ''Siamosaurus'' lived in a [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] habitat of [[Floodplain|floodplains]] and meandering rivers, where it coexisted with other theropod, sauropod, and (in at least the Khok Kruat Formation) [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]] dinosaurs. [[Isotope analysis]] of spinosaurid teeth indicates they may have had [[semiaquatic]] habits, and ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s role as a largely piscivorous predator might have reduced the prominence of contemporaneous [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]] competing for the same food source.\n\n== History of discovery ==\n[[File:Cretaceous_strata_in_northeast_and_southeastern_Thailand.png|thumb|left|Geological map of the [[Khorat Plateau]] in northeast Thailand]]\n\nThe [[Sao Khua Formation]], where the first ''Siamosaurus'' [[Fossil|fossils]] were discovered, is part of the [[Khorat Group]].<ref name=\":0\">Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref> The formation is dated to the [[Barremian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], 129.4 to 125 million years ago,<ref name=\":15\" /> though it was formerly believed to be [[Late Jurassic]] in age.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Racey|first=Andrew|last2=G. S. Goodall|first2=J|date=2009|title=Palynology and stratigraphy of the Mesozoic Khorat Group red bed sequences from Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249552008|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|volume=315|issue=1|pages=69\u201383|bibcode=2009GSLSP.315...69R|citeseerx=10.1.1.1030.8425|doi=10.1144/SP315.6|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Bertin|first=Tor|date=2010|title=A catalogue of material and review of the Spinosauridae|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235679976|journal=PalArch's Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology|volume=7|pages=|via=}}</ref> Out of all [[Mesozoic]] formations in northeastern Thailand, the Sao Khua is the most abundant and diversified in [[vertebrate]] fossil discoveries.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> The Khorat Group exhibits fossil [[taxa]] only of continental origin, with no definitive evidence for marine fossils or [[Sedimentary rock|sedimentary]] structures found so far. In 1963, Yoshitsugu Kobayashi of the [[Hokkaido University]] reported ichthyosaur and [[Plesiosauria|plesiosaur]] teeth from the Sao Khua Formation, but these have now been identified as belonging to ''Siamosaurus'' and a [[Crocodilia|crocodilian]] respectively.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/books/book/1678/late-palaeozoic-and-mesozoic-continental|title=Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Continental Ecosystems in SE Asia|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Cuny|first2=Gilles|date=2009|publisher=Geological Society of London|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=2018-06-11|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Suteethorn|first4=Varavudh}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, French [[Paleontologists|palaeontologist]] [[Eric Buffetaut|\u00c9ric Buffetaut]] and his Thai colleague Rucha Ingavat described a set of fossil teeth recovered from the Phu Pratu Teema locality of the Sao Khua Formation, in [[Khon Kaen Province]]. They reached no conclusion as to what animal they originated from, their opinion being that the specimens belonged \"either to an unusual [[Theropoda|theropod]] [[dinosaur]], or to some unknown crocodilian\". In [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], a reassessment of the remains by the same authors attributed them to a new [[genus]] and [[species]] of [[spinosaurid]] theropod, which they named ''Siamosaurus suteethorni''. The generic name alludes to the ancient name of Thailand, \"''Siam''\", and is combined with the [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u03c3\u03b1\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''{{lang|grc-Latn|sauros}}''), meaning \"lizard\" or \"reptile\". The specific name honours Thai [[geologist]] and palaeontologist [[Varavudh Suteethorn]], and his contributions to [[vertebrate]] palaeontology discoveries in Thailand.<ref name=\":0\" />[[File:Museum_Dinosaur_KK.jpg|thumb|The [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]] houses [[fossil]] replicas and a sculpture of ''Siamosaurus''<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Boonchai|first=N|last2=Grote|first2=Paul|last3=Jintasakul|first3=P|date=2009-01-01|title=Paleontological parks and museums and prominent fossil sites in Thailand and their importance in the conservation of fossils|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/286206751|journal=PaleoParks - the Protection and Conservation of Fossil Sites Worldwide|pages=75\u201395}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|date=2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref>]]The best-preserved specimen from the series, designated DMR TF 2043a, was chosen as the [[holotype]] of ''Siamosaurus.<ref name=\":0\" />'' The [[Paratype|paratypes]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Siamosaurussuteethorni|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> comprise eight other well-preserved teeth catalogued as DMR TF 2043b to i. The original fossils are currently housed in the palaeontological collection of the [[Department of Mineral Resources (Thailand)|Department of Mineral Resources]], [[Bangkok]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Other Thai fossils later referred to the taxon, including two well preserved teeth (SM2016-1-147 and SM2016-1-165) and one [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#cervicals|cervical]] (neck) [[vertebra]] (SM2016-1-067) are stored in the [[Sirindhorn Museum]], [[Kalasin Province]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219641|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219713|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sdm.dmr.go.th/db/datafossils_detailf.php?id=00000000000000219621|title=Database of Sirindhorn Museum Collection|website=www.sdm.dmr.go.th|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> ''Siamosaurus'' teeth are common in the Sao Khua Formation, and further isolated specimens would later be found throughout the late 20th century and 21st century.<ref name=\":1\" />''<ref name=\":24\" />'' Sculptures of the animal have been erected in various places across northeastern Thailand, including Si Wiang Dinosaur Park,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1137381/jurassic-park-vs-the-weekend-warrior|title=Jurassic Park vs the weekend warrior|date=2016|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[Siam Paragon]] shopping mall in Bangkok,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mekloy|first=Pongpet|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/formerly-one-of-the-biggest-smiles-in-the-land-of-smiles|title=Formerly one of the biggest smiles in the Land of Smiles|date=2017|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Phataranawik|first=Phatarawadee|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/life/Dinosaurs-in-the-big-city-30273487.html|title=Dinosaurs in the big city - The Nation|date=2015|work=The Nation|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Phu Wiang Dinosaur Museum]].<ref name=\":102\">{{Cite news|last=Karnjanatawe|first=Karnjana|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/travel/in-thailand/1264683/centre-of-the-northeast|title=Centre of the Northeast|date=2017|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=2018-08-23|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Siamosaurus'' ''suteethorni'' was also illustrated on Thai postage stamps released in 1997, along with fellow Thai dinosaurs ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]] sirindhornae,'' ''[[Siamotyrannus]] isanensis'', and ''[[Psittacosaurus]] sattayaraki''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Scott Publishing Co|url=http://archive.org/details/scott2002standar00scot_1|title=Scott 2002 standard postage stamp catalogue. Volume 6 : countries of the world, So-Z|date=2001|publisher=Sidney, OH : Scott Pub. Co.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Khok_Kruat_spinosaurid_neural_spine.png|thumb|left|upright=0.60|Illustrated [[neural spine]] of a [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] skeleton (specimen SM-KK 14) from the [[Khok Kruat Formation]]]]\n\n''Siamosaurus'' is the first reported spinosaurid dinosaur from Asia,<ref name=\":14\" /> and subsequently to its naming, material resembling or possibly belonging to the taxon has been found across the continent. In 1975, Chinese palaeontologist Hou Lian-Hai and colleagues described five teeth as a new species of the [[Pliosauroidea|pliosauroid]] ''[[Sinopliosaurus]]'', which they named ''S. fusuiensis'', the specific name referring to [[Fusui County]] in [[Guangxi]], China, from which the fossils were collected.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hou|first1= L.|last2= Yeh|first2= H.|last3=  Zhao|first3= X. |date=1975|title= Fossil reptiles from Fusui, Kwangshi |journal=Vertebrata PalAsiatica|volume=13|pages= 24\u201333|issue=1|issn=1000-3118}}</ref> Four of these teeth (one was not found in the museum collection) were reassigned by Buffetaut and colleagues in 2008 to a spinosaurid theropod, and referred to as [[\"Sinopliosaurus\" fusuiensis|\"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'']]''.'' The researchers deemed it as \"closely related to, if not identical with\" ''Siamosaurus suteethorni.<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref>'' American palaeontologist Mickey Mortimer informally placed \"''S.''\" ''fusuiensis'' under the latter genus as a tentative additional species, ''Siamosaurus''? ''fusuiensis'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Sinopliosaurusfusuiensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=M.|date=|website=theropoddatabase.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-06}}</ref> which was also done by Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi in a 2016 book.''<ref name=\":20\" />'' In 2019, \"''S''.\" ''fusuiensis'' was referred to by Thai palaeontologist Wongko Kamonlak and colleagues as ''Siamosaurus sp''. (of uncertain species).''<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892|via=}}</ref>'' Later in 2019, Thai palaeontologist Adun Samathi and colleagues considered the teeth as belonging to an indeterminate spinosaurid.<ref name=\":22\" /> The specimens were retrieved from China's Early Cretaceous [[Xinlong Formation]], in which spinosaurid teeth are frequently reported, though most of them are hard to differentiate from those of Japan or Thailand without more complete fossil material, such as a skull''.''<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=Mo|first=Jinyou|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|last4=Amiot|first4=Romain|last5=Cavin|first5=Lionel|last6=Cuny|first6=Gilles|last7=Suteethorn|first7=Varavudh|last8=Suteethorn|first8=Suravech|last9=Jiang|first9=Shan|date=2015|title=Early Cretaceous vertebrates from the Xinlong Formation of Guangxi (southern China): A review|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279805233|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=153|issue=1|pages=143\u2013159|doi=10.1017/S0016756815000394|via=}}</ref> Buffetaut and Suteethorn suggested that the Xinlong Formation could be geologically related to the Sao Khua or Khok Kruat Formation, since similar types of fossils have been recovered in all three regions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=1999|title=The dinosaur fauna of the Sao Khua Formation of Thailand and the beginning of the Cretaceous radiation of dinosaurs in Asia|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031018299000048|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=150|issue=1\u20132|pages=13\u201323|bibcode=1999PPP...150...13B|doi=10.1016/S0031-0182(99)00004-8|issn=0031-0182|via=}}</ref> Further spinosaurid teeth from unnamed and indeterminate forms have been discovered in central China<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/271967379|title=A probable Baryonychine (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) tooth from the Upper Cretaceous of Henan Province, China|last=Hone|first=David|last2=Xu|first2=Xing|date=2010|journal=Vertebrata PalAsiatica|volume=48|issue=1|language=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-11-19|last3=Wang|first3=Deyou|pages=19\u201326|issn=1000-3118}}</ref> and [[Malaysia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2014/02/140224204737.htm|title=First discovery of dinosaur fossils in Malaysia|last=|first=|date=2014|access-date=2018-10-25|publisher=ResearchSEA|language=en|via=ScienceDaily}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, an isolated tooth (specimen [[Gunma Museum of Natural History|GMNH]]-PV-999) was found by a fossil prospector in the [[Sebayashi Formation]], Japan. The tooth was believed to belong to a [[marine reptile]] until 2003, when Japanese palaeontologist Yoshikazu Hasegawa and colleagues referred it to ?''Siamosaurus sp.'' (of uncertain species).<ref name=\":4\" /> The tooth came from rocks dated to the Barremian, similar in age to [[Sediment|sediments]] that ''Siamosaurus'' teeth have been recovered from in Thailand.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Hasegawa|first=Y|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Manabe|first3=M|last4=Takakuwa|first4=Yuji|date=2003|title=A possible spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Gunma, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/313142817|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=7|pages=1\u20135|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> In 2015, a more incomplete tooth was recovered from the same formation by two local children. Kept under the specimen number KDC-PV-0003, the tooth was assigned to an indeterminate spinosaurid in 2017 by Japanese palaeontologist Kubota Katsuhiro and colleagues.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsuhiro|first=Kubota|last2=Takakuwa|first2=Yuji|last3=Yoshikazu|first3=Hasegawa|date=2017|title=Second discovery of a spinosaurid tooth from the Sebayashi Formation (Lower Cretaceous), Kanna Town, Gunma Prefecture, Japan|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/317368894|journal=Bulletin of the Gunma Museum of Natural History|volume=01|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Phu_Wiang_Spinosaurid_Skeletal_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|Skeletal diagram and estimated size of \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" compared to a human]]\n\nThailand's [[Khok Kruat Formation]] assumes a younger ([[Aptian]]; 125 to 113 million years old) age than the Sao Khua Formation,<ref name=\":12\" /> and has provided many spinosaurid teeth, including ones from ''Siamosaurus'' and closely allied forms.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.miketaylor.org.uk/dino/pubs/svpca2005/SVPCA2005Abstracts.pdf|title=53rd Symposium of Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy|last=Ahlberg|first=P.E.|last2=Blom|first2=H.|last3=Brazeau|first3=M.D.|last4=Anderson|first4=P.|publisher=The Natural History Museum|year=2005|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|volume=|pages=575\u2013581|via=}}</ref> Given the varied size and [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of the teeth found, the presence of multiple spinosaur taxa in the region is likely.''<ref name=\":24\" />''<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Kamonlak|first=Wonkgo|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/252320809|title=The palaeoenvironment of the spinosaurid-bearing strata in the Khok Kruat Formation from Northeastern Thailand|last2=Lauprasert|first2=Komsorn|last3=Buffetaut|first3=Eric|last4=Suttethorn|first4=Varavudh|last5=Suteethorn|first5=Suravech|publisher=Program and Abstracts. 9th Annual Meeting of the European Association of Vertebrate Palaeontologists|year=2011|isbn=|location=Heraklion, Crete|pages=14\u201319}}</ref> Nearly 60 fossil teeth were recovered from the formation by joint Thai-French palaeontological fieldwork between 2003 to 2008, including specimens from the Sam Ran, Khok Pha Suam, and Lam Pao Dam localities. Eight of these teeth were described in detail by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, and classified into two main [[Morphotype|morphotypes]]: the Khok Kruat morphotype, which is found only in the Khok Kruat Formation, and the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, which includes forms widely recovered from both the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.''<ref name=\":24\" />'' \n\nIn 2004, excavation began on a partial skeleton from an outcrop of the Khok Kruat Formation near the city of [[Khon Kaen]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|title=52nd Symposium for Vertebrate Palaeontology and Comparative Anatomy and the 13th meeting of the Symposium for Palaeontological Preparation and Conservation|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Tong|first3=Haiyan|publisher=University of Leicester & New Walk Museum|year=2004|isbn=|location=Leicester|pages=}}</ref> The specimen (SM-KK 14) consists of cervical and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] (back) vertebrae, a {{Convert|60|cm||adj=on}} high [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#neural spine|neural spine]], [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] (hip) fragments, a possible [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#metacarpal|metacarpal]] (long bone of the hand), and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#chevron|chevron]]. The cervical vertebrae and pelvic region resemble those of the European spinosaur ''[[Baryonyx]]'', and the neural spine is elongated, similarly to those of other spinosaurids.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=Adun|last2=Chanthasit|first2=Phornphen|last3=Sander|first3=Paul Martin|date=2019|title=A review of theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic to mid-Cretaceous of Southeast Asia|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396919300151|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|series=Palaeobiodiversity of Southeast Asia, issue 1|language=en|volume=105|issue=3|pages=201\u2013215|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2019.03.003|issn=0753-3969|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> A ''Siamosaurus'' tooth found nearby indicates the skeleton may belong to this genus, though this could also represent a scavenging event.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2019, a series of spinosaurid [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' were recovered from the Sao Khua Formation, and described in a dissertation by Samathi. The fossils (SM-PW9B-11 to 17, SM-PW9B, SM-PW9A-unnumbered, SM-PW9-unnumbered, and SM 2017-1-176) were designated by Samathi as \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\", and bear similarities to the possible spinosaurid ''[[Camarillasaurus]]'' and a ''Baryonyx'' specimen discovered in Portugal.<ref name=\":23\">Adun Samathi (2019) CHAPTER 6: \"A Spinosaurid from Thailand and the Reassessment of ''Camarillasaurus'' from the Early Cretaceous of Spain\" in [http://hss.ulb.uni-bonn.de/2019/5605/5605.pdf THEROPOD DINOSAURS FROM THAILAND AND SOUTHEAST ASIA PHYLOGENY, EVOLUTION, AND PALEOBIOGEOGRAPHY] Dissertation Thesis, University of Bonn pp.161-181</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nIn 2004, [[Don Lessem]] estimated ''Siamosaurus'' at {{Convert|9.1|m||abbr=}} long.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lessem|first=Don|url=http://archive.org/details/scholasticdinosa00less|title=Scholastic dinosaurs A to Z : the ultimate dinosaur encyclopedia|last2=Sovak|first2=Jan|last3=Scholastic Reference (Firm)|date=2004|publisher=New York : Scholastic|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 2005, Sussana Davidson and colleagues gave a lower estimate of {{Convert|8|m||abbr=}} in length and weighing {{Convert|1|tonne|short ton}}.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/usborneinternetl00susa|title=The Usborne Internet-linked World atlas of dinosaurs|last=Davidson|first=Susanna|last2=Turnbull|first2=Stephanie|last3=Firth|first3=Rachel|last4=Rey|first4=Luis V.|last5=Slane|first5=Andrea|last6=Naish|first6=Darren|last7=Martill|first7=David M.|last8=Usborne Publishing Ltd|date=2005|publisher=New York : Scholastic Inc.|others=Internet Archive}}</ref> And in 2016, Molina-P\u00e9rez and Larramendi estimated it at approximately {{convert|5.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|1.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall at the hips and weighing {{convert|255|kg|lb}}.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|last=Molina-Per\u00e9z & Larramendi|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=9780565094973|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=275}}</ref> However, reliable calculations on the weight and body size of fragmentary dinosaurs like ''Siamosaurus'' are hindered by the lack of good material, such as a skull or body fossil.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> \"Phuwiang spinosaurid B\" was calculated as approximately {{convert|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} long by Samathi in 2019.<ref name=\":23\" /> \n\n=== Type specimens ===\n[[File:Asian_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Diagram comparing the [[holotype]] tooth (first from left) with other spinosaurid teeth from Asia]]\n\nFossil theropod teeth are typically identified by attributes such as the proportions, size, and curvature of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#crown|crown]], as well as the presence and/or shape of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#denticles|denticles]] (serrations).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Joshua B.|last2=Vann|first2=David R.|last3=Dodson|first3=Peter|date=2005|title=Dental morphology and variation in theropod dinosaurs: Implications for the taxonomic identification of isolated teeth|journal=The Anatomical Record Part A: Discoveries in Molecular, Cellular, and Evolutionary Biology|language=en|volume=285A|issue=2|pages=699\u2013736|doi=10.1002/ar.a.20206|pmid=15986487|issn=1552-4884}}</ref> The holotype of ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' (specimen DMR TF 2043a) is {{Convert|62.5|mm|}} in total length, with the crown being {{Convert|47.7|mm||abbr=on}} long, and {{Convert|16.6 by 12.5|mm||abbr=on}} wide at its base. It is among the larger teeth discovered by Buffetaut and Ingavat, one much smaller specimen (DMR TF 2043b) measures {{Convert|24.3|mm||abbr=on}} in length. According to the authors, this dramatic size range suggests the teeth are from individuals of different ages. The holotype tooth is relatively straight, with only minor front to back curvature. It is oval in cross section while other specimens are nearly circular in this aspect. Unlike in most theropods, the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#carinae|carinae]] (cutting edges) of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth lack well-defined serrations. Some teeth (including the holotype) have a wave-like double recurvature when viewed from the front or back, which Buffetaut and Ingavat compared to that seen in [[Carnosauria|carnosaur]] teeth from the same formation and one ''[[Deinonychus]]'' tooth described by [[John Ostrom]] in 1969. The ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype is symmetrically concave front to back, and bears 15 flutes (lengthwise grooves) on its [[Glossary of dentistry#lingual|lingual]] (inward facing) and [[Glossary of dentistry#labial|labial]] (outward facing) surfaces. These flutes run from the base of the crown before stopping {{Convert|5|mm||abbr=on}} from the rounded tooth tip. A region of the holotype where the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#enamel|enamel]] (outer layer of the teeth) has weathered away reveals that these flutes extend down to the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentin|dentin]] (second layer of the teeth).<ref name=\":0\" /> The enamel also has a granular (finely wrinkled) texture, as seen in teeth from the spinosaurid ''Baryonyx''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2007|title=The spinosaurid dinosaur Baryonyx (Saurischia, Theropoda) in the Early Cretaceous of Portugal|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/spinosaurid-dinosaur-baryonyx-saurischia-theropoda-in-the-early-cretaceous-of-portugal/E2F9B7C099506CE2CD948E022FBDAD5E|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=144|issue=6|pages=1021\u20131025|doi=10.1017/S0016756807003883|bibcode=2007GeoM..144.1021B|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref> Some of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#root|root]] is preserved in the holotype and, as in all theropods, there is a large pocket for the tooth [[Pulp (tooth)|pulp]], which would have housed blood vessels and nerves.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Khok Kruat teeth ===\n[[File:Siamosaurus.jpg|thumb|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]] of ''Siamosaurus'' based on relatives]]Of the two Khok Kruat Formation tooth morphotypes assigned by Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019, morphotype I, the Khok Kruat morphotype, is on average {{Convert|46.35|mm||abbr=on}} in total length, of which the crown takes up {{Convert|43.77|mm||abbr=on}}, with a {{Convert|18.40 by 13.5|mm||abbr=on|adj=on}} wide base. They are oval in cross section, have well defined carinae, and a smooth enamel surface, which becomes wrinkled at the base of the crown. They bear fine, sharply defined flutes, of which there are about 21 to 32 on each side. Morphotype II, the ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype, is on average {{Convert|51.25|mm||abbr=on}} long, with a {{Convert|48.30|mm||abbr=on}} tall crown that is {{Convert|17.30  by 14.65|mm||abbr=on}} wide at the base. They are also oval in cross section and have distinct carinae, but unlike the Khok Kruat morphotype, the entire length of the crown has wrinkled enamel, and the flutes are coarser and fewer in number, with 11 to 16 on each side. The ''Siamosaurus'' morphotype also shares with ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'', GMNH-PV-999, and IVPP V 4793 a wrinkled enamel surface, and between 12 to 15 flutes on each side.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n=== Possible material ===\n[[File:Sebayashi_spinosaurid_teeth.png|thumb|left|Partial tooth of an indeterminate spinosaurid (KDC-PV-0003) and possible ''Siamosaurus'' tooth (GMNH-PV-999), in the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo]]\n\nThe first Sebayashi Formation specimen (GMNH-PV-999) is an isolated tooth crown with a partially intact root. It is unknown on which jaw the tooth was positioned nor which surface faced the inside or outside of the mouth. The tooth's front and back carinae are well-defined, though the former is not well preserved. Besides having a broader, {{Convert|20 by 14|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}} wide base and being slightly smaller at {{Convert|51|mm||abbr=on}} in length, GMNH-PV-999 has a very similar morphology to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype. Features shared between the two specimens include: a straight and only slightly compressed shape; a somewhat oval cross section; no serrations on the carinae (possibly due to bad preservation); and flutes on the crown surface, the Japan specimen having 12 on each side. The specimens also share a crown surface with numerous small granular structures oriented parallel to their lengths. Because of these resemblances, Hasegawa and colleagues regarded GMNH-PV-999 as nearly identical to the ''Siamosaurus suteethorni'' holotype tooth.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nKDC-PV-0003, the second tooth found in the Sebayashi Formation, consists of a slightly recurved crown fragment with a preserved length of {{Convert|10|mm||abbr=on}}, the top and bottom of the tooth having broken off. At its base, the crown is {{Convert|7.4|mm||abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|6.8|mm||abbr=on}} wide, with an almost circular cross section. Though less complete than the former specimens, KDC-PV-0003 exhibits better preservation of small details such as visible serrations, although poorly defined ones. The denticles, of which there are two to three every {{Convert|1|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}}, are visible only on the front carinae, due to the rear of the tooth being obscured by rock [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. A {{Convert|5.5|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}} long gap at the fossil's base exposes the dentine, which is covered in a {{Convert|1.6|mm||adj=on|abbr=on}} thick layer of enamel. The little that is preserved of KDC-PV-0003 shows that like the first Sebayashi Formation tooth, it has a granular texture and a minimum of 12 flutes on its surface, not all of which stretch to the full length of the crown. The granular structures of KDC-PV-0003 are sharper than in GMNH-PV-999. The interdenticle sulci (tiny furrows near the gaps between each denticle) of KDC-PV-0003 have an [[Oblique angle|oblique]] orientation of 45 degrees, exactly like those seen in GMNH-PV-999.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOut of the four teeth referred to \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'', specimen [[IVPP]] V 4793 is the most intact, although still somewhat deformed. The crown, which is missing its tip, is {{Convert|69|mm||abbr=on}} long and {{Convert|16.5 by 13|mm||abbr=on}} wide at the base. The tooth is straight, only slightly recurved, and has an oval cross section. The front and rear carinae are distinct, though their serrations have been heavily eroded, similar to those of KDC-PV-0003. Like the Thailand and Japan teeth, the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' specimens bear developed flutes and a granular surface. As in both Sebayashi Formation teeth, there are 12 flutes on each face of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis''{{'}}s teeth. Like in KDC-PV-0003, these flutes are of varied lengths. Buffetaut and colleagues likened the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth most to those of ''Siamosaurus'', given their identical crown shape, fluting, and granular enamel.<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />\n\n== Classification ==\n[[File:Spinosaurus_sp_Marocco_Cenom.JPG|thumb|Tooth of the related genus ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', Museo di Storia Naturale A. Stoppani, [[Lombardy]]]]\n\nIn 1986, Buffetaut and Ingavat classified ''Siamosaurus'' as a theropod because of the straight tall crown and double lateral recurvature of its teeth. At the time, ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s particular combination of dental characteristics, especially the longitudinal fluting and lack of serrations, had not been observed in other theropods. The authors noted similarities in ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s teeth to those of [[Ceratosauria|ceratosaurian]] tooth crowns, some of which also have longitudinal flutes. However, this identification was ruled out, since ceratosaur teeth differ in cross section, bear far fewer dental flutes, and have distinct serrations. Buffetaut and Suteethorn concluded that the closest taxon in [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentition|dentition]] to ''Siamosaurus'' was ''[[Spinosaurus]]''. Like ''Siamosaurus,'' this African genus had straight and unserrated conical teeth, and though ''Spinosaurus'' lacked the developed flutes seen in ''Siamosaurus,'' Buffetaut and Ingavat noted that both smooth and fluted spinosaur teeth have been reported from Africa. Therefore, they tentatively placed ''Siamosaurus'' in the Spinosauridae [[Family (biology)|family]], based on close similarities in dentition to ''Spinosaurus aegyptiacus.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nMany palaeontologists later questioned Buffetaut and Ingavat's identification of ''Siamosaurus'', given that spinosaurid teeth, including many from Asia, have often been mistaken for those of aquatic reptiles like crocodilians, plesiosaurs, and ichthyosaurs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|date=2010|title=Spinosaurs before Stromer: early finds of spinosaurid dinosaurs and their interpretations|url=http://sp.lyellcollection.org/content/343/1/175|journal=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|language=en|volume=343|issue=1|pages=175\u2013188|bibcode=2010GSLSP.343..175B|doi=10.1144/SP343.10|issn=0305-8719|via=}}</ref> In view of this, the German palaeontologist [[Hans-Dieter Sues]] and colleagues in 2002 asserted that there is not enough material to confidently identify ''Siamosaurus'' as a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sues|first=Hans-Dieter|last2=Frey|first2=Eberhard|last3=Martill|first3=David M.|last4=Scott|first4=Diane M.|date=2002|title=Irritator challengeri, a spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Brazil|url=|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|language=en|volume=22|issue=3|pages=535\u2013547|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2002)022[0535:icasdt]2.0.co;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> In 2004, American palaeontologist [[Thomas Holtz]] and colleagues considered it a [[dubious name]], stating that the teeth might instead belong to contemporaneous fish such as [[saurodontid]] or [[Ichthyodectidae|ichthyodectid]] [[Teleost|teleosts]].<ref name=\"HMC04\">Holtz Jr., T.R., Molnar, R.E., and Currie, P.J. (2004). \"Basal Tetanurae\". In: Weishampel, D.B., Dodson, P., and Osm\u00f3lska, H. (eds.), ''The Dinosauria'' (second edition). Berkeley: University of California Press:Berkeley, p. 71-110. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}</ref> The same year, American palaeontologist [[David Weishampel]] and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' as an indeterminate theropod.<ref>{{Citation|last=Weishampel|first=David|title=Dinosaur Distribution|date=2004|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/234025996|volume=|pages=517\u2013606|access-date=2018-08-28|last2=Le Loeuff|first2=Jean|last3=Coria|first3=Rodolfo|last4=M. P. Gomani|first4=Elizabeth|last5=Zhao|first5=X|last6=Xu|first6=Xing|last7=Barrett|first7=Paul|last8=Sahni|first8=Ashok|last9=Noto|first9=Christopher}}</ref> And in 2012, an analysis by American palaeontologist Matthew Carrano and colleagues agreed with the possibility of confusion with other reptiles, and regarded the genus as a possible indeterminate spinosaurid. They noted that oftentimes, isolated teeth are an unstable foundation for naming new theropod taxa, and most species based on them turn out to be invalid.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Carrano|first=Matthew T.|last2=Benson|first2=Roger B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=Scott D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|url=|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|language=en|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927|issn=1477-2019}}</ref> This problem is especially common with spinosaurs, given that skull and skeletal fossils from the group are rare.<ref name=\"hone2017\" />\n\n[[File:Plesiosaur_skull.jpg|thumb|left|Spinosaurid teeth are often mistaken for those of [[plesiosaurs]] (above) and vice versa, though there are certain differences between their dentition]]\n\nAuthors such as Buffetaut and Ingavat in 1986, and Hasegawa and colleagues in 2003 have noted that since crocodilian teeth are usually more strongly recurved than spinosaur teeth, they cannot represent the same taxon.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> Crocodilians also lack the lateral double recurvature of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s tooth crowns, which, based on their shape, were vertically inserted into the jaw, whereas long-snouted crocodilian teeth are usually angled outwards from the mouth. Though ''Siamosaurus'' and plesiosaur teeth are similar in overall shape, Buffetaut and Ingavat pointed out that plesiosaurs have significantly more curvature to their tooth crowns.<ref name=\":0\" /> Other researchers have also noted that compared to plesiosaurs, Asian spinosaurid teeth also have coarser and more numerous flutes that extend almost the whole length of the crown.<ref name=\":0\" />''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />''<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2008, Buffetaut and colleagues stated that the \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' teeth bear carinae on the plane of the crown's curvature, a condition not observed in plesiosaur teeth. The discovery of the Khok Kruat skeleton and of baryonychine teeth with dental flutes similar to those of ''Siamosaurus'', were also brought up by the researchers as further evidence of ''Siamosaurus''{{'}}s spinosaurid classification.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\" />'' Later discoveries revealed that largely straight tooth crowns with flutes and a lack or reduction of serrations were unique characteristics of spinosaurid teeth.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966}}</ref> Due to new discoveries and research on spinosaurid teeth since ''Siamosaurus'' was named in 1986, a redescription of the genus's validity is currently being prepared by Buffetaut.<ref name=\":222\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=Adun|last2=Chanthasit|first2=Phornphen|last3=Sander|first3=Paul Martin|date=2019-07-01|title=A review of theropod dinosaurs from the Late Jurassic to mid-Cretaceous of Southeast Asia|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396919300151|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|series=Palaeobiodiversity of Southeast Asia, issue 1|language=en|volume=105|issue=3|pages=201\u2013215|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2019.03.003|issn=0753-3969}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|Restoration of ''[[Ichthyovenator]]'', a [[Spinosaurinae|spinosaurine]] from what is now Laos]]\n\nIn 2012, French palaeontologist Ronan Allain and colleagues described a partial skeleton from the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, and used it to name the new spinosaurid genus ''[[Ichthyovenator]]''. They considered it the first definitive evidence of spinosaurids in Asia, in light of the debated identity of ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis.''<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> In a 2014 abstract, Allain announced that further ''Ichthyovenator'' material, including three teeth had been excavated. Typically of spinosaurines, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s teeth bore straight and unserrated crowns, though no comparison was made to the other Asian teeth.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> In 2017, Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Cesar Schultz suggested that the various Asian teeth might eventually be attributed to ''Ichthyovenator''-like forms. The researchers accepted ''Siamosaurus'' as a spinosaurid, but stated that its teeth and those of \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' are too similar to those of other Early Cretaceous spinosaurids to unequivocally erect new taxa.<ref name=\":17\" /> Carrano and colleagues noted that the Khok Kruat skeleton may provide answers to their identification.<ref name=\":6\" /> Authors such as Milner and colleagues in 2007,<ref name=\":9\" /> Bertin Tor in 2010,<ref name=\":14\" /> [[Thomas Holtz]] in 2011,<ref name=\"Holtz2008\">{{cite book|last=Holtz|first=Thomas R. Jr.|title=Dinosaurs: The Most Complete, Up-to-Date Encyclopedia for Dinosaur Lovers of All Ages|date=2011|chapter=Winter 2010 Appendix|chapter-url=http://www.geol.umd.edu/~tholtz/dinoappendix/HoltzappendixWinter2010.pdf}}</ref> and Kamonlak and colleagues in 2019 regarded the skeleton as first definitive evidence of spinosaurs in Asia.<ref name=\":8\" /> \n\nSpinosaurids were large [[Bipedalism|bipedal]] [[Carnivore|carnivores]] with well-built forelimbs and elongated, crocodile-like skulls. The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic]] and [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] affinities of the group are subject to active research and debate, given that in comparison to other theropod groups, many of the family's taxa are based on poor fossil material.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Traditionally, the group is split into the [[subfamilies]] Spinosaurinae (unserrated, straight teeth with well marked flutes and more circular cross sections) and Baryonychinae (finely serrated, somewhat recurved teeth with weaker flutes and a more oval cross section). Since spinosaurines were, on average, larger animals than baryonychines, their teeth were also generally larger as well.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\" /> The morphological variation seen in spinosaurid teeth, however, has shown that the aforementioned characteristics are not always consistent within the subfamilies.<ref name=\":19\" /> The validity of Baryonychinae has also been cast into doubt by researchers such as Sales and Schultz.<ref name=\":17\" /> As it is definitively known only from teeth, ''Siamosaurus''<nowiki/>'s exact position within the Spinosauridae is difficult to determine.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Ouaja|first2=Mohamed|date=2002|title=A new specimen of Spinosaurus (Dinosauria, Theropoda) from the Lower Cretaceous of Tunisia, with remarks on the evolutionary history of the Spinosauridae|url=https://pubs.geoscienceworld.org/sgf/bsgf/article-abstract/173/5/415/88325/a-new-specimen-of-spinosaurus-dinosauria-theropoda|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9ologique de France|language=en|volume=173|issue=5|pages=415\u2013421|doi=10.2113/173.5.415|issn=0037-9409|via=}}</ref> In 2010, British palaeontologist David Hone and colleagues placed ''Siamosaurus'' and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' in the Spinosaurinae.<ref name=\":19\" /> Likewise, British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues resolved ''Siamosaurus'' as a [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] (early-diverging or \"primitive\") member of the subfamily in 2019, their [[cladogram]] can be seen below:<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2019|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|url=|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1='''''Siamosaurus suteethorni'''''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1=''[[Ichthyovenator laosensis]]'' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\nLater in 2019, the Khok Kruat Formation teeth were also referred to the Spinosaurinae by Kamonlak and colleagues, on the basis that both the Khok Kruat and ''Siamosaurus'' morphotypes lack characteristics seen in baryonychines, such as long and slender roots, 0-10 flutes on each side, no well defined carinae, a sculptured surface of the crown base, and 45 degree orientation of the interdenticle sulci. But they share with spinosaurines a sub-circular to oval cross section, fluted tooth crowns, well defined front and rear carinae, distinct striations on the crown, varying denticle size, and a wrinkled surface of the crown base. The authors also noted that unlike spinosaurines such as ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Spinosaurus'', Asian spinosaurines usually have more laterally compressed tooth crowns, and wrinkles across more of the enamel surface.''<ref name=\":24\" />''\n\n==Palaeobiology==\n\n=== Diet and feeding ===\nBuffetaut and Ingavat suggested in 1986 that ''Siamosaurus'' probably led a heavily [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle, as has often been suggested for spinosaurids. Spinosaurids had highly specialised teeth better suited for piercing rather than tearing flesh, due to their long, conical tooth crowns with reduced or absent serrations. This dental morphology is also seen in other piscivorous predators like plesiosaurs and long-snouted crocodilians.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> Though skull material from ''Siamosaurus'' is lacking, spinosaurs are known to have had low, narrow and elongated jaws, with snout tips that fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape, similar to that of modern [[Gharials]].<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Fossil evidence has shown that besides fish, spinosaurids also consumed other dinosaurs and [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Martill|first2=David|last3=Escuilli\u00e9|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|date=2004|title=Pterosaurs as part of a spinosaur diet|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/430033a|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=429|issue=6995|pages=33|bibcode=2004Natur.429...33B|doi=10.1038/430033a|issn=0028-0836|pmid=15229562|via=}}</ref> In the Sao Khua Formation, localities such as Wat Sakawan have yielded sauropod remains in association with tooth crowns from ''Siamosaurus'', documenting either predation or scavenging on part of the latter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[File:Spinosaurid_and_Kinnareemimus.PNG|thumb|Restoration of a generic spinosaur feeding on a [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] carcass in the [[Sao Khua Formation]] (''[[Kinnareemimus]]'' in the background), based on teeth belonging to ''Siamosaurus''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=Marcel B.|last3=Horn|first3=Bruno L. D.|last4=Oliveira|first4=Isabel A. P. de|last5=Schultz|first5=Cesar L.|date=2016-02-01|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmid=26829315|pmc=4734717|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 2006, Thai biologist Komsorn Lauprasert examined fossils collected from the Phu Kradung, Sao Khua, and Khok Kruat Formations. In this study, the teeth of ''Siamosaurus'' and a Morrocan spinosaurid were compared to those of crocodilians using [[Scanning electron microscope|scanning electron microscopy]]. Lauprasert found that spinosaurids and crocodilians may have employed similar feeding tactics and been under comparable [[Constraint (classical mechanics)|mechanical constraints]], based on resemblances in the [[microstructure]] of their tooth enamel. Lauprasert suggested that ''Siamosaurus'' could have therefore replaced the [[ecological niche]] of contemporaneous long-snouted crocodilians as a piscivorous predator. He notes that this likely occurred in correlation with the rising aridity of the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations during the Early Cretaceous, since ''Siamosaurus'' had better mobility in a dry environment than crocodilians did. This could explain the absence of long-snouted crocodilian fossils from that time and place.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite thesis|last=Lauprasert|first=Komsorn|title=Evolution and palaeoecology of crocodiles in the mesozoic of Khorat plateau, Thailand|date=2006|publisher=Chulalongkorn University|url=https://cuir.car.chula.ac.th/handle/123456789/14411|language=en}}</ref> A similar scenario was proposed for spinosaurids by Hone and colleagues in 2010, who also noted that compared to large crocodilians and obligate aquatic predators, they could more easily travel from one body of water to another in search for prey.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n=== Aquatic habits ===\n\nA 2010 publication by French palaeontologist Romain Amiot and colleagues compared the [[isotopes of oxygen|oxygen isotope]] ratios of spinosaurid teeth from various localities, including Thailand and China, with those of turtles, crocodilians, and contemporaneous theropods. The study revealed that, among theropods, spinosaurid isotope ratios were closer to those of turtles and crocodilians. Thai spinosaurid teeth tended to have the largest difference from the ratios of other theropods, and those from Morocco tended to have the least difference. The authors concluded that spinosaurids, like modern crocodilians and hippopotamuses, were [[semiaquatic]] animals, and spent much of their daily lives in or near water. They also suggested that  piscivory and aquatic habits may explain how spinosaurids coexisted with other large theropods; by feeding on different prey items and occupying a distinct ecological role, a phenomenon known as [[niche partitioning]], the different types of theropods would have been out of direct competition.<ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"RMetal10\">{{cite journal |last=Amiot |first=R. |author2=Buffetaut, E. |author3=L\u00e9cuyer, C. |author4=Wang, X. |author5=Boudad, L. |author6=Ding, Z. |author7=Fourel, F. |author8=Hutt, S. |author9=Martineau, F. |author10=Medeiros, A. |author11=Mo, J. |author12=Simon, L. |author13=Suteethorn, V. |author14=Sweetman, S. |author15=Tong, H. |author16=Zhang, F. |author17=Zhou, Z. |year=2010 |title=Oxygen isotope evidence for semi-aquatic habits among spinosaurid theropods |journal=Geology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=139\u2013142 |doi=10.1130/G30402.1|bibcode=2010Geo....38..139A }}</ref>\n\n== Palaeoenvironment and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Sao_Khua_Formation_V2.png|thumb|left|Restoration of ''Siamosaurus'' hunting fish in the Sao Khua Formation, with a herd of ''[[Phuwiangosaurus]]'' in the background]]\n\nThe sediments of the Sao Khua Formation, composed of [[Red clay|red clays]], [[Mudstone|mudstones]], [[Sandstone|sandstones]], [[Siltstone|siltstones]] and [[Conglomerate (geology)|conglomerate]] rocks, record a [[fluvial]] environment dominated by lakes, [[Floodplain|floodplains]], and meandering low-energy rivers.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Eric|first=Buffetaut|last2=Varavudh|first2=Suteethorn|date=1998|title=The biogeographical significance of the Mesozoic vertebrates from Thailand|url=http://doc.rero.ch/record/15441|journal=Biogeography and Geological Evolution of SE Asia|language=en}}</ref> This is consistent with the types of vertebrate fauna present in the formation, which comprise only terrestrial or freshwater animals, including dinosaurs, turtles, freshwater [[hybodont sharks]] and [[Actinopterygii|actinopterygian]] fishes, and the freshwater crocodilian ''[[Sunosuchus]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> Besides ''Siamosaurus'', there were dinosaurs like the [[Metriacanthosauridae|metriacanthosaurid]] ''Siamotyrannus isanensis'',<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrano|first1=M. T.|last2=Benson|first2=R. B. J.|last3=Sampson|first3=S. D.|date=2012|title=The phylogeny of Tetanurae (Dinosauria: Theropoda)|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=10|issue=2|pages=211\u2013300|doi=10.1080/14772019.2011.630927}}</ref> the [[Ornithomimosauria|ornithomimosaur]] ''[[Kinnareemimus]] khonkaenensis'',<ref name=\"description\">Buffetaut, E., Suteethorn, V. and Tong, H. (2009). \"An early 'ostrich dinosaur' (Theropoda: Ornithomimosauria) from the Early Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of NE Thailand\", pp. 229-243 IN E. Buffetaut, G. Cuny, J. Le Loeuff & V. Suteethorn (eds.), ''Late Palaeozoic and Mesozoic Ecosystems in SE Asia''. Geological Society, London, Special Publications 315: 229-243. {{doi|10.1144/SP315.16}}</ref> the [[Megaraptora|megaraptoran]] ''[[Phuwiangvenator]]'' ''yaemniyomi'', the basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaur]] ''[[Vayuraptor]]'' ''nongbualamphuensis,<ref name=\"Samathietal2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Samathi|first=A.|last2=Chanthasit|first2=P.|last3=Martin Sander|first3=P.|date=May 2019|title=Two new basal coelurosaurian theropod dinosaurs from the Lower Cretaceous Sao Khua Formation of Thailand|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|language=en|volume=64|issue=2|pages=239\u2013260|doi=10.4202/app.00540.2018|doi-access=free}}</ref>'' a ''[[Compsognathus]]''-like theropod, as well as sauropods like ''Phuwiangosaurus sirindhornae'' and two indeterminate forms. Sauropod remains are some of the most abundant in the Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> No [[Ornithischia|ornithischian]] dinosaur fossils have been found in the Sao Khua Formation, possibly suggesting that they were uncommon compared to [[Saurischia|saurischian]] dinosaurs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Sao Khua and Khok Kruat Formations had a more [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]] climate than the older, more humid [[Phu Kradung Formation]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Khok Kruat Formation is composed mostly of sandstones, conglomerates, siltstones, and [[Shale|shales]]. Similarly to the Sao Khua Formation, the deposition of these sediments occurred in an arid to semi-arid floodplain environment of slow-moving, meandering rivers.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=Jintasakul|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|last4=You|first4=Hai-Lu|date=2015|title=A New Basal Hadrosauroid Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation in Nakhon Ratchasima Province, Northeastern Thailand|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=10|issue=12|pages=e0145904|bibcode=2015PLoSO..1045904S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0145904|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4696827|pmid=26716981}}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /> Vertebrates from the Khok Kruat assemblage include [[Semionotiformes|semionotiform]] fishes, hybodont sharks, turtles, dinosaurs, pterosaurs, and crocodilians. The dinosaur fauna of this ecosystem included the [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] ''[[Siamraptor]]'' ''suwati'',''<ref name=\"Chokchaloemwong2019\">{{Cite journal|last=Chokchaloemwong|first=Duangsuda|last2=Hattori|first2=Soki|last3=Cuesta|first3=Elena|last4=Jintasakul|first4=Pratueng|last5=Shibata|first5=Masateru|last6=Azuma|first6=Yoichi|date=2019|editor-last=Liu|editor-first=Jun|title=A new carcharodontosaurian theropod (Dinosauria: Saurischia) from the Lower Cretaceous of Thailand|url=|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=14|issue=10|pages=e0222489|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0222489|issn=1932-6203|pmc=6784982|pmid=31596853}}</ref>'' [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontians]] like ''[[Sirindhorna]] khoratensis'',<ref name=\":15\" /> ''[[Ratchasimasaurus]] suranaerae'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shibata|first=Masateru|last2=JINTASAKUL|first2=Pratueng|last3=Azuma|first3=Yoichi|date=2011|title=A New Iguanodontian Dinosaur from the Lower Cretaceous Khok Kruat Formation, Nakhon Ratchasima in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264655916|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica|volume=85|issue=5|pages=969\u2013976|doi=10.1111/j.1755-6724.2011.00530.x|via=}}</ref> and ''[[Siamodon]] nimngami'';<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Buffetaut|first1=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|date=2011|title=A new iguanodontian dinosaur from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous, Aptian) of northeastern Thailand|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0753396911000425|journal=Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie|language=en|volume=97|issue=1\u20132|pages=51\u201362|doi=10.1016/j.annpal.2011.08.001|issn=0753-3969|via=}}</ref> as well as a ''Phuwiangosaurus''-like sauropod,<ref name=\":7\" /> an indeterminate [[Ceratopsia|ceratopsian]],<ref name=\"sereno2010\">{{cite book|title=New Perspectives on Horned Dinosaurs: The Royal Tyrrell Museum Ceratopsian Symposium|last=Sereno|first=Paul C.|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2010|editor1-last=Ryan|editor1-first=Michael J.|location=Bloomington and Indianapolis|pages=21\u201358|chapter=Taxonomy, cranial morphology, and relationships of parrot-beaked dinosaurs (Ceratopsia:''Psittacosaurus'')|editor2-last=Chinnery-Allgeier|editor2-first=Brenda J.|editor3-last=Eberth|editor3-first=David A.}}</ref> and various indeterminate theropods.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> The formation is probably equivalent to the [[Gres superieurs Formation]] of Laos, since animals like advanced iguanodontians, sauropods, and spinosaurids have also been found there.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\nAmerican palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted in 2010 that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12|via=|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues suggested such a global distribution may have occurred earlier across [[Pangaea]] before the [[Late Jurassic]], even if Asia became separated from the supercontinent first.<ref name=\"AXRK122\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref> In 2019, Spanish palaeontologist Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues also indicated a complex [[biogeographical]] pattern for spinosaurs during the Early Cretaceous, based on anatomical similarities between the ''Ichthyovenator'' and the European genus ''[[Vallibonavenatrix]]''.<ref name=\":32\">{{cite journal |last1=Malafaia |first1=Elisabete |last2=Gasulla |first2=Jos\u00e9 Miguel |last3=Escaso |first3=Fernando |last4=Narv\u00e1ez |first4=Iv\u00e1n |last5=Sanz |first5=Jos\u00e9 Luis |last6=Ortega |first6=Francisco |title=A new spinosaurid theropod (Dinosauria: Megalosauroidea) from the upper Barremian of Vallibona, Spain: Implications for spinosaurid diversity in the Early Cretaceous of the Iberian Peninsula |journal=Cretaceous Research |date=February 2020 |volume=106 |page=104221 |doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104221}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Megalosauroidea}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q134636}}\n\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Barremian life]]\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fossils of Thailand]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1986]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by \u00c9ric Buffetaut]]\n", "name_user": "Twofingered Typist", "label": "safe", "comment": "added British English tag; wording & edits for flow; added WP link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siamosaurus"}
{"title_page": "Gilad Atzmon", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gilad Atzmon<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}\n| image=Gilad Atzmon.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Atzmon in concert, February 2007\n| birth_name = Gilad Atzmon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|9}}\n| birth_place = Tel Aviv, Israel\n| known_for = Music, political activism\n| education = [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]], [[University of Essex]]\n| occupation = Musician, novelist\n| website = {{url|gilad.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Gilad Atzmon''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}, {{IPA-he|\u0261i\u02c8lad at\u0361s\u02c8mon|}}; born 9 June 1963) is a British [[jazz]] saxophonist, novelist, political activist, and writer.<ref name=\"Urbain\">Karen Abi-Ezzi, 'Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon,' in Olivier Urbain (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA93&dq=Atzmon+renounced+Israeli+citizenship ''Music and Conflict Transformation: Harmonies and Dissonances in Geopolitics,''] [[I. B. Tauris]], 2015 pp.93\u2013103, p. 93</ref><ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/><ref name=\"gilchrist222\">{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/39I-thought-music-could-heal.3804991.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000|title='I thought music could heal the wounds of the past. I may have got that wrong'|last=Gilchrist|first=Jim|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=Lewis>John Lewis [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/06/gilad-atzmon-israel-jazz-interview#history-byline \"Manic beat preacher\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 March 2009</ref><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Richard|year=2005|title=Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich|url-access=registration|publisher=Penguin Books| location = London | isbn = 0-141-00646-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich/page/23 23]}}</ref>\n\nAtzmon has written novels, journalistic pieces for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>Examples of Gilad Atzmon in [[CounterPunch]]:[https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/09/18/vengeance-barbarism-and-tarantino-s-inglourious-basterds/ Vengeance, Barbarism and Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds], 18 September 2009; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/08/28/the-most-common-mistakes-of-israelis/ Collective Self-Deception: The Most Common Mistakes of Israelis], 28 August 2003; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/10/thinking-outside-of-the-secular-box/ The Left and Islam: Thinking Outside of the Secular Box], 10\u201312 July 2009.</ref> ''Uruknet'',<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://uruknet.info/?p=m31096&s1=h1 Purim Special, From Esther to AIPAC], Uruknet, 3 March 2007.</ref> ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',<ref>Example of Gilad Atzmon in ''The Palestine Telegraph'': [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/jewish-ideology-and-world-peace-by-gilad-atzmon.html 'Israeli Ideology and World Peace,'] 7 June 2010.</ref>  and polemical works on [[Jewish identity]]. His criticisms of [[Zionism]], Jewish identity, and Judaism, as well as his controversial views on [[Holocaust denial]] and [[Jewish history]], have led to allegations of antisemitism.<ref>[[Nick Lowles (activist)|Nick Lowles]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20131205131225/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr 'GILAD ATZMON: Supporting Holocaust deniers and spreading hatred,'] [[Hope Not Hate]] blog 24 November 2011</ref><ref name=Disavow>{{cite web|title=Palestinian writers, activists disavow racism, anti-Semitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/palestinian-writers-activists-disavow-racism-anti-semitism-gilad-atzmon|publisher=Electronic Intifada|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Not Quite \"Ordinary Human Beings\" \u2014 Anti-Imperialism and the Anti-Humanist Rhetoric of Gilad Atzmon |url=https://mronline.org/2012/02/28/ga280212-html/ |publisher=Monthly Review |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAtzmon was born in a [[secular Jew]]ish family in Tel Aviv, Israel, [[Ashkenazi]] on his father's side,<ref name=\"Beauty\" /> and grew up in Jerusalem.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/haunted-by-ghosts-1.319263 |title=Haunted by Ghosts |first=Yaron |last=Frid |date=15 October 2010 |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=12 January 2018 }}</ref> His great-grandmother was a victim of World War II, but he refuses to assign her death a special [[Holocaust]] status.<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA175  ''The Wandering Who,'']  p. 175 \"Historical narratives do not need the protection of the law and political lobbies. It took me years to grasp that my great-grandmother wasn\u2019t made into a \u2018soap\u2019 or a \u2018lampshade\u2019 as I was taught in Israel. She probably perished of exhaustion, typhus or maybe even by mass shooting. This was indeed bad and tragic, but not that different from the fate of many millions of Ukrainians, on learning the real meaning of communism\".</ref> His grandfather was, he states, a commander in the paramilitary [[Irgun]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate in Palestine]], who subscribed to the [[Iron Wall (essay)|doctrines]] of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], hated Germans, despised the British, was angry with Palestinians for living on land that God had given to Jews, and loathed Jewish leftists.<ref name = WanderingBook /> For Atzmon he was a 'veteran [[Zionist political violence|Zionist terrorist]]', and he himself grew up in what he describes as a 'happy childhood'<ref>. Silvia Cattori [http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-wandering-who/2011/9/27/silvia-cattori-interviews-gilad-atzmon.html 'Interview with Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon.com 27 September 2011</ref> imbued with a spirit of 'militant enthusiasm.'<ref name = WanderingBook />\n\nAtzmon first became interested in the British variety of [[jazz]] when he came across some recordings of it in a British record shop in Jerusalem in the 1970s, and found inspiration in the work of [[Ronnie Scott]] and [[Tubby Hayes]] and regarded London as \"the Mecca of Jazz.\"<ref name=\"JazzHot\"/> However, at 17, while readying himself for induction into the army, he happened to hear a radio broadcast of a recording of [[Charlie Parker]]'s ''[[Charlie Parker with Strings|With Strings]]'' and was swept off his feet. Atzmon has said of the album that he \"loved the way the music is both beautiful and subversive&nbsp;\u2013 the way he basks in the strings but also fights against them.\"<ref name=Lewis/> He skipped school to visit Jerusalem's Piccadilly Records outlet, and bought up every [[Bebop]] recording they stocked. Two days later, he purchased a saxophone.<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nAtzmon was [[Conscription in Israel|conscripted]] into the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) in June 1981. He began his service as a combat medic and participated in the [[1982 Lebanon War]]. Aztmon was transferred to a position within the [[Israel Defense Forces Orchestra]] and spent most of his military service in the [[Israeli Air Force]] orchestra. He explains this as a reflection of the fact that '\u2019(p)laying scales at the speed of light seemed to me far more important than killing Arabs in the name of Jewish suffering.\u2019 Three weeks before the end of his military service, in the wake of the war, his troupe visited an IDF detention camp at [[Ansar, Lebanon]]. He later wrote that this was a 'life-changing' experience, coming into direct contact with the conditions of captured Palestinians, some locked in [[solitary confinement]] in what he took at first to be 1 metre square concrete boxes for guard dogs. During a guided tour, he states that, as he peered across the barbed wire at the POWs, he felt that \u2018the place was a concentration camp. The inmates were the 'Jews', and I was nothing but a \u2018Nazi\u2019.'<ref name = WanderingBook/> After he was demobilised, he travelled to Europe in December 1984, living as a [[Street performer|busker]].<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nIn the following years, he trained at the [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|work=People|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> During the late 1980s and 1990s Atzmon was a popular [[session musician]] and producer, recording extensively and performing with Israeli artists such as: [[Yehuda Poliker]], [[Yardena Arazi]], Si Himan, [[Meir Banai]] and [[Ofra Haza]]. Additionally, he started the first incarnation of the \"Gilad Atzmon Quartet\" and a group named \"Spiel Acid Jazz Band\" with fellow Israeli Jazz musicians, and performed regularly at the [[Red Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref name=haaretz />\n\nIn 1994, disenchanted with the implications of the [[Oslo Accords]], Atzmon immigrated to the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"RainLore bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rainloresworldofmusic.net/Artists/Artists_A-D/Atzmon_Gilad.html|title=Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|date=21 March 2003|publisher=Rainlore's World of Music}}</ref>{{deadlink}} attending the [[University of Essex]]<ref>[http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm University of Essex news release dated 14 December 2007 notes Atzmon is a \"graduate\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422032736/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}, Essex.ac.uk; accessed 27 February 2016.</ref> and earning a master's degree in Philosophy,<ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/> while landing a residency as musician at the Irish [[Black Lion, Kilburn|Black Lion pub]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]].<ref name = WanderingBook/> He has lived subsequently in the UK,<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> becoming a British citizen in 2002<ref name=\"St. Clair\"/> and renouncing his Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"Urbain\"/>\n\n==Music==\nWhile Atzmon's main instrument is the alto saxophone, he also plays soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones and clarinet, [[Sol (instrument)|sol]], [[zurna]] and flute.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\" /> Atzmon's jazz style has been described as [[bebop]]/[[hard bop]], with forays into [[free jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]], and seemingly inspired by [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=\"RainLore bio\" /> Atzmon sometimes plays the alto and soprano sax simultaneously.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/>\n\nAtzmon's works have also explored the music of the Middle East, North Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|title=GILAD ATZMON&nbsp;\u2013 MUSICIAN, COMPOSER, PRODUCER, EDUCATOR, WRITER|accessdate=28 October 2008|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2007|publisher=Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221120611/http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Atzmon told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he draws on [[Arabic music]] which he says cannot be notated like western music but must be internalised, which he calls \"reverting to the primacy of the ear\". Atzmon's musical method has been to play with notions of cultural identity, flirting with genres such as tango and [[klezmer]] as well as various Arabic, Balkan, Gypsy and [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] folk forms. Atzmon's recordings deliberately differ from his live shows. \"I don't think that anyone can sit in a house, at home, and listen to me play a full-on bebop solo. It's too intense. My albums need to be less manic.\"<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Collaborations and groups===\nAtzmon joined the veteran [[punk rock]] band [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] in 1998, and continued with the Blockheads after Dury's death.<ref>Stephen Robb, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6253257.stm \"The old Blockheads shows go on\"], [[BBC News]], 25 January 2007.</ref><ref>Sara Greek, [http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm Blockheads come to Hertford Corn Exchange] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206100511/http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm |date=6 December 2013 }}, [[Hertfordshire Mercury]], 28 October 2011.</ref> He has recorded and performed with [[Shane MacGowan]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Robert Wyatt]] and [[Paul McCartney]].<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/><ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\"/> He has recorded two albums with Robert Wyatt, who describes him as \"one of the few musical geniuses I've ever met\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has collaborated, recorded and performed with musicians from all around the world, including the Palestinian singer, [[Reem Kelani]], Tunisian singer and [[oud]] player [[Dhafer Youssef]], violinist Marcel Mamaliga, accordion player Romano Viazzani, bassist Yaron Stavi, violinist and trumpet-violin player, Dumitru Ovidiu Fratila, and Guillermo Rozenthuler on vocals.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> He played tenor saxophone and clarinet on one track, \"Anisina\", on the 2014 Pink Floyd album, ''[[The Endless River]]''. He has worked with leading bands as a musical producer.<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], [http://www.tourdates.co.uk/ London Tour Dates], 5 October 2007.</ref>\n\nAtzmon founded the Orient House Ensemble band in London in 2000 with [[Asaf Sirkis]] on drums, Frank Harrison on piano and Oli Hayhurst on bass. In 2003 Yaron Stavi replaced Hayhurst. In 2009 Eddie Hick replaced Sirkis.<ref name=Ensemble>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-orient-house-ensemble/ Orient House Ensemble description at Gilad Atzmon home page.]</ref><ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/14/asaf-sirkis-letting-go-review Asaf Sirkis Trio: Letting Go \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 October 2010.</ref>  The group was named after [[Orient House]], the former [[East Jerusalem]] headquarters of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], later seized by the [[Israeli Defense Forces]].<ref name=Searle>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 Gilad Atzmon and The Orient House Ensemble] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107195523/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 |date=7 November 2017 }}, [[Morning Star (UK newspaper)]], 14 November 2011.</ref><ref>Jack Massarik, \"Gilad Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble\", [[Evening Standard]], 16 January 2006.</ref> The band has recorded eight albums. Orient House announced a 40-date tour in 2010.<ref name=Searle/><ref name=Fordham>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/05/gilad-atzmon-orient-house-ensemble-review Gilad Atzmon Orient House Ensemble \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Wyatt]], who has said that Atzmon combines \"great artistry with a sense of the intrinsically non-racialist philosophy that's implicit in jazz,\"<ref>Lester Paul [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/26/best-band-rock-pop \"So who is top of the pops\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 June 2010.</ref> worked with Atzmon and others on his album ''[[Comicopera]]'' (2007).<ref>Chris Jones, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gwcz A national treasure makes another peerless album], [[BBC]], 5 October 2007.</ref> Wyatt collaborated with Atzmon and Ros Stephens, as well as lyricist [[Alfreda Benge]], on the album ''For the Ghosts Within'' (2010), released on [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]].<ref>Andy Gill, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-wyatt--atzmon--stephen-for-the-ghosts-within-domino-2102994.html Album: Wyatt, Atzmon, Stephen, For The Ghosts Within (Domino)], [[The Independent]], 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Alex Hudson, [https://exclaim.ca/music/article/robert_wyatt_unveils_new_collaborative_album \"Robert Wyatt Unveils New Collaborative Album\"], [[Exclaim!]], 8 July 2010</ref>\n\nAtzmon produced and arranged two albums for [[Sarah Gillespie]] ''Stalking Juliet ''(2009) and ''In The Current Climate ''(2011). Both albums were critically acclaimed.<ref name=\"Guardian\">John Fordham [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/10/sarah-gillespie-stalking-juliet-review \"Stalking Juliet review\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 April 2009</ref><ref name=\"Mail\">{{Cite web |url=http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday |title=\"Current Climate Review\", ''Mail on Sunday'', January 2011. |access-date=15 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826172200/http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday/ |archive-date=26 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has toured extensively as a member of Sarah Gillespie's band, playing saxophone, clarinet and accordion.<ref name=\"Metro\">[http://www.metro.co.uk/music/852007-jazz-your-cd-collection-up \"Robert Shaw, Guitarist Keeps Her Finger on the Pulse\"], Metro.co.uk, 6 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon is on the creative panel of the [[Global Music Foundation]],<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/> a non-profit organization formed in December 2004 which runs residential educational and performance workshops and events in different countries around the world.<ref name=\"GMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad mAtzmon|accessdate=23 October 2017|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> and also offers personal workshops to students.<ref name=\"Atzmon-Workshop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/education-1/|title=MUSIC EDUCATION|accessdate=3 January 2018|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2015|publisher=Gilad Atzmon}}</ref> A musical transcription of ten saxophone solos by Atzmon was released in 2010.<ref>Chris Gumbley, [http://www.gumblespublications.co.uk/saxophone-solos/ Gilad Uncovered: 10 Transcriptions], Gumbles Publications, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Reviews and awards===\nAtzmon and his ensemble have received favorable reviews from the ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[The Scotsman]]'', ''[[Birmingham Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bacon|first=Peter|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CULTURE%3A+Arts+reviews%3A+Activist+with+quotes+and+plenty+to+say%3B+Gilad...-a0127526728|title=Activist with quotes and plenty to say; Gilad Atzmon CBSO Centre|work=Birmingham Post| date=24 January 2005|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon web site].</ref> Reviews of his 2007 album ''Refuge'' included:\n:''[[Manchester Evening News]]'': \"The individuality of the music is extraordinary. No one is more willing to serve his music with raw political passion, and that curious [[Hazzan|cantor]]-like tone on clarinet is immediately arresting, like [[Artie Shaw]] writhing in his death throes.\"<ref>Alan Brownlee, [http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/world_music/s/1015/1015003_gilad_atzmon__the_orient_house_ensemble__refuge_enja.html Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble&nbsp;\u2013 Refuge (Enja)], [[Manchester Evening News]], 30 August 2007.</ref>\n:[[BBC]]: \"...the OHE is finding its voice in an increasingly subtle blend of East and West, that\u2019s brutal and beautiful.\"<ref>Kathryn Shackleton, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/5vp2/ Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble, Refuge], [[BBC]], 1 October 2007.</ref>\n\nIn February 2009 ''[[The Guardian]]'' jazz critic [[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]] reviewed Atzmon's newest album ''In loving memory of America'' which was described by Atzmon as \"a memory of America I had cherished in my mind for many years\". It includes five standards and six originals \"inspired by the sumptuous harmonies and impassioned sax-playing of [[Charlie Parker|(Charlie) Parker]]'s late-40s recordings with classical strings\".<ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/27/gilad-atzmon-loving-memory-america \"Gilad Atzmon: In Loving Memory of America\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 February 2009.</ref> Music journalist John Lewis has praised much of Atzmon's work and described Atzmon as \"one of London's finest saxophonists\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon was the recipient of the [[HMV]] ''Top Dog Award'' at the [[Jazz of Birmingham|Birmingham International Jazz Festival]] in 1996\u201398.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> Gilad Atzmon's ''Exile'' was BBC jazz album of the year in 2003.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/3107607.stm Jazz winners span generations], BBC, 30 July 2003.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nAtzmon has defined himself variously as a \"[[secular Jew]]\",<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> a \"proud self-hating Jew\"  in the style of [[Otto Weininger]],<ref name=\"Panayides\" >Theo Panayides, [https://web.archive.org/web/20100223072804/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/living/wandering-jazz-player/20100221 'Wandering jazz player,'], [[Cyprus Mail]], 21 February 2010: \"My ethical duty is to say the things that I know and feel. I\u2019m an artist. Do you know.. this is something I learned from Otto Weininger, the Austrian philosopher. He was a clever boy, killed himself when he was 21. ..He was definitely a proud self-hating Jew! I\u2019m not a self-hating Jew: I\u2019m a proud self-hating Jew! It\u2019s a big difference\u2026 I celebrate my hatred towards everything I represent \u2013 or better to say [everything] I\u2019m associated with\".</ref> an \"ex-Jew\",<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/a-new-jewish-goal-by-gilad-atzmon.html A New Jewish Goal], at his personal web site.</ref> \"a Jew who hates Judaism\",<ref>{{cite news|last=\u05d7\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc\u05d9|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d8\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df|url=http://article.yedioth.co.il/default.aspx?articleid=5448|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=9 November 2011|language=Hebrew|quote=\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e9\u05dd \u05d0\u05ea \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9 \u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05ea \u05de\u05d2\u05d3\u05dc\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d7\u05df \u05db\u05dc \u05d0\u05e1\u05e4\u05e7\u05d8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05d9. (As a Jew who hates Judaism, I put myself under a magnifying glass and examine every Jewish aspect in me).}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halily|first=Yaniv|title=The protocols of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4147243,00.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> and \"a Hebrew-speaking Palestinian\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/>\n\nAtzmon writes and edits for the website, Palestine Think Tank.<ref name=Lewis/> He told interviewer Theo Panayides: \"I don't write about politics, I write about ethics. I write about Identity. I write a lot about the [[Jewish Question]]&nbsp;\u2013 because I was born in the Jew-land, and my whole process in maturing into an adult was involved with the realisation that my people are living on stolen land.\"<ref name=\"Panayides\"/> Atzmon has said that his experience in the military of \"my people destroying other people left a big scar\" and led to his decision that he was deluded about Zionism. He has condemned \"Jewishness\" as \"very much a supremacist, racist tendency\", but he has also stated that \"I don't have anything against Jews in particular and you won't find that in my writings\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> Regarding the one-state solution, Atzmon concedes that such a state probably would be controlled by [[Islamist]]s, but says, \"That's their business\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has compared \"the Jewish Ideology\" to that of the [[Nazis]] and has described Israel's policy toward the Palestinians as [[genocide]].<ref name=\"gibson\"/> [[David Hirst (journalist)|David Hirst]], in his 2003 book ''The Gun and the Olive Branch,'' quotes Atzmon as saying America was \"about to lose its sovereignty...becoming a remote colony of an apparently far greater state, the Jewish state.\u201d<ref>David Hirst, ''The Gun and the Olive Branch: the roots of violence in the Middle East,'' Nation Books, 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Oisa_1Dc69kC&pg=PA49&dq=gun+and+olive+branch+atzmon&hl=en&ei=ZgdFTM-YAsP98Abntc3aAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 49]</ref> In 2009, [[Turkey|Turkish]] Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] cited Atzmon's written comment \"Israeli barbarity is far beyond even ordinary cruelty\" during a debate with Israeli president [[Shimon Peres]].<ref name=\"Lewis\"/>\n\n===Novels===\nAtzmon's ''[[A Guide to the Perplexed]]'', published in 2001, is set in a 2052 in which Israel has been replaced by a Palestinian state. It largely reviews memoirs of the alienated Israeli Gunther Wunker's rise to fame as a \"peepologist\", or voyeur. The perplexed are defined as \"the unthinking Chosen\" who \"cling to clods of earth that don't belong to them.\" The novel excoriates what it describes as the commercialization of the Holocaust and \"argues that the Holocaust is invoked as a kind of reflexive propaganda designed to shield the Zionist state from responsibility for any transgression against Palestinians.\"<ref name=\"St. Clair\">[[Jeffrey St. Clair]],[https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/07/17/gilad-atzmon-s-a-guide-to-the-perplexed/ 'Gilad Atzmon's \"A Guide to the Perplexed\",'] [[CounterPunch]] 17 July 2003</ref>\n\nMatthew J. Reisz, a reviewer for ''[[The Independent]]'', wrote that \"As a viciously black satire on Israeli life\" the book \"is grandiose, childish and nasty, but with just enough connection with reality to give it a certain unsettling power\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Reisz|first=Matthew J.|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-guide-to-the-perplexed-by-gilad-atzmon-trans-philip-simpson-609999.html|title=A Guide to the Perplexed, by Gilad Atzmon, trans. Philip Simpson|work=The Independent|date=7 December 2002|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} Darren King in ''[[The Observer]]'' noted of this \"provocative debut novel\" that it is \"odd to mix knob gags with highly serious assertions\", but thought it works because \"Atzmon writes with so much style and his gags are so hilarious\".<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Darren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/featuresreviews.guardianreview16|title=Mr. Peepology|work=The Observer|date=25 January 2003|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', \"Atzmon clearly wants to provoke, but his approach is so familiar that few readers will take the bait.\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-85242-826-6 \"A Guide to the Perplexed\"], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', 31 March 2003.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's second novel, ''My One and Only Love'', was published in 2005 and features as a protagonist a trumpeter who chooses to play only one note (extremely well), as well as a spy who uncovers Nazi war criminals and locks them inside double bass cases which then tour permanently in the protagonist's orchestra's luggage.<ref>Sholto Byrnes. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/talking-jazz-529796.html \"Talking Jazz\"], ''The Independent'', 25 March 2005</ref> The book is also a comedic take on \"Zionist espionage and intrigue\" which explores \"the personal conflict between being true to one\u2019s heart and being loyal to The Jews\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2004/10/01/gilad_event_feature.shtml \"Gilad Atzmon's Orient House Ensemble \u2013 The Junction\"], BBC Cambridgeshire, 3 June 2005.</ref>\n\n===''The Wandering Who?''===\nIn 2011, [[Zero Books]] published Atzmon's book ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics'', stating that it \"examines Jewish identity politics and Jewish contemporary ideology using both popular culture and scholarly texts.\"<ref name = WanderingBook>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=rTbtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&lpg=PT7 ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics''], Zero Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84694-875-6}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jean Bricmont]], in his preface for the French edition, ''La Parabole d\u2019Esther'', Atzmon starts by making three definitions of the word 'Jewish': (a) it may refer to adherents of Judaism, and he has no quarrel with them; (b) secondly, it may refer to ethnic Jews, and, likewise, he sees no problem in that; (c) thirdly, it can refer to a third category, those who, without being particularly religious, place great emphasis on their Jewish \"identity\" as something more important than their basic membership of the human race.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" >[[Jean Bricmont]], [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/counterpunch-print-edition-in-defense-of-gilad-atzmon-by-jea.html  'In Defense of Gilad Atzmon By Jean Bricmont,'] Counterpunch April 2012 print edition, cited on Atzmon's blog.</ref> Bricmont then adds that it is very easy to mount a case to 'prove' Atzmon is an antisemite by consistently construing his criticisms of (c) as though they were aimed as (a) or (b) or both.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" /> \n\n[[Marc H. Ellis]],  professor of Jewish studies at [[Baylor University]], likens Atzmon's rhetorical extremism and harsh censure of Jews to the [[Prophet|prophetic voices]] of the [[Old Testament]], arguing that, for Atzmon, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] Jews are asked to construct their identity on the basis of the [[State of Israel]] and the [[Holocaust]], an identity he regards as without foundation. He adds that Atzmon considers charges that he is antisemitic as 'last ditch attempts' to validate that identity. In Ellis's view, there may be, in the perceived anxiety in these repeated attacks, a reflection of the same anxiety Atzmon himself arguably embodies.<ref name=\"Ellis\" >[[Marc H. Ellis]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=doN-AwAAQBAJ&dq=Marc+Ellis%2BGilad+Atzmon&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y  ''Future of the Prophetic: Israel's Ancient Wisdom Re-presented,''] [[Fortress Press]], 2014 pp.331\u2013332.</ref><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/the-new-jewish-prophet.html  'The New Jewish Prophet,'] 24 June 2014.</ref> {{efn|Ellis also notes that Atzmon considers the bible 'bogus'.<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> Atzmon himself cites evidence 600 passages in the OT are violent, and argues that this 'lethal spirit of the scriptures has infused the essence of modern Jewish political discourse,' underwriting in his view even the secular mindset of military commanders conducting war in Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.<ref>G. Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA122 ''The Wandering Who,''] 2011 p.122.</ref>}}\n\nTen authors published by Zero Books, including [[Laurie Penny]] and [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]], criticised the publisher publicly for releasing the book, arguing:<blockquote>The thrust of Atzmon's work is to normalise and legitimise anti-Semitism. We do not believe that Zero's decision to publish this book is malicious. Atzmon's ability to solicit endorsements from respectable figures such as [[Richard Falk]] and [[John Mearsheimer]] shows that he is adept at muddying the waters both on his own views and on the question of anti-Semitism. But at a time when dangerous forces are attempting to racialise political antagonisms, we think the decision is grossly mistaken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leninology.blogspot.com/2011/09/zero-authors-statement-on-gilad-atzmon.html|title=Zero Authors Statement on Gilad Atzmon|publisher=Lenin's Tomb|date=26 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nMearsheimer has said that \"There is no question that the book is provocative, both in terms of its central argument and the overly hot language that Atzmon sometimes uses. But it is also filled with interesting insights that make the reader think long and hard about an important subject.\"<ref>Stephen Walt, [http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The New Republic]]'', [[Alan Dershowitz]] criticized Mearsheimer and Falk for recommending the book<ref name=\"Dershowitz\">Alan Dershowitz, [http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/97030/atzmon-wandering-who-anti-semitism-israel \"Why are John Mearsheimer and Richard Falk Endorsing a Blatantly Anti-Semitic Book?\"], ''The New Republic'', 4 November 2011.</ref> and challenged them to a public debate.<ref name=\"Dershowitz\"/> Falk rejected Dershowitz's call to debate.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} Atzmon offered to debate Dershowitz at \"any time\".<ref>Gilad Atzmon at Gilad Atzmon website, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/dershowitz-lies-and-glitches-by-gilad-atzmon.html Dershowitz\u2019 Lies and Glitches], 9 November 2011 and [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/if-dershowitz-wants-a-debate-i-will-meet-him-any-time.html \"If Dershowitz Wants a Debate, I Will Meet Him Any Time\"], 23 October 2011.</ref> He called various criticisms \"a typical [[Hasbara]] smear & intimidation campaign.\u201d<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/goldberg-vs-mearsheimer-by-gilad-atzmon.html Goldberg vs. Mearsheimer], Gilad Atzmon website, 25 September 2011.</ref> Atzmon replied to the MacDonald review referenced by Dershowitz, writing that his book \"is a study of Jewish identity politics and Jewish culture, it is not concerned with Jewish ethnicity or racial origins.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-supremacists-on-the-wandering-who.html \"Supremacists on 'The Wandering Who'\"], Gilad.co.uk, 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\n==Allegations of antisemitism==\nSeveral of Atzmon's statements regarding Jews and Judaism have led to allegations of antisemitism. \n\n===Campaigners===\nThe [[Anti-Defamation League]] describes Atzmon as \"antisemitic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/profiles/gilad-atzmon|title=Gilad Atzmon|publisher=ADL|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[Hope not Hate]] called for the cancellation of an Atzmon performance at the \"Raise Your Banners\" festival of political song.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1487/pull-the-plug-on-gilad-atzmon|title=Pull the plug on Gilad Atzmon|work=Hope not Hate|date=21 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127145630/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1487/pull-the-plug-on-gilad-atzmon|archive-date=27 November 2013}}</ref> Bradford's Trades Union Council also condemned the appearance and the Board of Deputies of British Jews asked the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council]], which had funded the festival, to stop it.<ref name=Griffiths>Kathie Griffiths, [http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/9376005.Jazz_saxophonist_Gilad_Atzmon_at_centre_of_Raise_Your_Banners_festival_row/ \"Calls for musician's show to be cancelled\"], ''[[Telegraph & Argus]]'', 22 November 2011.</ref> [[Gerry Sutcliffe]], Labour MP for [[Bradford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford South]], and the Right Reverend [[David Ison]], then Dean of Bradford Cathedral also called for the festival to rescind their invitation.<ref>Simon Rocker, [http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/58942/more-calls-gilad-atzmon-concert-ban More calls for Gilad Atzmon concert ban], [[The Jewish Chronicle]], 24 November 2011.</ref> The Arts Council refused the request, while the festival director said organisers did not believe the claims. Atzmon said the Trade Union Council's letter \"stitched together\u201d phrases from five separate paragraphs into one quote to make him look racist, and demanded an apology.<ref name=Griffiths/>  \n\nIn ''Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today,'' published in 2012 by Hope not Hate, [[Nick Lowles]] wrote: \"Despite being Jewish himself, Atzmon has promoted Holocaust deniers and claims that the established history of the Holocaust is misleading. He attacks Jewish identity in a way that would clearly be recognised as racist if it were about any other minority identity and claims that people might think that Hitler was right about the Jews because of their behaviour today. He tells crude antisemitic jokes and mocks any concerns about antisemitism.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111105903/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-01-11|date=December 2012|publisher=[[Hope not Hate]]|page=9|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\nIn 2005, [[David Aaronovitch]] criticized Atzmon's essay \"On Anti-Semitism\", for defending [[Israel Shamir]], circulating an essay by Paul Eisen defending [[Holocaust denier]] [[Ernst Z\u00fcndel]]'s right to think, speak, and write as he pleases, and for supporting many aspects of Z\u00fcndel's Holocaust denial theories.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\">{{cite news|last=Aaronovitch|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-did-the-far-left-manage-to-slip-into-bed-with-the-jew-hating-right-766cbwpdqfd|title=How did the far Left manage to slip into bed with the Jew-hating Right?|work=The Times|location=London|date=28 June 2005|accessdate=24 February 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"onanti\">Gilad Atzmon, {{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |title=On Anti-Semitism |accessdate=27 July 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050213011436/http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |archivedate=13 February 2005 }}, originally at his personal web site, 20 December 2003.</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 piece in ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[David Hirsh]] also criticized Atzmon's \"On Anti-Semitism\" essay, and particularly its [[Jewish deicide]] claim, as an example of Atzmon's \"openly anti-Jewish rhetoric.\"<ref>Hirsh, David. [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/nov/30/anewmenacingcurrentisappe Openly embracing prejudice], ''The Guardian'', 30 November 2006. Hirsh also refers to the statement in [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/apr/03/nobodyhaseverclaimedthatc \"What charge?\"], \"The Guardian\", 3 April 2006.</ref> In response to a question about this quote from [[Lenni Brenner]], Atzmon replied that he meant \"I find it astonishing that people today happen to be offended by such accusations.\"<ref>[https://www.counterpunch.org/2007/02/15/quot-do-i-look-like-the-pope-quot/ \"Are You a Christian?\" \"Do I Look Like the Pope?\"&nbsp;\u2013 An Exchange Between Lenni Brenner & Gilad Atzmon], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 15 February 2007.</ref>\n\n[[Nick Cohen]], in a 2009 piece for ''[[The Observer]]'', criticised Atzmon.<ref name=\"Cohen\">Nick Cohen [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/jun/14/james-von-brunn-far-right \"The unlikely friends of the Holocaust memorial killer\"], ''The Observer'', 14 June 2009</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 blog for ''[[The Times]]'', [[Oliver Kamm]] charged Atzmon with antisemitism for his article \"Truth, History and Integrity\".<ref>Oliver Kamm, [http://timesonline.typepad.com/oliver_kamm/2010/03/an-antisemites-progress.html An antisemite's progress] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329214204/http://timesonline.typepad.com/oliver_kamm/2010/03/an-antisemites-progress.html |date=29 March 2010 }}, ''The Times'', 26 March 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Keith Kahn-Harris]] argues that Atzmon's view of the world in ''Being In Time'' (2017) is inherently antisemitic. Kahn-Harris describes Atzmon as \"deliberately apathetic about the Holocaust and other atrocities against Jews, nodding towards without completely embracing both justification and denial\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Kahn-Harris|first=Keith|url=https://forward.com/opinion/389696/cloaked-in-pretensions-gilad-atzmons-anti-semitism-soldiers-on/|title=Cloaked In Pretensions, Gilad Atzmon\u2019s Anti-Semitism Soldiers On|work=Forward|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Zionists===\nIn September 2011 trade unionist and blogger Andy Newman<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/andy-newman Andy Newman profile] on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website</ref> writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'' described his writing as \"anti-Jewish hate-speech\". In his view, Atzmon's political writing are \"a wild conspiracy argument, dripping with contempt for Jews\".<ref name=\"Newman\">Andy Newman [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/sep/25/gilad-atzmon-antisemitism-the-left?newsfeed=true \"Gilad Atzmon, antisemitism and the left\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 25 September 2011.</ref> In a letter printed by the ''Guardian'', Atzmon wrote that Newman had \"misrepresented\" his views and that \"how to define a Jew is a loaded topic since Jews define themselves in many different ways, some contradictory, and use those definitions to try to achieve political aims.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/sep/28/moral-obligation-and-jewish-identity?newsfeed=true Letter: Moral obligation and Jewish identity], ''The Guardian'', 28 September 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2011, David Landy, an Irish academic and former chair of the Ireland Palestine Solidarity Campaign, wrote that Atzmon's words, \"if not actually anti-Semitic, certainly border on it\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Landy|first=David|title=Jewish Identity and Palestinian Rights: Disapora Jewish Opposition to Israel|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84813-926-8|page=167}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Community Security Trust]] report on antisemitic discourse in the UK in 2011 described Atzmon as increasingly regarded among anti-Zionists as an unwelcome antisemite: \"Atzmon's analysis of Jewish history, identity and culture introduces an unusually explicit and quite new antisemitism into far left-wing politics. Leading Jewish anti-Zionist figures have denounced Atzmon as an antisemite. Most anti-Zionists have followed suit and now also condemn Atzmon, but some factional splits have occurred due to a minority of activists defending him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Antisemitic Discourse in Britain in 2011|url=https://cst.org.uk/docs/Antisemitic%20Discourse%20Report%202011%20WEB.pdf|date=November 2012|publisher=Community Standard Trust|page=30|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nA group of leading Palestinian activists issued a statement in March 2012 calling for \"the disavowal of Atzmon by fellow Palestinian organizers, as well as Palestine solidarity activists, and allies of the Palestinian people\". The statement affirmed that \"we regard any attempt to link and adopt antisemitic or racist language, even if it is within a self-described anti-imperialist and anti-Zionist politics, as reaffirming and legitimizing Zionism.\" Signatories included [[Ali Abunimah]], [[Naseer Aruri]], [[Omar Barghouti]], [[Nadia Hijab]], [[Joseph Massad]].<ref name=Disavow/><ref>{{cite web|title=Granting No Quarter: A Call for the Disavowal of the Racism and Antisemitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://uspcn.org/2012/03/13/granting-no-quarter-a-call-for-the-disavowal-of-the-racism-and-antisemitism-of-gilad-atzmon|publisher=US Palestinian Community Network|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Palestinian activists disavow Israeli musician Atzmon|url=https://www.jta.org/2012/03/14/news-opinion/united-states/palestinian-activists-disavow-israeli-musician-atzmon|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=14 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Palestinian writers, activists disavow racism, anti-Semitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/palestinian-writers-activists-disavow-racism-anti-semitism-gilad-atzmon|date=13 March 2012|publisher=Electronic Intifada|accessdate= 25 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=467843|title=Palestinian writers disavow Gilad Atzmon|date=14 March 2012|publisher= Maan News Agency|accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Comments at talk===\nAt a talk by Richard Falk at [[London School of Economics|LSE]] in March 2017, which was being disrupted by protestors, Atzmon was alleged to have commented that Jews had been \"expelled from Germany for misbehaving\" and that people should read Holocaust denier [[David Irving]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-students-told-dont-study-at-lse-by-board-president/|title=Jewish students told 'don\u2019t study at LSE' by Board president|work=Jewish News Online|date=23 March 2017|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Responses===\nAtzmon refers to charges of antisemitism as being a \"common Zionist silencing apparatus.\"<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], Interview with Gilad Atzmon in ''London Tour Dates'' magazine, 5 October 2006</ref> He denies that he is an antisemite and states that, \"Because 'Anti-Semite' is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have.\"<ref name=1001Lies>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/1001-lies-about-gilad-atzmon.html 1001 Lies About Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon com. 18 June 2011 \"I am an anti Zionist and oppose the Zionist mindset. I look at questions of Jewish identity and I do question the ties between a Jewish world view and Zionism. I refute totally that I am anti-Semite. In fact I also believe that the current concept of an Anti-Semitism is meaningless. Once the Zionists had managed to establish their Jewish state, any form of anti Jewish sentiments should be comprehended either as a private case of xenophobia or as a political retaliation to Israeli/Zionist atrocities. In other words, the title Anti-Semite became an \u2018empty signifier, i.e. a signifier with a vague, highly variable, unspecifiable or non-existent signified. It is an empty verbal utterance that exists merely to serve a political cause (very much like Blair\u2019s WMD and Bush\u2019s Axis of Evil). Because Anti-Semite is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have\".</ref> In 2009, Atzmon said \"I've got nothing against the Semite people, I don't have anything against people&nbsp;\u2014 I'm anti-Jewish, not anti-Jews.\"<ref name=\"gibson\">Gibson, Martin. \"No choice but to speak out&nbsp;\u2014 Israeli musician 'a proud self-hating Jew'\", ''The Gisborne Herald'', 23 January 2009.</ref> He added that \"Stupidly we interpreted the Nazi defeat as a vindication of the Jewish ideology and the Jewish people\"; however, \"in fact Jewish ideology and Nazi ideology were very similar.\"<ref name=\"gibson\"/> Atzmon has also stated that he does not deny the Holocaust or the \"Nazi Judeocide\u201d but insists \"that both the Holocaust and World War II should be treated as historical events rather than as religious myth. ... But then, even if we accept the Holocaust as the new Anglo-American liberal-democratic religion, we must allow people to be atheists.\u201d<ref name=\"Beauty\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|title=Beauty as a political weapon; Three in one: jazzman, writer and activist&nbsp;\u2013 A conversation with Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072556/http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|archivedate=3 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Talens\" >[[:es:Manuel Talens|Manuel Talens]],  [http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=24333 'La belleza como arma pol\u00edtica,'] [[Rebelion.org]] 19 December 2005,</ref> Atzmon has said his statements have lost him performance contracts, especially in the United States.<ref>Karen Abi-Ezzi, \"Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon\u201d, Chapter 7 of Olivier Urbain, Editor, ''Music and conflict transformation: harmonies and dissonances in geopolitics'', I.B. Tauris, 2008  [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA101&dq=urbain+atzmon+contracts&hl=en&ei=2wpFTPf2C8P88Ab03uDKDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 101].</ref> Atzmon has had conflicts with anti-Zionists who have attempted to stop his performances.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\"/><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-lieberman-and-the-jewish-political-continuum.html \"Gilad Atzmon: Lieberman and the Jewish Political Continuum\"], at Gilad Atzmon's web site, 10 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Oren Ben-Dor]] wrote in 2008 \"I am firmly convinced that these vulgar attempts at silencing of Gilad and other courageous voices offends against supremely thoughtful, compassionate and egalitarian intellectual endeavours.\"<ref>[[Oren Ben-Dor]], [https://www.counterpunch.org/2008/03/15/the-silencing-of-gilad-atzmon/ 'The Silencing of Gilad Atzmon'], [[CounterPunch]], 15 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, reviewer [[Chris Searle]] defended accusations against Atzmon's \"crude anti-zionist rhetoric\u201d, writing \"No jazz musicians have done more to honour, publicise and spread solidarity with the struggle of the Palestinians than Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble.\u201d<ref>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 Review of the book ''Jazz Jews'' by Mike Gerber] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175013/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 |date=23 October 2017 }}, ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', February 2010.</ref> \n\nIn 2011, [[John Mearsheimer]] defended Atzmon, writing with regard to the charge that Atzmon is antisemitic, \"to be perfectly clear, he has no animus toward Judaism as a religion or with individuals who are Jewish by birth. Rather, his target is the tribalism that he believes is common to most Jews, and I might add, to most other peoples as well. ... The more important and interesting issue is whether Atzmon is a self-hating Jew. Here the answer is unequivocally yes.\" \n\n[[Richard Falk]] described Atzmon \"a de-Zionized patriot of humanity\".<ref>Stephen M. Walt,[http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], 26 September 2011 (posted on Walt.Foreignpolicy.com)</ref> \n\nIn 2012, [[Norton Mezvinsky]] wrote that \"Gilad Atzmon is a critical and committed secular humanist with firm views, who delights in being provocative.\"<ref>[[Norton Mezvinsky]], [http://wrmea.org/archives/507-washington-report-archives-2011-2015/may-2012/11161-gilad-atzmon-and-the-wandering-who.html Gilad Atzmon and The Wandering Who?], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.wrmea.org/action-alert-archives/11194-engaging-gilad-atzmon.html 'Engaging Gilad Atzmon], video of Norton Mezvinsky interview with Gilad Atzmon,' [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref>\n\n==Libel suit==\nIn July 2018, Atzmon issued an apology to Gideon Falter, the chairman of the [[Campaign Against Antisemitism]] after being sued for libel. Atzmon had alleged that Falter had personally profited from fabricating antisemitic incidents. He was also liable for legal costs and damages.<ref name=\"Libel\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Ben |title=Gilad Atzmon is forced to apologise to CAA's Gideon Falter over libel |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/gideon-falter-gilad-atzmon-1.466405 |accessdate=3 July 2018 |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CAA\">{{cite web |title=Antisemitic author and saxophonist Gilad Atzmon capitulates, making humiliating apology and paying substantial damages and costs after just two hours in court against CAA |url=https://antisemitism.uk/antisemitic-author-and-saxophonist-gilad-atzmon-capitulates-making-humiliating-apology-and-paying-substantial-damages-and-costs-after-just-two-hours-in-court-against-caa/ |website=antisemitism.uk |publisher=Campaign Against Antisemitism |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The Spirit of Trane'' (Fanfare Jazz, 2017)\n*''World Peace Trio'' (Enja, 2017)\n*''Songs of the Metropolis'' (World Village, 2013)\n*''The Tide Has Changed'' (World Village, 2010)\n*''In Loving Memory of America'' (Enja, 2009)\n*''Refuge'' (Enja, 2007)\n*''Artie Fishel and the Promised Band'' (WMD, 2006)\n*''MusiK'' (Enja, 2004)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/oct/08/jazz.shopping1</ref>\n*''Exile'' (Enja, 2004)\n*''Nostalgico'' (Enja, 2001)\n*''Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble'' (Enja, 2000)\n*''Juizz Muzic'' (FruitBeard, 1999)\n*''Take It or Leave It'' (Face Jazz, 1997)\n*''Spiel: Both Sides'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel Acid Jazz Band'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel'' (In Acoustic & H.M. Acoustica, 1993)\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |title=[[A Guide to the Perplexed]] |translator= Philip Simpson |location=London|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]] |year=2002 |isbn=1-85242-826-0}}\n*''My one and only love''. London: Saqi Books, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86356-507-7}} (pbk.). {{ISBN|978-0-86356-507-6}} (pbk.)\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C| title=The Wandering Who?: A Study of Jewish Identity Politics |publisher=[[John Hunt Publishing|Zero Books]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-84694-875-6}}\n* ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon''. London, Fanfare Press, 2015.{{ISBN|978-0993183706}} (pbk.). \n*''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', Newbold on Stour, Warwickshire: Skyscraper Publications, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1911072201}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brian Lenzo, [http://www.palestinechronicle.com/old/view_article_details.php?id=16132 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed: Each Village is a Reminder], originally published by Socialist Worker Online, 13 July 2010 (reprinted by the Palestine Chronicle).\n*Alan Maass, [https://socialistworker.org/2010/07/14/an-article-retracted An Article Retracted], Socialist Worker Online, 14 July 2010 (retraction of preceding interview).\n*[http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/eveningnews24/norwich-whats-on-guide/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=GoingOutMusic&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=WhatsOn&itemid=NOED26%20Nov%202009%2016%3A03%3A06%3A953 Interview: Gilad Atzmon] by Rob Garratt, Evening News 24, 11 November 2009.\n*[https://archive.org/details/GiladAtzmonOnArabvoices.netJune2009 Gilad Atzmon interview on ArabVoices.net], [[KPFT]], June 2009 during visit to Houston, Texas.\n*Ivan Hewett, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3667959/Gilad-Altzmon-High-flown-ecstasies-from-an-angry-man.html Gilad Altzmon: High-flown ecstasies from an angry man], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 17 September 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133806/http://middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21321 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed by Mary Rizzo], Middle East Online, July 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon website]\n\n{{The Blockheads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atzmon, Gilad}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anti-Judaism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:Bebop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:The Blockheads members]]\n[[Category:British jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Writers on Zionism]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{pp-30-500|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Gilad Atzmon<br />{{Hebrew|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}\n| image=Gilad Atzmon.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Atzmon in concert, February 2007\n| birth_name = Gilad Atzmon\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|6|9}}\n| birth_place = Tel Aviv, Israel\n| known_for = Music, political activism\n| education = [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]], [[University of Essex]]\n| occupation = Musician, novelist\n| website = {{url|gilad.co.uk}}\n}}\n'''Gilad Atzmon''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df}}, {{IPA-he|\u0261i\u02c8lad at\u0361s\u02c8mon|}}; born 9 June 1963) is a British [[jazz]] saxophonist, novelist, political activist, and writer.<ref name=\"Urbain\">Karen Abi-Ezzi, 'Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon,' in Olivier Urbain (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA93&dq=Atzmon+renounced+Israeli+citizenship ''Music and Conflict Transformation: Harmonies and Dissonances in Geopolitics,''] [[I. B. Tauris]], 2015 pp.93\u2013103, p. 93</ref><ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/><ref name=\"gilchrist222\">{{cite news|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/39I-thought-music-could-heal.3804991.jp?CommentPage=1&CommentPageLength=1000|title='I thought music could heal the wounds of the past. I may have got that wrong'|last=Gilchrist|first=Jim|date=22 February 2008|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=21 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=Lewis>John Lewis [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/mar/06/gilad-atzmon-israel-jazz-interview#history-byline \"Manic beat preacher\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 March 2009</ref><ref name=\"RCJE\">{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Richard|year=2005|title=Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia|url=https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich|url-access=registration|publisher=Penguin Books| location = London | isbn = 0-141-00646-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/richardcooksjazz00rich/page/23 23]}}</ref>\n\nAtzmon has written novels, journalistic pieces for such publications as the ''[[Unz Review]]'' (where he has a regular column), ''[[CounterPunch]]'',<ref>Examples of Gilad Atzmon in [[CounterPunch]]:[https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/09/18/vengeance-barbarism-and-tarantino-s-inglourious-basterds/ Vengeance, Barbarism and Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds], 18 September 2009; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/08/28/the-most-common-mistakes-of-israelis/ Collective Self-Deception: The Most Common Mistakes of Israelis], 28 August 2003; [https://www.counterpunch.org/2009/07/10/thinking-outside-of-the-secular-box/ The Left and Islam: Thinking Outside of the Secular Box], 10\u201312 July 2009.</ref> ''Uruknet'',<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://uruknet.info/?p=m31096&s1=h1 Purim Special, From Esther to AIPAC], Uruknet, 3 March 2007.</ref> ''[[The Palestine Telegraph]]'',<ref>Example of Gilad Atzmon in ''The Palestine Telegraph'': [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/jewish-ideology-and-world-peace-by-gilad-atzmon.html 'Israeli Ideology and World Peace,'] 7 June 2010.</ref>  and polemical works on [[Jewish identity]]. His criticisms of [[Zionism]], Jewish identity, and Judaism, as well as his controversial views on [[Holocaust denial]] and [[Jewish history]], have led to allegations of antisemitism.<ref>[[Nick Lowles (activist)|Nick Lowles]], [https://web.archive.org/web/20131205131225/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr 'GILAD ATZMON: Supporting Holocaust deniers and spreading hatred,'] [[Hope Not Hate]] blog 24 November 2011</ref><ref name=Disavow>{{cite web|title=Palestinian writers, activists disavow racism, anti-Semitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/palestinian-writers-activists-disavow-racism-anti-semitism-gilad-atzmon|publisher=Electronic Intifada|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Not Quite \"Ordinary Human Beings\" \u2014 Anti-Imperialism and the Anti-Humanist Rhetoric of Gilad Atzmon |url=https://mronline.org/2012/02/28/ga280212-html/ |publisher=Monthly Review |accessdate=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAtzmon was born in a [[secular Jew]]ish family in Tel Aviv, Israel, [[Ashkenazi]] on his father's side,<ref name=\"Beauty\" /> and grew up in Jerusalem.<ref name=haaretz>{{cite web |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/haunted-by-ghosts-1.319263 |title=Haunted by Ghosts |first=Yaron |last=Frid |date=15 October 2010 |work=[[Haaretz]] |accessdate=12 January 2018 }}</ref> His great-grandmother was a victim of World War II, but he refuses to assign her death a special [[Holocaust]] status.<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA175  ''The Wandering Who,'']  p. 175 \"Historical narratives do not need the protection of the law and political lobbies. It took me years to grasp that my great-grandmother wasn\u2019t made into a \u2018soap\u2019 or a \u2018lampshade\u2019 as I was taught in Israel. She probably perished of exhaustion, typhus or maybe even by mass shooting. This was indeed bad and tragic, but not that different from the fate of many millions of Ukrainians, on learning the real meaning of communism\".</ref> His grandfather was, he states, a commander in the paramilitary [[Irgun]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate in Palestine]], who subscribed to the [[Iron Wall (essay)|doctrines]] of [[Ze'ev Jabotinsky]], hated Germans, despised the British, was angry with Palestinians for living on land that God had given to Jews, and loathed Jewish leftists.<ref name = WanderingBook /> For Atzmon he was a 'veteran [[Zionist political violence|Zionist terrorist]]', and he himself grew up in what he describes as a 'happy childhood'<ref>. Silvia Cattori [http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-wandering-who/2011/9/27/silvia-cattori-interviews-gilad-atzmon.html 'Interview with Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon.com 27 September 2011</ref> imbued with a spirit of 'militant enthusiasm.'<ref name = WanderingBook />\n\nAtzmon first became interested in the British variety of [[jazz]] when he came across some recordings of it in a British record shop in Jerusalem in the 1970s, and found inspiration in the work of [[Ronnie Scott]] and [[Tubby Hayes]] and regarded London as \"the Mecca of Jazz.\"<ref name=\"JazzHot\"/> However, at 17, while readying himself for induction into the army, he happened to hear a radio broadcast of a recording of [[Charlie Parker]]'s ''[[Charlie Parker with Strings|With Strings]]'' and was swept off his feet. Atzmon has said of the album that he \"loved the way the music is both beautiful and subversive&nbsp;\u2013 the way he basks in the strings but also fights against them.\"<ref name=Lewis/> He skipped school to visit Jerusalem's Piccadilly Records outlet, and bought up every [[Bebop]] recording they stocked. Two days later, he purchased a saxophone.<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nAtzmon was [[Conscription in Israel|conscripted]] into the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) in June 1981. He began his service as a combat medic and participated in the [[1982 Lebanon War]]. Aztmon was transferred to a position within the [[Israel Defense Forces Orchestra]] and spent most of his military service in the [[Israeli Air Force]] orchestra. He explains this as a reflection of the fact that '\u2019(p)laying scales at the speed of light seemed to me far more important than killing Arabs in the name of Jewish suffering.\u2019 Three weeks before the end of his military service, in the wake of the war, his troupe visited an IDF detention camp at [[Ansar, Lebanon]]. He later wrote that this was a 'life-changing' experience, coming into direct contact with the conditions of captured Palestinians, some locked in [[solitary confinement]] in what he took at first to be 1 metre square concrete boxes for guard dogs. During a guided tour, he states that, as he peered across the barbed wire at the POWs, he felt that \u2018the place was a concentration camp. The inmates were the 'Jews', and I was nothing but a \u2018Nazi\u2019.'<ref name = WanderingBook/> After he was demobilised, he travelled to Europe in December 1984, living as a [[Street performer|busker]].<ref name = WanderingBook/>\n\nIn the following years, he trained at the [[Jerusalem Academy of Music and Dance|Rubin Academy of Music]] in Jerusalem.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|work=People|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> During the late 1980s and 1990s Atzmon was a popular [[session musician]] and producer, recording extensively and performing with Israeli artists such as: [[Yehuda Poliker]], [[Yardena Arazi]], Si Himan, [[Meir Banai]] and [[Ofra Haza]]. Additionally, he started the first incarnation of the \"Gilad Atzmon Quartet\" and a group named \"Spiel Acid Jazz Band\" with fellow Israeli Jazz musicians, and performed regularly at the [[Red Sea Jazz Festival]].<ref name=haaretz />\n\nIn 1994, disenchanted with the implications of the [[Oslo Accords]], Atzmon immigrated to the United Kingdom,<ref name=\"RainLore bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rainloresworldofmusic.net/Artists/Artists_A-D/Atzmon_Gilad.html|title=Profile&nbsp;\u2013 Gilad Atzmon|accessdate=28 October 2008|date=21 March 2003|publisher=Rainlore's World of Music}}</ref>{{deadlink}} attending the [[University of Essex]]<ref>[http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm University of Essex news release dated 14 December 2007 notes Atzmon is a \"graduate\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422032736/http://www.essex.ac.uk/news/2007/nr20071214.htm |date=22 April 2008 }}, Essex.ac.uk; accessed 27 February 2016.</ref> and earning a master's degree in Philosophy,<ref name=\"CryFreedom\"/> while landing a residency as musician at the Irish [[Black Lion, Kilburn|Black Lion pub]] in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]].<ref name = WanderingBook/> He has lived subsequently in the UK,<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> becoming a British citizen in 2002<ref name=\"St. Clair\"/> and renouncing his Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"Urbain\"/>\n\n==Music==\nWhile Atzmon's main instrument is the alto saxophone, he also plays soprano, tenor and baritone saxophones and clarinet, [[Sol (instrument)|sol]], [[zurna]] and flute.<ref name=\"GMF-GA\" /> Atzmon's jazz style has been described as [[bebop]]/[[hard bop]], with forays into [[free jazz]] and [[Swing music|swing]], and seemingly inspired by [[John Coltrane]] and [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=\"RainLore bio\" /> Atzmon sometimes plays the alto and soprano sax simultaneously.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/>\n\nAtzmon's works have also explored the music of the Middle East, North Africa, and Eastern Europe.<ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|title=GILAD ATZMON&nbsp;\u2013 MUSICIAN, COMPOSER, PRODUCER, EDUCATOR, WRITER|accessdate=28 October 2008|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2007|publisher=Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221120611/http://www.gilad.co.uk/index.html|archivedate=21 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Atzmon told ''[[The Guardian]]'' that he draws on [[Arabic music]] which he says cannot be notated like western music but must be internalised, which he calls \"reverting to the primacy of the ear\". Atzmon's musical method has been to play with notions of cultural identity, flirting with genres such as tango and [[klezmer]] as well as various Arabic, Balkan, Gypsy and [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] folk forms. Atzmon's recordings deliberately differ from his live shows. \"I don't think that anyone can sit in a house, at home, and listen to me play a full-on bebop solo. It's too intense. My albums need to be less manic.\"<ref name=Lewis/>\n\n===Collaborations and groups===\nAtzmon joined the veteran [[punk rock]] band [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] in 1998, and continued with the Blockheads after Dury's death.<ref>Stephen Robb, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6253257.stm \"The old Blockheads shows go on\"], [[BBC News]], 25 January 2007.</ref><ref>Sara Greek, [http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm Blockheads come to Hertford Corn Exchange] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206100511/http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Whats-On-Leisure/Music/Blockheads-come-to-Hertford-Corn-Exchange-28102011.htm |date=6 December 2013 }}, [[Hertfordshire Mercury]], 28 October 2011.</ref> He has recorded and performed with [[Shane MacGowan]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]], [[Robert Wyatt]] and [[Paul McCartney]].<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/><ref name=\"Atzmonhomepage\"/> He has recorded two albums with Robert Wyatt, who describes him as \"one of the few musical geniuses I've ever met\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has collaborated, recorded and performed with musicians from all around the world, including the Palestinian singer, [[Reem Kelani]], Tunisian singer and [[oud]] player [[Dhafer Youssef]], violinist Marcel Mamaliga, accordion player Romano Viazzani, bassist Yaron Stavi, violinist and trumpet-violin player, Dumitru Ovidiu Fratila, and Guillermo Rozenthuler on vocals.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> He played tenor saxophone and clarinet on one track, \"Anisina\", on the 2014 Pink Floyd album, ''[[The Endless River]]''. He has worked with leading bands as a musical producer.<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], [http://www.tourdates.co.uk/ London Tour Dates], 5 October 2007.</ref>\n\nAtzmon founded the Orient House Ensemble band in London in 2000 with [[Asaf Sirkis]] on drums, Frank Harrison on piano and Oli Hayhurst on bass. In 2003 Yaron Stavi replaced Hayhurst. In 2009 Eddie Hick replaced Sirkis.<ref name=Ensemble>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/the-orient-house-ensemble/ Orient House Ensemble description at Gilad Atzmon home page.]</ref><ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/14/asaf-sirkis-letting-go-review Asaf Sirkis Trio: Letting Go \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 14 October 2010.</ref>  The group was named after [[Orient House]], the former [[East Jerusalem]] headquarters of the [[Palestine Liberation Organization]], later seized by the [[Israeli Defense Forces]].<ref name=Searle>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 Gilad Atzmon and The Orient House Ensemble] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107195523/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/97593 |date=7 November 2017 }}, [[Morning Star (UK newspaper)]], 14 November 2011.</ref><ref>Jack Massarik, \"Gilad Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble\", [[Evening Standard]], 16 January 2006.</ref> The band has recorded eight albums. Orient House announced a 40-date tour in 2010.<ref name=Searle/><ref name=Fordham>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/05/gilad-atzmon-orient-house-ensemble-review Gilad Atzmon Orient House Ensemble \u2013 review], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 5 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Robert Wyatt]], who has said that Atzmon combines \"great artistry with a sense of the intrinsically non-racialist philosophy that's implicit in jazz,\"<ref>Lester Paul [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/26/best-band-rock-pop \"So who is top of the pops\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 26 June 2010.</ref> worked with Atzmon and others on his album ''[[Comicopera]]'' (2007).<ref>Chris Jones, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/gwcz A national treasure makes another peerless album], [[BBC]], 5 October 2007.</ref> Wyatt collaborated with Atzmon and Ros Stephens, as well as lyricist [[Alfreda Benge]], on the album ''For the Ghosts Within'' (2010), released on [[Domino Recording Company|Domino Records]].<ref>Andy Gill, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-wyatt--atzmon--stephen-for-the-ghosts-within-domino-2102994.html Album: Wyatt, Atzmon, Stephen, For The Ghosts Within (Domino)], [[The Independent]], 8 October 2011.</ref><ref>Alex Hudson, [https://exclaim.ca/music/article/robert_wyatt_unveils_new_collaborative_album \"Robert Wyatt Unveils New Collaborative Album\"], [[Exclaim!]], 8 July 2010</ref>\n\nAtzmon produced and arranged two albums for [[Sarah Gillespie]] ''Stalking Juliet ''(2009) and ''In The Current Climate ''(2011). Both albums were critically acclaimed.<ref name=\"Guardian\">John Fordham [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/apr/10/sarah-gillespie-stalking-juliet-review \"Stalking Juliet review\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 April 2009</ref><ref name=\"Mail\">{{Cite web |url=http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday |title=\"Current Climate Review\", ''Mail on Sunday'', January 2011. |access-date=15 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826172200/http://sarahgillespie.com/reviews/the-mail-on-sunday/ |archive-date=26 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has toured extensively as a member of Sarah Gillespie's band, playing saxophone, clarinet and accordion.<ref name=\"Metro\">[http://www.metro.co.uk/music/852007-jazz-your-cd-collection-up \"Robert Shaw, Guitarist Keeps Her Finger on the Pulse\"], Metro.co.uk, 6 January 2011.</ref>\n\nAtzmon is on the creative panel of the [[Global Music Foundation]],<ref name=\"GMF-GA\"/> a non-profit organization formed in December 2004 which runs residential educational and performance workshops and events in different countries around the world.<ref name=\"GMF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalmusicfoundation.org/people/gilad-atzmon/|title=Gilad mAtzmon|accessdate=23 October 2017|publisher=Global Music Foundation}}</ref> and also offers personal workshops to students.<ref name=\"Atzmon-Workshop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/education-1/|title=MUSIC EDUCATION|accessdate=3 January 2018|last=Atzmon|first=Gilad|year=2015|publisher=Gilad Atzmon}}</ref> A musical transcription of ten saxophone solos by Atzmon was released in 2010.<ref>Chris Gumbley, [http://www.gumblespublications.co.uk/saxophone-solos/ Gilad Uncovered: 10 Transcriptions], Gumbles Publications, 2010.</ref>\n\n===Reviews and awards===\nAtzmon and his ensemble have received favorable reviews from the ''[[Financial Times]]'', ''[[The Scotsman]]'', ''[[Birmingham Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Bacon|first=Peter|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CULTURE%3A+Arts+reviews%3A+Activist+with+quotes+and+plenty+to+say%3B+Gilad...-a0127526728|title=Activist with quotes and plenty to say; Gilad Atzmon CBSO Centre|work=Birmingham Post| date=24 January 2005|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''.<ref>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon web site].</ref> Reviews of his 2007 album ''Refuge'' included:\n:''[[Manchester Evening News]]'': \"The individuality of the music is extraordinary. No one is more willing to serve his music with raw political passion, and that curious [[Hazzan|cantor]]-like tone on clarinet is immediately arresting, like [[Artie Shaw]] writhing in his death throes.\"<ref>Alan Brownlee, [http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/entertainment/music/world_music/s/1015/1015003_gilad_atzmon__the_orient_house_ensemble__refuge_enja.html Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble&nbsp;\u2013 Refuge (Enja)], [[Manchester Evening News]], 30 August 2007.</ref>\n:[[BBC]]: \"...the OHE is finding its voice in an increasingly subtle blend of East and West, that\u2019s brutal and beautiful.\"<ref>Kathryn Shackleton, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/release/5vp2/ Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble, Refuge], [[BBC]], 1 October 2007.</ref>\n\nIn February 2009 ''[[The Guardian]]'' jazz critic [[John Fordham (jazz critic)|John Fordham]] reviewed Atzmon's newest album ''In loving memory of America'' which was described by Atzmon as \"a memory of America I had cherished in my mind for many years\". It includes five standards and six originals \"inspired by the sumptuous harmonies and impassioned sax-playing of [[Charlie Parker|(Charlie) Parker]]'s late-40s recordings with classical strings\".<ref>John Fordham, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/27/gilad-atzmon-loving-memory-america \"Gilad Atzmon: In Loving Memory of America\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 27 February 2009.</ref> Music journalist John Lewis has praised much of Atzmon's work and described Atzmon as \"one of London's finest saxophonists\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon was the recipient of the [[HMV]] ''Top Dog Award'' at the [[Jazz of Birmingham|Birmingham International Jazz Festival]] in 1996\u201398.<ref name=\"RainLore bio\"/> Gilad Atzmon's ''Exile'' was BBC jazz album of the year in 2003.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/low/entertainment/3107607.stm Jazz winners span generations], BBC, 30 July 2003.</ref>\n\n==Writings==\nAtzmon has defined himself variously as a \"[[secular Jew]]\",<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> a \"proud self-hating Jew\"  in the style of [[Otto Weininger]],<ref name=\"Panayides\" >Theo Panayides, [https://web.archive.org/web/20100223072804/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/living/wandering-jazz-player/20100221 'Wandering jazz player,'], [[Cyprus Mail]], 21 February 2010: \"My ethical duty is to say the things that I know and feel. I\u2019m an artist. Do you know.. this is something I learned from Otto Weininger, the Austrian philosopher. He was a clever boy, killed himself when he was 21. ..He was definitely a proud self-hating Jew! I\u2019m not a self-hating Jew: I\u2019m a proud self-hating Jew! It\u2019s a big difference\u2026 I celebrate my hatred towards everything I represent \u2013 or better to say [everything] I\u2019m associated with\".</ref> an \"ex-Jew\",<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/a-new-jewish-goal-by-gilad-atzmon.html A New Jewish Goal], at his personal web site.</ref> \"a Jew who hates Judaism\",<ref>{{cite news|last=\u05d7\u05dc\u05d9\u05dc\u05d9|first=\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d1|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d8\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d2\u05dc\u05e2\u05d3 \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d5\u05df|url=http://article.yedioth.co.il/default.aspx?articleid=5448|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=9 November 2011|language=Hebrew|quote=\u05d3\u05d5\u05d5\u05e7\u05d0 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d0 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea, \u05d0\u05e0\u05d9 \u05e9\u05dd \u05d0\u05ea \u05e2\u05e6\u05de\u05d9 \u05ea\u05d7\u05ea \u05d6\u05db\u05d5\u05db\u05d9\u05ea \u05de\u05d2\u05d3\u05dc\u05ea \u05d5\u05d1\u05d5\u05d7\u05df \u05db\u05dc \u05d0\u05e1\u05e4\u05e7\u05d8 \u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9 \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05db\u05d9. (As a Jew who hates Judaism, I put myself under a magnifying glass and examine every Jewish aspect in me).}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halily|first=Yaniv|title=The protocols of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4147243,00.html|accessdate=1 August 2013|newspaper=Yediot Ahronot|date=14 November 2011}}</ref> and \"a Hebrew-speaking Palestinian\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/>\n\nAtzmon writes and edits for the website, Palestine Think Tank.<ref name=Lewis/> He told interviewer [[Theo Panayides]]: \"I don't write about politics, I write about ethics. I write about Identity. I write a lot about the [[Jewish Question]]&nbsp;\u2013 because I was born in the Jew-land, and my whole process in maturing into an adult was involved with the realisation that my people are living on stolen land.\"<ref name=\"Panayides\"/> Atzmon has said that his experience in the military of \"my people destroying other people left a big scar\" and led to his decision that he was deluded about Zionism. He has condemned \"Jewishness\" as \"very much a supremacist, racist tendency\", but he has also stated that \"I don't have anything against Jews in particular and you won't find that in my writings\".<ref name=\"gilchrist222\"/> Regarding the one-state solution, Atzmon concedes that such a state probably would be controlled by [[Islamist]]s, but says, \"That's their business\".<ref name=Lewis/>\n\nAtzmon has compared \"the Jewish Ideology\" to that of the [[Nazis]] and has described Israel's policy toward the Palestinians as [[genocide]].<ref name=\"gibson\"/> [[David Hirst (journalist)|David Hirst]], in his 2003 book ''The Gun and the Olive Branch,'' quotes Atzmon as saying America was \"about to lose its sovereignty...becoming a remote colony of an apparently far greater state, the Jewish state.\u201d<ref>David Hirst, ''The Gun and the Olive Branch: the roots of violence in the Middle East,'' Nation Books, 2003, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Oisa_1Dc69kC&pg=PA49&dq=gun+and+olive+branch+atzmon&hl=en&ei=ZgdFTM-YAsP98Abntc3aAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCUQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 49]</ref> In 2009, [[Turkey|Turkish]] Prime Minister [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]] cited Atzmon's written comment \"Israeli barbarity is far beyond even ordinary cruelty\" during a debate with Israeli president [[Shimon Peres]].<ref name=\"Lewis\"/>\n\n===Novels===\nAtzmon's ''[[A Guide to the Perplexed]]'', published in 2001, is set in a 2052 in which Israel has been replaced by a Palestinian state. It largely reviews memoirs of the alienated Israeli Gunther Wunker's rise to fame as a \"peepologist\", or voyeur. The perplexed are defined as \"the unthinking Chosen\" who \"cling to clods of earth that don't belong to them.\" The novel excoriates what it describes as the commercialization of the Holocaust and \"argues that the Holocaust is invoked as a kind of reflexive propaganda designed to shield the Zionist state from responsibility for any transgression against Palestinians.\"<ref name=\"St. Clair\">[[Jeffrey St. Clair]],[https://www.counterpunch.org/2003/07/17/gilad-atzmon-s-a-guide-to-the-perplexed/ 'Gilad Atzmon's \"A Guide to the Perplexed\",'] [[CounterPunch]] 17 July 2003</ref>\n\nMatthew J. Reisz, a reviewer for ''[[The Independent]]'', wrote that \"As a viciously black satire on Israeli life\" the book \"is grandiose, childish and nasty, but with just enough connection with reality to give it a certain unsettling power\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Reisz|first=Matthew J.|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-guide-to-the-perplexed-by-gilad-atzmon-trans-philip-simpson-609999.html|title=A Guide to the Perplexed, by Gilad Atzmon, trans. Philip Simpson|work=The Independent|date=7 December 2002|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2020}} Darren King in ''[[The Observer]]'' noted of this \"provocative debut novel\" that it is \"odd to mix knob gags with highly serious assertions\", but thought it works because \"Atzmon writes with so much style and his gags are so hilarious\".<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Darren|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/jan/25/featuresreviews.guardianreview16|title=Mr. Peepology|work=The Observer|date=25 January 2003|accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', \"Atzmon clearly wants to provoke, but his approach is so familiar that few readers will take the bait.\".<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-85242-826-6 \"A Guide to the Perplexed\"], ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'', 31 March 2003.</ref>\n\nAtzmon's second novel, ''My One and Only Love'', was published in 2005 and features as a protagonist a trumpeter who chooses to play only one note (extremely well), as well as a spy who uncovers Nazi war criminals and locks them inside double bass cases which then tour permanently in the protagonist's orchestra's luggage.<ref>Sholto Byrnes. [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/talking-jazz-529796.html \"Talking Jazz\"], ''The Independent'', 25 March 2005</ref> The book is also a comedic take on \"Zionist espionage and intrigue\" which explores \"the personal conflict between being true to one\u2019s heart and being loyal to The Jews\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/cambridgeshire/content/articles/2004/10/01/gilad_event_feature.shtml \"Gilad Atzmon's Orient House Ensemble \u2013 The Junction\"], BBC Cambridgeshire, 3 June 2005.</ref>\n\n===''The Wandering Who?''===\nIn 2011, [[Zero Books]] published Atzmon's book ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics'', stating that it \"examines Jewish identity politics and Jewish contemporary ideology using both popular culture and scholarly texts.\"<ref name = WanderingBook>Gilad Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=rTbtBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT7&lpg=PT7 ''The Wandering Who? A Study of Jewish Identity Politics''], Zero Books, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-84694-875-6}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jean Bricmont]], in his preface for the French edition, ''La Parabole d\u2019Esther'', Atzmon starts by making three definitions of the word 'Jewish': (a) it may refer to adherents of Judaism, and he has no quarrel with them; (b) secondly, it may refer to ethnic Jews, and, likewise, he sees no problem in that; (c) thirdly, it can refer to a third category, those who, without being particularly religious, place great emphasis on their Jewish \"identity\" as something more important than their basic membership of the human race.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" >[[Jean Bricmont]], [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/counterpunch-print-edition-in-defense-of-gilad-atzmon-by-jea.html  'In Defense of Gilad Atzmon By Jean Bricmont,'] Counterpunch April 2012 print edition, cited on Atzmon's blog.</ref> Bricmont then adds that it is very easy to mount a case to 'prove' Atzmon is an antisemite by consistently construing his criticisms of (c) as though they were aimed as (a) or (b) or both.<ref name=\"Bricmont\" /> \n\n[[Marc H. Ellis]],  professor of Jewish studies at [[Baylor University]], likens Atzmon's rhetorical extremism and harsh censure of Jews to the [[Prophet|prophetic voices]] of the [[Old Testament]], arguing that, for Atzmon, [[Diaspora|diasporic]] Jews are asked to construct their identity on the basis of the [[State of Israel]] and the [[Holocaust]], an identity he regards as without foundation. He adds that Atzmon considers charges that he is antisemitic as 'last ditch attempts' to validate that identity. In Ellis's view, there may be, in the perceived anxiety in these repeated attacks, a reflection of the same anxiety Atzmon himself arguably embodies.<ref name=\"Ellis\" >[[Marc H. Ellis]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=doN-AwAAQBAJ&dq=Marc+Ellis%2BGilad+Atzmon&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y  ''Future of the Prophetic: Israel's Ancient Wisdom Re-presented,''] [[Fortress Press]], 2014 pp.331\u2013332.</ref><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/the-new-jewish-prophet.html  'The New Jewish Prophet,'] 24 June 2014.</ref> {{efn|Ellis also notes that Atzmon considers the bible 'bogus'.<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> Atzmon himself cites evidence 600 passages in the OT are violent, and argues that this 'lethal spirit of the scriptures has infused the essence of modern Jewish political discourse,' underwriting in his view even the secular mindset of military commanders conducting war in Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.<ref>G. Atzmon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C&pg=PA122 ''The Wandering Who,''] 2011 p.122.</ref>}}\n\nTen authors published by Zero Books, including [[Laurie Penny]] and [[Richard Seymour (writer)|Richard Seymour]], criticised the publisher publicly for releasing the book, arguing:<blockquote>The thrust of Atzmon's work is to normalise and legitimise anti-Semitism. We do not believe that Zero's decision to publish this book is malicious. Atzmon's ability to solicit endorsements from respectable figures such as [[Richard Falk]] and [[John Mearsheimer]] shows that he is adept at muddying the waters both on his own views and on the question of anti-Semitism. But at a time when dangerous forces are attempting to racialise political antagonisms, we think the decision is grossly mistaken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leninology.blogspot.com/2011/09/zero-authors-statement-on-gilad-atzmon.html|title=Zero Authors Statement on Gilad Atzmon|publisher=Lenin's Tomb|date=26 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nMearsheimer has said that \"There is no question that the book is provocative, both in terms of its central argument and the overly hot language that Atzmon sometimes uses. But it is also filled with interesting insights that make the reader think long and hard about an important subject.\"<ref>Stephen Walt, [http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], ''[[Foreign Policy]]'', 26 September 2011.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The New Republic]]'', [[Alan Dershowitz]] criticized Mearsheimer and Falk for recommending the book<ref name=\"Dershowitz\">Alan Dershowitz, [http://www.tnr.com/article/politics/97030/atzmon-wandering-who-anti-semitism-israel \"Why are John Mearsheimer and Richard Falk Endorsing a Blatantly Anti-Semitic Book?\"], ''The New Republic'', 4 November 2011.</ref> and challenged them to a public debate.<ref name=\"Dershowitz\"/> Falk rejected Dershowitz's call to debate.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} Atzmon offered to debate Dershowitz at \"any time\".<ref>Gilad Atzmon at Gilad Atzmon website, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/dershowitz-lies-and-glitches-by-gilad-atzmon.html Dershowitz\u2019 Lies and Glitches], 9 November 2011 and [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/if-dershowitz-wants-a-debate-i-will-meet-him-any-time.html \"If Dershowitz Wants a Debate, I Will Meet Him Any Time\"], 23 October 2011.</ref> He called various criticisms \"a typical [[Hasbara]] smear & intimidation campaign.\u201d<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/goldberg-vs-mearsheimer-by-gilad-atzmon.html Goldberg vs. Mearsheimer], Gilad Atzmon website, 25 September 2011.</ref> Atzmon replied to the MacDonald review referenced by Dershowitz, writing that his book \"is a study of Jewish identity politics and Jewish culture, it is not concerned with Jewish ethnicity or racial origins.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-supremacists-on-the-wandering-who.html \"Supremacists on 'The Wandering Who'\"], Gilad.co.uk, 7 October 2011.</ref>\n\n==Allegations of antisemitism==\nSeveral of Atzmon's statements regarding Jews and Judaism have led to allegations of antisemitism. \n\n===Campaigners===\nThe [[Anti-Defamation League]] describes Atzmon as \"antisemitic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/profiles/gilad-atzmon|title=Gilad Atzmon|publisher=ADL|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[Hope not Hate]] called for the cancellation of an Atzmon performance at the \"Raise Your Banners\" festival of political song.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1487/pull-the-plug-on-gilad-atzmon|title=Pull the plug on Gilad Atzmon|work=Hope not Hate|date=21 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127145630/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1487/pull-the-plug-on-gilad-atzmon|archive-date=27 November 2013}}</ref> Bradford's Trades Union Council also condemned the appearance and the Board of Deputies of British Jews asked the [[Arts Council England|Arts Council]], which had funded the festival, to stop it.<ref name=Griffiths>Kathie Griffiths, [http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/9376005.Jazz_saxophonist_Gilad_Atzmon_at_centre_of_Raise_Your_Banners_festival_row/ \"Calls for musician's show to be cancelled\"], ''[[Telegraph & Argus]]'', 22 November 2011.</ref> [[Gerry Sutcliffe]], Labour MP for [[Bradford South (UK Parliament constituency)|Bradford South]], and the Right Reverend [[David Ison]], then Dean of Bradford Cathedral also called for the festival to rescind their invitation.<ref>Simon Rocker, [http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/58942/more-calls-gilad-atzmon-concert-ban More calls for Gilad Atzmon concert ban], [[The Jewish Chronicle]], 24 November 2011.</ref> The Arts Council refused the request, while the festival director said organisers did not believe the claims. Atzmon said the Trade Union Council's letter \"stitched together\u201d phrases from five separate paragraphs into one quote to make him look racist, and demanded an apology.<ref name=Griffiths/>  \n\nIn ''Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today,'' published in 2012 by Hope not Hate, [[Nick Lowles]] wrote: \"Despite being Jewish himself, Atzmon has promoted Holocaust deniers and claims that the established history of the Holocaust is misleading. He attacks Jewish identity in a way that would clearly be recognised as racist if it were about any other minority identity and claims that people might think that Hitler was right about the Jews because of their behaviour today. He tells crude antisemitic jokes and mocks any concerns about antisemitism.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Rewriting History: Holocaust Revisionism Today|url=http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111105903/http://www.hopenothate.org.uk/blog/article/1493/gilad-atzmon-supporting-holocaust-deniers-and-spreading-hatr|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-01-11|date=December 2012|publisher=[[Hope not Hate]]|page=9|accessdate=14 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\nIn 2005, [[David Aaronovitch]] criticized Atzmon's essay \"On Anti-Semitism\", for defending [[Israel Shamir]], circulating an essay by Paul Eisen defending [[Holocaust denier]] [[Ernst Z\u00fcndel]]'s right to think, speak, and write as he pleases, and for supporting many aspects of Z\u00fcndel's Holocaust denial theories.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\">{{cite news|last=Aaronovitch|first=David|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/how-did-the-far-left-manage-to-slip-into-bed-with-the-jew-hating-right-766cbwpdqfd|title=How did the far Left manage to slip into bed with the Jew-hating Right?|work=The Times|location=London|date=28 June 2005|accessdate=24 February 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"onanti\">Gilad Atzmon, {{cite web|url=http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |title=On Anti-Semitism |accessdate=27 July 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050213011436/http://www.gilad.co.uk/html%20files/onanti.html |archivedate=13 February 2005 }}, originally at his personal web site, 20 December 2003.</ref>\n\nIn a 2006 piece in ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[David Hirsh]] also criticized Atzmon's \"On Anti-Semitism\" essay, and particularly its [[Jewish deicide]] claim, as an example of Atzmon's \"openly anti-Jewish rhetoric.\"<ref>Hirsh, David. [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/nov/30/anewmenacingcurrentisappe Openly embracing prejudice], ''The Guardian'', 30 November 2006. Hirsh also refers to the statement in [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/apr/03/nobodyhaseverclaimedthatc \"What charge?\"], \"The Guardian\", 3 April 2006.</ref> In response to a question about this quote from [[Lenni Brenner]], Atzmon replied that he meant \"I find it astonishing that people today happen to be offended by such accusations.\"<ref>[https://www.counterpunch.org/2007/02/15/quot-do-i-look-like-the-pope-quot/ \"Are You a Christian?\" \"Do I Look Like the Pope?\"&nbsp;\u2013 An Exchange Between Lenni Brenner & Gilad Atzmon], ''[[CounterPunch]]'', 15 February 2007.</ref>\n\n[[Nick Cohen]], in a 2009 piece for ''[[The Observer]]'', criticised Atzmon.<ref name=\"Cohen\">Nick Cohen [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/jun/14/james-von-brunn-far-right \"The unlikely friends of the Holocaust memorial killer\"], ''The Observer'', 14 June 2009</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 blog for ''[[The Times]]'', [[Oliver Kamm]] charged Atzmon with antisemitism for his article \"Truth, History and Integrity\".<ref>Oliver Kamm, [http://timesonline.typepad.com/oliver_kamm/2010/03/an-antisemites-progress.html An antisemite's progress] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100329214204/http://timesonline.typepad.com/oliver_kamm/2010/03/an-antisemites-progress.html |date=29 March 2010 }}, ''The Times'', 26 March 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Keith Kahn-Harris]] argues that Atzmon's view of the world in ''Being In Time'' (2017) is inherently antisemitic. Kahn-Harris describes Atzmon as \"deliberately apathetic about the Holocaust and other atrocities against Jews, nodding towards without completely embracing both justification and denial\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Kahn-Harris|first=Keith|url=https://forward.com/opinion/389696/cloaked-in-pretensions-gilad-atzmons-anti-semitism-soldiers-on/|title=Cloaked In Pretensions, Gilad Atzmon\u2019s Anti-Semitism Soldiers On|work=Forward|date=10 December 2017|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Anti-Zionists===\nIn September 2011 trade unionist and blogger Andy Newman<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/andy-newman Andy Newman profile] on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website</ref> writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'' described his writing as \"anti-Jewish hate-speech\". In his view, Atzmon's political writing are \"a wild conspiracy argument, dripping with contempt for Jews\".<ref name=\"Newman\">Andy Newman [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/sep/25/gilad-atzmon-antisemitism-the-left?newsfeed=true \"Gilad Atzmon, antisemitism and the left\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 25 September 2011.</ref> In a letter printed by the ''Guardian'', Atzmon wrote that Newman had \"misrepresented\" his views and that \"how to define a Jew is a loaded topic since Jews define themselves in many different ways, some contradictory, and use those definitions to try to achieve political aims.\"<ref>Gilad Atzmon [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/sep/28/moral-obligation-and-jewish-identity?newsfeed=true Letter: Moral obligation and Jewish identity], ''The Guardian'', 28 September 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2011, David Landy, an Irish academic and former chair of the Ireland Palestine Solidarity Campaign, wrote that Atzmon's words, \"if not actually anti-Semitic, certainly border on it\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Landy|first=David|title=Jewish Identity and Palestinian Rights: Disapora Jewish Opposition to Israel|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84813-926-8|page=167}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Community Security Trust]] report on antisemitic discourse in the UK in 2011 described Atzmon as increasingly regarded among anti-Zionists as an unwelcome antisemite: \"Atzmon's analysis of Jewish history, identity and culture introduces an unusually explicit and quite new antisemitism into far left-wing politics. Leading Jewish anti-Zionist figures have denounced Atzmon as an antisemite. Most anti-Zionists have followed suit and now also condemn Atzmon, but some factional splits have occurred due to a minority of activists defending him.<ref>{{cite web|title=Antisemitic Discourse in Britain in 2011|url=https://cst.org.uk/docs/Antisemitic%20Discourse%20Report%202011%20WEB.pdf|date=November 2012|publisher=Community Standard Trust|page=30|accessdate=3 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nA group of leading Palestinian activists issued a statement in March 2012 calling for \"the disavowal of Atzmon by fellow Palestinian organizers, as well as Palestine solidarity activists, and allies of the Palestinian people\". The statement affirmed that \"we regard any attempt to link and adopt antisemitic or racist language, even if it is within a self-described anti-imperialist and anti-Zionist politics, as reaffirming and legitimizing Zionism.\" Signatories included [[Ali Abunimah]], [[Naseer Aruri]], [[Omar Barghouti]], [[Nadia Hijab]], [[Joseph Massad]].<ref name=Disavow/><ref>{{cite web|title=Granting No Quarter: A Call for the Disavowal of the Racism and Antisemitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://uspcn.org/2012/03/13/granting-no-quarter-a-call-for-the-disavowal-of-the-racism-and-antisemitism-of-gilad-atzmon|publisher=US Palestinian Community Network|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Palestinian activists disavow Israeli musician Atzmon|url=https://www.jta.org/2012/03/14/news-opinion/united-states/palestinian-activists-disavow-israeli-musician-atzmon|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|accessdate=3 January 2018|date=14 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Palestinian writers, activists disavow racism, anti-Semitism of Gilad Atzmon|url=http://www.electronicintifada.net/blogs/ali-abunimah/palestinian-writers-activists-disavow-racism-anti-semitism-gilad-atzmon|date=13 March 2012|publisher=Electronic Intifada|accessdate= 25 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maannews.net/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?ID=467843|title=Palestinian writers disavow Gilad Atzmon|date=14 March 2012|publisher= Maan News Agency|accessdate=25 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Comments at talk===\nAt a talk by Richard Falk at [[London School of Economics|LSE]] in March 2017, which was being disrupted by protestors, Atzmon was alleged to have commented that Jews had been \"expelled from Germany for misbehaving\" and that people should read Holocaust denier [[David Irving]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/jewish-students-told-dont-study-at-lse-by-board-president/|title=Jewish students told 'don\u2019t study at LSE' by Board president|work=Jewish News Online|date=23 March 2017|access-date=22 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Responses===\nAtzmon refers to charges of antisemitism as being a \"common Zionist silencing apparatus.\"<ref>Barnaby Smith, [https://archive.today/20130114032502/http://www.tourdates.co.uk/LondonTourdates/issue-007/2007/10/05/222-Sax-With-An-Axe-To-Grind Sax With An Axe To Grind], Interview with Gilad Atzmon in ''London Tour Dates'' magazine, 5 October 2006</ref> He denies that he is an antisemite and states that, \"Because 'Anti-Semite' is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have.\"<ref name=1001Lies>[http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/1001-lies-about-gilad-atzmon.html 1001 Lies About Gilad Atzmon,'] Gilad Atzmon com. 18 June 2011 \"I am an anti Zionist and oppose the Zionist mindset. I look at questions of Jewish identity and I do question the ties between a Jewish world view and Zionism. I refute totally that I am anti-Semite. In fact I also believe that the current concept of an Anti-Semitism is meaningless. Once the Zionists had managed to establish their Jewish state, any form of anti Jewish sentiments should be comprehended either as a private case of xenophobia or as a political retaliation to Israeli/Zionist atrocities. In other words, the title Anti-Semite became an \u2018empty signifier, i.e. a signifier with a vague, highly variable, unspecifiable or non-existent signified. It is an empty verbal utterance that exists merely to serve a political cause (very much like Blair\u2019s WMD and Bush\u2019s Axis of Evil). Because Anti-Semite is an empty signifier, no one actually can be an Anti-Semite and this includes me of course. In short, you are either a racist which I am not or have an ideological disagreement with Zionism, which I have\".</ref> In 2009, Atzmon said \"I've got nothing against the Semite people, I don't have anything against people&nbsp;\u2014 I'm anti-Jewish, not anti-Jews.\"<ref name=\"gibson\">Gibson, Martin. \"No choice but to speak out&nbsp;\u2014 Israeli musician 'a proud self-hating Jew'\", ''The Gisborne Herald'', 23 January 2009.</ref> He added that \"Stupidly we interpreted the Nazi defeat as a vindication of the Jewish ideology and the Jewish people\"; however, \"in fact Jewish ideology and Nazi ideology were very similar.\"<ref name=\"gibson\"/> Atzmon has also stated that he does not deny the Holocaust or the \"Nazi Judeocide\u201d but insists \"that both the Holocaust and World War II should be treated as historical events rather than as religious myth. ... But then, even if we accept the Holocaust as the new Anglo-American liberal-democratic religion, we must allow people to be atheists.\u201d<ref name=\"Beauty\" >{{cite web|url=http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|title=Beauty as a political weapon; Three in one: jazzman, writer and activist&nbsp;\u2013 A conversation with Gilad Atzmon|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080403072556/http://www.redress.btinternet.co.uk/gatzmon14.htm|archivedate=3 April 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Talens\" >[[:es:Manuel Talens|Manuel Talens]],  [http://www.rebelion.org/noticia.php?id=24333 'La belleza como arma pol\u00edtica,'] [[Rebelion.org]] 19 December 2005,</ref> Atzmon has said his statements have lost him performance contracts, especially in the United States.<ref>Karen Abi-Ezzi, \"Music as a Discourse of Resistance: The Case of Gilad Atzmon\u201d, Chapter 7 of Olivier Urbain, Editor, ''Music and conflict transformation: harmonies and dissonances in geopolitics'', I.B. Tauris, 2008  [https://books.google.com/books?id=oMLkUmraBCAC&pg=PA101&dq=urbain+atzmon+contracts&hl=en&ei=2wpFTPf2C8P88Ab03uDKDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false p. 101].</ref> Atzmon has had conflicts with anti-Zionists who have attempted to stop his performances.<ref name=\"Aaronovitch\"/><ref>Gilad Atzmon, [http://www.gilad.co.uk/writings/gilad-atzmon-lieberman-and-the-jewish-political-continuum.html \"Gilad Atzmon: Lieberman and the Jewish Political Continuum\"], at Gilad Atzmon's web site, 10 October 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Oren Ben-Dor]] wrote in 2008 \"I am firmly convinced that these vulgar attempts at silencing of Gilad and other courageous voices offends against supremely thoughtful, compassionate and egalitarian intellectual endeavours.\"<ref>[[Oren Ben-Dor]], [https://www.counterpunch.org/2008/03/15/the-silencing-of-gilad-atzmon/ 'The Silencing of Gilad Atzmon'], [[CounterPunch]], 15 March 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, reviewer [[Chris Searle]] defended accusations against Atzmon's \"crude anti-zionist rhetoric\u201d, writing \"No jazz musicians have done more to honour, publicise and spread solidarity with the struggle of the Palestinians than Atzmon and the Orient House Ensemble.\u201d<ref>Chris Searle, [http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 Review of the book ''Jazz Jews'' by Mike Gerber] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023175013/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/86692 |date=23 October 2017 }}, ''[[Morning Star (UK newspaper)|Morning Star]]'', February 2010.</ref> \n\nIn 2011, [[John Mearsheimer]] defended Atzmon, writing with regard to the charge that Atzmon is antisemitic, \"to be perfectly clear, he has no animus toward Judaism as a religion or with individuals who are Jewish by birth. Rather, his target is the tribalism that he believes is common to most Jews, and I might add, to most other peoples as well. ... The more important and interesting issue is whether Atzmon is a self-hating Jew. Here the answer is unequivocally yes.\" \n\n[[Richard Falk]] described Atzmon \"a de-Zionized patriot of humanity\".<ref>Stephen M. Walt,[http://walt.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/09/25/mearsheimer_responds_to_goldbergs_latest_smear \"Mearsheimer responds to Goldberg's latest smear\"], 26 September 2011 (posted on Walt.Foreignpolicy.com)</ref> \n\nIn 2012, [[Norton Mezvinsky]] wrote that \"Gilad Atzmon is a critical and committed secular humanist with firm views, who delights in being provocative.\"<ref>[[Norton Mezvinsky]], [http://wrmea.org/archives/507-washington-report-archives-2011-2015/may-2012/11161-gilad-atzmon-and-the-wandering-who.html Gilad Atzmon and The Wandering Who?], [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.wrmea.org/action-alert-archives/11194-engaging-gilad-atzmon.html 'Engaging Gilad Atzmon], video of Norton Mezvinsky interview with Gilad Atzmon,' [[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]], May 2012.</ref>\n\n==Libel suit==\nIn July 2018, Atzmon issued an apology to Gideon Falter, the chairman of the [[Campaign Against Antisemitism]] after being sued for libel. Atzmon had alleged that Falter had personally profited from fabricating antisemitic incidents. He was also liable for legal costs and damages.<ref name=\"Libel\">{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Ben |title=Gilad Atzmon is forced to apologise to CAA's Gideon Falter over libel |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/gideon-falter-gilad-atzmon-1.466405 |accessdate=3 July 2018 |work=The Jewish Chronicle |date=2 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CAA\">{{cite web |title=Antisemitic author and saxophonist Gilad Atzmon capitulates, making humiliating apology and paying substantial damages and costs after just two hours in court against CAA |url=https://antisemitism.uk/antisemitic-author-and-saxophonist-gilad-atzmon-capitulates-making-humiliating-apology-and-paying-substantial-damages-and-costs-after-just-two-hours-in-court-against-caa/ |website=antisemitism.uk |publisher=Campaign Against Antisemitism |accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''The Spirit of Trane'' (Fanfare Jazz, 2017)\n*''World Peace Trio'' (Enja, 2017)\n*''Songs of the Metropolis'' (World Village, 2013)\n*''The Tide Has Changed'' (World Village, 2010)\n*''In Loving Memory of America'' (Enja, 2009)\n*''Refuge'' (Enja, 2007)\n*''Artie Fishel and the Promised Band'' (WMD, 2006)\n*''MusiK'' (Enja, 2004)<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/oct/08/jazz.shopping1</ref>\n*''Exile'' (Enja, 2004)\n*''Nostalgico'' (Enja, 2001)\n*''Gilad Atzmon & The Orient House Ensemble'' (Enja, 2000)\n*''Juizz Muzic'' (FruitBeard, 1999)\n*''Take It or Leave It'' (Face Jazz, 1997)\n*''Spiel: Both Sides'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel Acid Jazz Band'' (MCI, 1995)\n*''Spiel'' (In Acoustic & H.M. Acoustica, 1993)\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |title=[[A Guide to the Perplexed]] |translator= Philip Simpson |location=London|publisher=[[Serpent's Tail]] |year=2002 |isbn=1-85242-826-0}}\n*''My one and only love''. London: Saqi Books, 2005. {{ISBN|0-86356-507-7}} (pbk.). {{ISBN|978-0-86356-507-6}} (pbk.)\n*{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=028jkw0GVY4C| title=The Wandering Who?: A Study of Jewish Identity Politics |publisher=[[John Hunt Publishing|Zero Books]] |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-84694-875-6}}\n* ''A to Zion: The Definitive Israeli Lexicon''. London, Fanfare Press, 2015.{{ISBN|978-0993183706}} (pbk.). \n*''Being in Time: A Post-Political Manifesto'', Newbold on Stour, Warwickshire: Skyscraper Publications, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1911072201}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Brian Lenzo, [http://www.palestinechronicle.com/old/view_article_details.php?id=16132 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed: Each Village is a Reminder], originally published by Socialist Worker Online, 13 July 2010 (reprinted by the Palestine Chronicle).\n*Alan Maass, [https://socialistworker.org/2010/07/14/an-article-retracted An Article Retracted], Socialist Worker Online, 14 July 2010 (retraction of preceding interview).\n*[http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/eveningnews24/norwich-whats-on-guide/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=GoingOutMusic&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=WhatsOn&itemid=NOED26%20Nov%202009%2016%3A03%3A06%3A953 Interview: Gilad Atzmon] by Rob Garratt, Evening News 24, 11 November 2009.\n*[https://archive.org/details/GiladAtzmonOnArabvoices.netJune2009 Gilad Atzmon interview on ArabVoices.net], [[KPFT]], June 2009 during visit to Houston, Texas.\n*Ivan Hewett, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandjazzmusic/3667959/Gilad-Altzmon-High-flown-ecstasies-from-an-angry-man.html Gilad Altzmon: High-flown ecstasies from an angry man], [[The Daily Telegraph]], 17 September 2007.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180103133806/http://middle-east-online.com/english/?id=21321 Gilad Atzmon Interviewed by Mary Rizzo], Middle East Online, July 2007.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.gilad.co.uk/ Gilad Atzmon website]\n\n{{The Blockheads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Atzmon, Gilad}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anti-Judaism]]\n[[Category:Anti-Zionism]]\n[[Category:Bebop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:The Blockheads members]]\n[[Category:British jazz saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Hard bop saxophonists]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Writers on Zionism]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWritings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gilad_Atzmon"}
{"title_page": "Kim Su-gil", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Kim Su-gil\n|office = Director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]]\n|term_start = May 2018\n|predecessor = [[Kim Jong-gak]]\n|leader = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1950}}\n|party = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n|allegiance = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|rank =   [[File:General of the Army rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Army general|General]]\n|branch = [[File:Flag of the Korean People's Army (1992\u20131993).svg|25px]] [[Korean People's Army]]\n}}\n\n'''Kim Su-gil''' ({{lang|ko|\uae40\uc218\uae38}}, born 1950)<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\uae40\uc218\uae38(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=23 March 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=127 |language=ko  }}</ref> is a [[North Korea]]n general and politician. He is the director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]] (KPA). He has served in this post since he replaced [[Kim Jong-gak]] in May 2018. Kim Su-gil is a full member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] and an alternate member of [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|its Politburo]]. He also has a seat in the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea]] and the [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea]].\n\n==Career==\nKim Su-gil is a career soldier.<ref name=\"kore_Resh\">{{Cite web | title = Reshuffle at top of Pyongyang\u2019s army politburo | author1 = Sarah Kim | author2 = Kim Eun-bin | work = Korea JoongAng Daily | date = 28 May 2018 | accessdate = 4 June 2018 | url = http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3048632&cloc=joongangdaily }}</ref> In his early career, he held posts in the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]] (KPA) and [[General Staff Department of the Korean People's Army|its General Staff Department]]. On 24 April 1992 he was promoted to the rank of ''[[sojang]]'' (Major General). On 15 April 2010 he was promoted to ''[[chungjang]]'' (Lieutenant General). In the fall of 2013 he was temporarily demoted to ''sojang'' again, like many other high-ranking KPA soldiers. He currently holds a rank of four-star general.<ref name=\"reut_Nort\"/>\n\nKim became a vice director of the [[Ministry of People's Armed Forces]] in 2006. He also served as the Vice Minister of People's Armed Forces since 2010. From this post, he was involved in the purge and execution of [[Jang Song-thaek]] in December 2013.<ref name=\"nkle_Gen.\"/>\n\nKim is a close aide of [[Kim Jong-un]] and often accompanies him in public functions.<ref name=\"reut_Nort\">{{Cite web | title = North Korea's three new military leaders are loyal to Kim, not policies | last = Shin | first = Hyonhee | last2 = Smith | first2 = Josh | agency = Reuters | date = 4 June 2018 | accessdate = 4 June 2018 | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa-military-leadership/north-koreas-three-new-military-leaders-are-loyal-to-kim-not-policies-idUSKCN1J01GT }}</ref> Kim has previously served as the Chairman of the Pyongyang City Committee of the Worker's Party from April 2014 to 2018 when he was replaced by [[Ri Man-gon]]. In this post, soon after  his appointment, he issued a public apology following a building collapse in the city. He was elected to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] (SPA) in [[2009 North Korean parliamentary election|2009 election]] and again in [[2014 North Korean parliamentary election|2014 election]]. Kim has served as a full member of the  [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] and an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea]] since May 2016. He is also on the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea]].<ref name=\"nkle_Gen.\">{{Cite web | title = Gen. Kim Su Gil | work = North Korea Leadership Watch | date = 31 May 2018 | accessdate = 5 May 2018 | url = http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/kim-su-gil/ }}</ref>\n\nKim served on the funeral committees of [[Jon Pyong-ho]] in 2014, [[Ri Ul-sol]] and [[Kim Yang-gon]] in 2015, and [[Kang Sok-ju]] in 2016.<ref name=\"nkle_Gen.\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, Kim was elected a member of the [[SPA Presidium]].<ref name=Leadership>{{Cite web |title=6th Session of the 13th SPA Held |work=North Korea Leadership Watch |date=14 April 2018 |access-date=16 October 2018 |url= http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/2018/04/14/6th-session-of-the-13th-spa-held/ }}</ref> Kim Su-gil replaced [[Kim Jong-gak]] in May 2018 as the director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]]. [[North Korean media]] announced the reshuffle in May 2018,<ref>{{Cite web | title = North Korea sacks top three military officials, as nuclear summit nears | last = Haas | first = Benjamin | work = the Guardian | date = 4 June 2018 | accessdate = 4 June 2018 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/04/north-koreas-top-three-military-officials-sacked-as-nuclear-summit-nears }}</ref> after Kim Jong-gak had served for merely four months. It is possible that the appointment took place on 17 May at a meeting of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea]] chaired by Kim Jong-un.<ref name=\"kore_Resh\"/>\n\nAt a personnel reshuffle at the First Session of the [[14th SPA]] Kim lost his seat in the presidium but was elevated to a member of the [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea]].<ref name=1stSession14thSPA>{{Cite web |title=In full: promotions and demotions at North Korea\u2019s 14th SPA |publisher=Korea Risk Group |work=NK PRO |date=12 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url= https://www.nknews.org/pro/in-full-promotions-and-demotions-at-north-koreas-14th-spa/ }}</ref> His son is Ri Jeong-hyeok, a captain in the KPA.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/kim-su-gil/ Biography] at [[North Korea Leadership Watch]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mun Kyong-dok]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretary of the [[Pyongyang]] City Committee of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Nung-o]]}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kim Jong-gak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army|KPA General Political Bureau]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Su-gil}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Kim Su-gil\n|office = Director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]]\n|term_start = May 2018\n|predecessor = [[Kim Jong-gak]]\n|leader = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1950}}\n|party = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n|allegiance = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|rank =   [[File:General of the Army rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Army general|General]]\n|branch = [[File:Flag of the Korean People's Army (1992\u20131993).svg|25px]] [[Korean People's Army]]\n}}\n\n'''Kim Su-gil''' ({{lang|ko|\uae40\uc218\uae38}}, born 1950)<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\uae40\uc218\uae38(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=23 March 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=127 |language=ko  }}</ref> is a [[North Korea]]n general and politician. He is the director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]] (KPA). He has served in this post since he replaced [[Kim Jong-gak]] in May 2018. Kim Su-gil is a full member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] and an alternate member of [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|its Politburo]]. He also has a seat in the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea]] and the [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea]].\n\n==Career==\nKim Su-gil is a career soldier.<ref name=\"kore_Resh\">{{Cite web | title = Reshuffle at top of Pyongyang\u2019s army politburo | author1 = Sarah Kim | author2 = Kim Eun-bin | work = Korea JoongAng Daily | date = 28 May 2018 | accessdate = 4 June 2018 | url = http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3048632&cloc=joongangdaily }}</ref> In his early career, he held posts in the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]] (KPA) and [[General Staff Department of the Korean People's Army|its General Staff Department]]. On 24 April 1992 he was promoted to the rank of ''[[sojang]]'' (Major General). On 15 April 2010 he was promoted to ''[[chungjang]]'' (Lieutenant General). In the fall of 2013 he was temporarily demoted to ''sojang'' again, like many other high-ranking KPA soldiers. He currently holds a rank of four-star general.<ref name=\"reut_Nort\"/>\n\nKim became a vice director of the [[Ministry of People's Armed Forces]] in 2006. He also served as the Vice Minister of People's Armed Forces since 2010. From this post, he was involved in the purge and execution of [[Jang Song-thaek]] in December 2013.<ref name=\"nkle_Gen.\"/>\n\nKim is a close aide of [[Kim Jong-un]] and often accompanies him in public functions.<ref name=\"reut_Nort\">{{Cite web | title = North Korea's three new military leaders are loyal to Kim, not policies | last = Shin | first = Hyonhee | last2 = Smith | first2 = Josh | agency = Reuters | date = 4 June 2018 | accessdate = 4 June 2018 | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa-military-leadership/north-koreas-three-new-military-leaders-are-loyal-to-kim-not-policies-idUSKCN1J01GT }}</ref> Kim has previously served as the Chairman of the Pyongyang City Committee of the Worker's Party since April 2014. In this post, soon after  his appointment, he issued a public apology following a building collapse in the city. He was elected to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]] (SPA) in 2009 and again in 2014. Kim has served as a full member of the  [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] and an alternate member of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea]] since May 2016. He is also on the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea]].<ref name=\"nkle_Gen.\">{{Cite web | title = Gen. Kim Su Gil | work = North Korea Leadership Watch | date = 31 May 2018 | accessdate = 5 May 2018 | url = http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/kim-su-gil/ }}</ref>\n\nKim served on the funeral committees of [[Jon Pyong-ho]] in 2014, [[Ri Ul-sol]] and [[Kim Yang-gon]] in 2015, and [[Kang Sok-ju]] in 2016.<ref name=\"nkle_Gen.\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, Kim was elected a member of the [[SPA Presidium]].<ref name=Leadership>{{Cite web |title=6th Session of the 13th SPA Held |work=North Korea Leadership Watch |date=14 April 2018 |access-date=16 October 2018 |url= http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/2018/04/14/6th-session-of-the-13th-spa-held/ }}</ref> Kim Su-gil replaced [[Kim Jong-gak]] in May 2018 as the director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army]]. [[North Korean media]] announced the reshuffle in May 2018,<ref>{{Cite web | title = North Korea sacks top three military officials, as nuclear summit nears | last = Haas | first = Benjamin | work = the Guardian | date = 4 June 2018 | accessdate = 4 June 2018 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/04/north-koreas-top-three-military-officials-sacked-as-nuclear-summit-nears }}</ref> after Kim Jong-gak had served for merely four months. It is possible that the appointment took place on 17 May at a meeting of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea]] chaired by Kim Jong-un.<ref name=\"kore_Resh\"/>\n\nAt a personnel reshuffle at the First Session of the [[14th SPA]] Kim lost his seat in the presidium but was elevated to a member of the [[State Affairs Commission of North Korea]].<ref name=1stSession14thSPA>{{Cite web |title=In full: promotions and demotions at North Korea\u2019s 14th SPA |publisher=Korea Risk Group |work=NK PRO |date=12 April 2019 |access-date=17 April 2019 |url= https://www.nknews.org/pro/in-full-promotions-and-demotions-at-north-koreas-14th-spa/ }}</ref> His son is Ri Jeong-hyeok, a captain in the KPA.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/kim-su-gil/ Biography] at [[North Korea Leadership Watch]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mun Kyong-dok]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretary of the [[Pyongyang]] City Committee of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Nung-o]]}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kim Jong-gak]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the [[General Political Bureau of the Korean People's Army|KPA General Political Bureau]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kim, Su-gil}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Su-gil"}
{"title_page": "\u014cme Kaid\u014d", "text_new": "{{nihongo|'''\u014cme Kaid\u014d'''|\u9752\u6885\u8857\u9053}} is one of the main roads leading westwards out of [[Tokyo]].  It begins in [[Shinjuku]], passes through [[\u014cme]], and ends in [[K\u014dfu]], [[Yamanashi]].<ref name=\"walk\">[http://kimama.life.coocan.jp/kimama2/oumekaidou.htm Enjoy Walking Highways - Ome Kaido] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200429100139/http://kimama.life.coocan.jp/kimama2/oumekaidou.htm |date=2020-04-29 }}. kimamanikaidouaruki. Accessed April 29, 2020.</ref>\n\n[[File:\u014cme Kaid\u014d highway in Asagaya, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n[[File:Starting point of \u014cme Kaid\u014d highway at the Shinjuku 3-Chome Intersection, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n[[File:Sidewalk map at the starting point of \u014cme Kaid\u014d highway at the Shinjuku 3-Chome Intersection, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n[[File:Historic post marker at the starting point of \u014cme Kaid\u014d highway at the Shinjuku 3-Chome Intersection, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n\n==Stations of the \u014cme Kaid\u014d==\nThere are 9 [[shukuba|post stations]] along the \u014cme Kaid\u014d. They are listed below with the corresponding modern-day municipality listed in [[Bracket#Parentheses|parentheses]].\n\n* Nakano-juku\uff08[[Nakano, Tokyo|Nakano]], [[Tokyo]]\uff09\n* Tanashi-juku\uff08[[Nishit\u014dky\u014d, Tokyo|Nishit\u014dky\u014d]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Ogawa-juku\uff08[[Kodaira, Tokyo|Kodaira]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Hakonegasaki-juku\uff08[[Mizuho,_Tokyo|Mizuho]], [[Nishitama District, Tokyo|Nishitama District]], Tokyo\uff09\n* \u014cme-juku\uff08[[\u014cme, Tokyo|\u014cme]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Hikawa-shuku\uff08[[Okutama, Tokyo|Okutama]], [[Nishitama District, Tokyo|Nishitama District]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Taba-shuku\uff08[[Tabayama]], [[Kitatsuru District, Yamanashi|Kitatsuru District]], [[Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi]]\uff09\n* Shioyama-juku\uff08[[K\u014dsh\u016b, Yamanashi|K\u014dsh\u016b]], Yamanashi)\n* Obara-juku\uff08[[Yamanashi, Yamanashi|Yamanashi]], Yamanashi)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edo Five Routes]]\n**[[T\u014dkaid\u014d (road)|T\u014dkaid\u014d]] (or [[53 Stations of the T\u014dkaid\u014d]])\n**[[Nakasend\u014d]] (or [[69 Stations of the Nakasend\u014d]])\n**[[\u014csh\u016b Kaid\u014d]]\n**[[Nikk\u014d Kaid\u014d]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|\u014cme Kaid\u014d}}\n*[https://gpscycling.net/tokaido/oume.html \u014cme Kaid\u014d Cycling]\n*[http://kimama.life.coocan.jp/kimama2/oumekaidou.htm Walking the \u014cme Kaid\u014d]\n*[http://home.e02.itscom.net/tabi/oume/oume.html \u014cme Kaid\u014d Log]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ome Kaido}}\n[[Category:Road transport in Japan]]\n[[Category:Edo period]]\n[[Category:Japan-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{nihongo|'''\u014cme Kaid\u014d'''|\u9752\u6885\u8857\u9053}} is one of the main roads leading westwards out of [[Tokyo]].  It begins in [[Shinjuku]], passes through [[\u014cme]], and ends in [[K\u014dfu]], [[Yamanashi]]<ref name=\"walk\">[http://kimama.life.coocan.jp/kimama2/oumekaidou.htm Enjoy Walking Highways - Ome Kaido] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200429100139/http://kimama.life.coocan.jp/kimama2/oumekaidou.htm |date=2020-04-29 }}. kimamanikaidouaruki. Accessed April 29, 2020.</ref>\n\n[[File:\u014cme Kaid\u014d highway in Asagaya, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n[[File:Starting point of \u014cme Kaid\u014d highway at the Shinjuku 3-Chome Intersection, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n[[File:Sidewalk map at the starting point of \u014cme Kaid\u014d highway at the Shinjuku 3-Chome Intersection, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n[[File:Historic post marker at the starting point of \u014cme Kaid\u014d highway at the Shinjuku 3-Chome Intersection, Tokyo.jpg|thumb|]]\n\n==Stations of the \u014cme Kaid\u014d==\nThere are 9 [[shukuba|post stations]] along the \u014cme Kaid\u014d. They are listed below with the corresponding modern-day municipality listed in [[Bracket#Parentheses|parentheses]].\n\n* Nakano-juku\uff08[[Nakano, Tokyo|Nakano]], [[Tokyo]]\uff09\n* Tanashi-juku\uff08[[Nishit\u014dky\u014d, Tokyo|Nishit\u014dky\u014d]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Ogawa-juku\uff08[[Kodaira, Tokyo|Kodaira]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Hakonegasaki-juku\uff08[[Mizuho,_Tokyo|Mizuho]], [[Nishitama District, Tokyo|Nishitama District]], Tokyo\uff09\n* \u014cme-juku\uff08[[\u014cme, Tokyo|\u014cme]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Hikawa-shuku\uff08[[Okutama, Tokyo|Okutama]], [[Nishitama District, Tokyo|Nishitama District]], Tokyo\uff09\n* Taba-shuku\uff08[[Tabayama]], [[Kitatsuru District, Yamanashi|Kitatsuru District]], [[Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi]]\uff09\n* Shioyama-juku\uff08[[K\u014dsh\u016b, Yamanashi|K\u014dsh\u016b]], Yamanashi)\n* Obara-juku\uff08[[Yamanashi, Yamanashi|Yamanashi]], Yamanashi)\n\n==See also==\n*[[Edo Five Routes]]\n**[[T\u014dkaid\u014d (road)|T\u014dkaid\u014d]] (or [[53 Stations of the T\u014dkaid\u014d]])\n**[[Nakasend\u014d]] (or [[69 Stations of the Nakasend\u014d]])\n**[[\u014csh\u016b Kaid\u014d]]\n**[[Nikk\u014d Kaid\u014d]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|\u014cme Kaid\u014d}}\n*[https://gpscycling.net/tokaido/oume.html \u014cme Kaid\u014d Cycling]\n*[http://kimama.life.coocan.jp/kimama2/oumekaidou.htm Walking the \u014cme Kaid\u014d]\n*[http://home.e02.itscom.net/tabi/oume/oume.html \u014cme Kaid\u014d Log]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ome Kaido}}\n[[Category:Road transport in Japan]]\n[[Category:Edo period]]\n[[Category:Japan-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Bradwarden", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%8Cme_Kaid%C5%8D"}
{"title_page": "List of Dutch patrician families", "text_new": "'''List of Dutch patrician families''' in the official ''[[Nederland's <!-- so spelt --> Patriciaat]]''.<ref>[http://www.cbg.nl/download/cbg_patriciaat_lijst.pdf List of families in the Nederland's Patriciaat 1910-2012]</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20160317170049/http://www.cbg.nl/download/cbg_patriciaat_lijst.pdf</ref><ref>https://verloren.nl/_file/145262/NP95_LIJST_VAN_DE_GESLACHTEN.pdf</ref>\n\nBranches of the same family are separated by a slash (/).\n\n{{compact ToC|side=yes|top=yes|num=yes}}\n\n==A==\nVan der Aa \u2022 Aalbersberg / Aalbertsberg \u2022 Abbing / Roscam Abbing \u2022 Abeleven \u2022 [[Aberson]] / Colson Aberson / van der Hardt Aberson / Wigeri Aberson \u2022 d'Abo \u2022 [[Acket]] \u2022 Acquoy \u2022 Hora Adema \u2022 Adriani / van der Tuuk Adriani \u2022 Advocaat \u2022 d'Ailly \u2022 Van Akerlaken \u2022 Albarda \u2022 [[Alberdingk|Alberdingk / Alberdingk Thijm]] \u2022 [[Van Alderwerelt|van Alderwerelt / van Alderwerelt van Rosenburgh / de Roo van Alderwerelt]] \u2022 (Van) Alkemade / van Rijn van Alkemade \u2022 Van Alphen (Etten) / Pascal van Alphen \u2022 van Alphen (Keulen) \u2022 van Alphen (Rotterdam) \u2022 Alpherts \u2022 van Regteren Altena \u2022 Altes / Korthals Altes / Meursing Korthals Altes  \u2022 Ament \u2022 Ameshoff \u2022 Ancher / Brouwer Ancher \u2022 van Andel \u2022 Andrau \u2022 [[:nl:Andr\u00e9 de la Porte]] \u2022 Andreae (F\u00fcrstenwalde) \u2022 Andreae (Hitzum) /  Beucker Andreae / van Bothnia Andreae / Fockema Andreae / Nauta Andreae \u2022 [[Ankersmit|Ankersmit / Kok Ankersmit]] \u2022 Van Appeltere \u2022 d'Aquin \u2022 van Arkel \u2022 Arntz / Ratering Arntz \u2022 Arntzenius \u2022 Arri\u00ebns / Lincklaen Arri\u00ebns \u2022 Asser / Nijhoff Asser \u2022 d'Aumerie\n\n==B==\nBaart de la Faille \u2022 De la Faille \u2022 Baartz \u2022 Bachiene \u2022 Backer \u2022 Backer van Leuven \u2022 Huyghens Backer \u2022 Badon Ghyben \u2022 Baelde 